<FIRST>u p AM-MississippiCongressional     10-03 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mississippi Congressional,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Republican, Democrat Advance to Congressional Runoff</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Election Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Democratic state senator and a
Republican political aide forced each other into a congressional
runoff Tuesday, capturing the top two spots in a special election
to fill the seat of the late Rep. Larkin Smith.
   Democrat Gene Taylor and Republican Tom Anderson easily took the
top two spots in the three-way race, leaving a stunned state
Attorney General Mike Moore trailing by more than 15,000 votes.
   The special election was scheduled after Smith died in a plane
crash Aug. 13. Taylor and Anderson will face each other in an Oct.
17 runoff.
   Democrats have been hoping to strip the GOP of a seat it has
held for more than 16 years.
   Unofficials returns showed Taylor with 51,383 votes, or 42
percent, Anderson with 45,623, or 37 percent, and Moore with
24,497, or 21 percent.
   Taylor, 36, who ran unsuccessfully for the same seat in 1988,
surprised the better-known Moore, who finished third in the home
county where he was district attorney for 12 years.
   ``We felt all along that we charted a course down the middle
that if there was a runoff we would be favored by each side,''
Taylor said. ``There were a lot more people who voted Democratic
than Republican.''
   Moore, 37, who was criticized for wanting to leave the attorney
general's office after only 21 months in office, said he would
support Taylor in the runoff.
   Anderson, 45, a longtime aide to U.S. Sen. Trent Lott, said his
campaign had ``come from nowhere to be here tonight.'' He promised
his supporters ``two weeks of excitment.''
</TEXT>
