<HEAD>With AM-Election Rdp</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with final figures in Mississippi,
Jackson winning in Atlanta. Pick up 6th graf, `Cleveland: City ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A brief look at Tuesday's elections around the nation:
   U.S. HOUSE=
   _ Mississippi: Democratic State Sen. Gene Taylor and Republican
Tom Anderson, a longtime aide to U.S. Sen. Trent Lott, advanced to
an Oct. 17 runoff in a race to succeed the late Rep. Larkin Smith.
Taylor had 42 percent of the vote to 37 percent for Anderson and 21
percent for state Attorney General Mike Moore.
   MAYORS=
   _ Atlanta: Former Mayor Maynard Jackson, who served from 1974 to
1982, reclaimed the mayor's office by defeating City Councilman
Hosea Williams and four longshot candidates by a 5-to-1 margin.
   _ Cleveland: City Council President George Forbes and state Sen.
Mike White won the top two spots in a non-partisan mayoral primary
and advanced to a Nov. 7 runoff. Forbes captured 37 percent to
White's 25 percent; the remainder was split by three other
candidates.
   _ Phoenix: Mayor Terry Goddard was favored to win a fourth term
in his race against state Republican Party Chairman Burton Kruglick
and real estate broker Norris Inman. Voters also were considering a
proposal to build a downtown baseball stadium.
   _ Albuquerque, N.M.: Mayor Ken Schultz was trying to become the
first mayor to be elected to back-to-back terms since the city
switched to a mayor-council form of government 15 years ago. He had
seven challengers.
   OTHER=
   _ Escondido, Calif.: A state Assembly runoff featured a write-in
campaign by an anti-abortion Republican, Dick Lyles, who opposed
the pro-choice positions of the regular party nominees, Republican
Tricia Hunter and Democrat Jeannine Correia.
</TEXT>
