<FIRST>r a PM-EugeneFodor     10-03 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eugene Fodor,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Violinist Enters Guilty Plea, Placed On Probation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDGARTOWN, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Violinist Eugene Fodor said he hopes to
rebuild his life and career now that he's been placed on probation
for pleading guilty to a drug-related break-in.
   ``I regard this event as a major turning point in my life,''
Fodor said Monday after a Dukes County court hearing.
   ``Of course I'm relieved that this ordeal is over,'' he said.
``The experience has been a frightening and profound one. What I
want to do now is get back to my music and my life.''
   Fodor, 39, of New York City, pleaded guilty to breaking into a
Martha's Vineyard motel room, where he was found July 27.
   A search of the room found a bottle containing more than 20
grams of cocaine, a hypodermic needle with a small amount of heroin
and a dagger, authorities said.
   A county grand jury met Monday morning and returned indictments
of breaking and entering, possession of heroin and cocaine and
possession of drug paraphernalia.
   After lawyers on both sides conferred, Fodor pleaded guilty to
the break-in charge, which carried a maximum penalty of six months
in jail.
   Judge Raymond Cross, however, placed Fodor on three years'
probation, in which he must continue a drug treatment program and
will be subject to random testing.
   Fodor pleaded innocent to the other charges, and they were
placed on file, pending completion of probation.
   ``This shouldn't have been treated as a serious criminal matter
and it wasn't,'' defense attorney Michael Altman said. ``Eugene
Fodor has been to a treatment center and has turned his life
around.''
   Born in Denver, Fodor began playing violin at age 8. He has
performed at the White House and in Moscow, where in 1974 he became
the first American medalist at the Tchaikovsky Violin Competition.
   After Fodor's arrest, family members and colleagues said his
drug use had begun recently, and followed the trouble he had
building on his early celebrity.
   ``This was a very important experience actually in his life,''
Altman said. ``He was feeling down in the dumps and he turned
toward drugs.''
   Altman said Fodor has undergone seven weeks of treatment, and
couselors say his progress has been good and they are confident he
can remain drug free.
</TEXT>
