<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-89 0018EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-ElectionRdp     10-03 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Election Rdp,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jackson Runs in Atlanta; Other Races in Mississippi, Cleveland, Phoenix</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Atlanta Mayor Maynard Jackson was a strong favorite to
reclaim his old job today, while Mississippi Republicans tried to
retain a congressional seat that was left vacant when Rep. Larkin
Smith died in a plane crash.
   In Cleveland, five candidates battled in a primary election to
succeed Mayor George Voinovich, who is quitting after a decade in
office. Incumbent mayors were running in Phoenix and Albuquerque,
N.M.
   Jackson, Atlanta's first black mayor, said he was poised for a
``huge victory'' in his bid to reclaim the seat he held from
1974-82. Few observers expected him to be disappointed.
   Jackson would succeed Andrew Young, who followed him in office
and who now is exploring a bid for governor. Young, like Jackson
before him, is prohibited from seeking a third consecutive term.
   The most prominent among Jackson's five opponents was former
City Councilman Hosea Williams, who entered the race late after
Fulton County Commission Chairman Michael Lomax dropped out.
   Further south, two Democrats and a Republican were running in
the Mississippi special election to fill the seat left vacant by
Smith's death in August. The freshman Republican had served less
than eight months.
   State Attorney General Mike Moore, one of two Democrats running,
is the best known of the three candidates and was considered by
many to be the front-runner. The others are Republican Tom
Anderson, who has been an aide to Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss., and
state Sen. Gene Taylor.
   If no candidate wins a majority, a runoff will be held Oct. 17.
   The winner will represent an 11{-county district in southeastern
Mississippi that has been in Republican hands since 1972 and is the
only GOP seat in the state's five-member House delegation.
   So far, Democrats have won four of six special elections to fill
U.S. House seats this year.
   In Cleveland, Voinovich's departure to run for governor led to a
free-for-all among five officeholders.
   Voinovich has endorsed the lone Republican in the race, Ralph J.
Perk Jr., the school board president and son of a former mayor.
   The other candidates, all Democrats, are Court Clerk Benny
Bonanno, City Council President George Forbes, Cuyahoga County
Commissioner Tim Hagan and state Sen. Michael White.
   The two top vote-getters will advance to the Nov. 7 general
election.
   In Phoenix, three-term incumbent Terry Goddard was the favorite
in a three-way non-partisan race, but the mayoral election was
somewhat overshadowed by a ballot issue on construction of a
downtown baseball stadium.
   Although Goddard favored the stadium, polls showed him far in
front of two challengers, state Republican Party chairman Burton
Kruglick and real estate broker Norris Inman, while the stadium
measure was trailing.
   In Albuquerque, Democrat Ken Schultz faced eight challengers in
his attempt to become the first mayor to be elected to back-to-back
terms since the city changed to a mayor-council form of government
15 years ago.
</TEXT>
