<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     10-03 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAU CLAIRE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thank God for Tuesday garbage pickups.
   They saved Carol Tiedemann $5.2 million.
   Mrs. Tiedemann had never purchased a lottery ticket before last
week, and last weekend she discarded her first ticket stub,
thinking she'd lost.
   But watching a television report Monday, Mrs. Tidemann
recognized the winning numbers and fished her ticket from the
bottom of the garbage can. Fortunately, pickup was scheduled for
today, she said.
   ``Never in a million years did we expect to win,'' said Mrs.
Tiedemann, 22.
   Mrs. Tiedemann, who works in a shoe factory, and her husband,
Dan, told reporters they had no immediate plans on spending the
money.
   ``I haven't the slightest idea. We'll put it into the bank and
sit on it,'' said Tiedemann, 26, a machinist.
   The couple married in April and recently bought a house.
   Mrs. Tiedemann said she bought the Lotto America ticket at a
convenience store last week, playing the numbers 8 and 18 because
they were the month and date of her birthday. The four other
numbers _ 26, 30, 42, and 46 _ were selected at random, she said.
   Bill Clausius, a lottery spokesman, said the couple will receive
20 annual installments of $192,175 after taxes.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HIGH POINT, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The thing that went bump in the night at
Roy Carroll's house turned out to be a 7-foot boa constrictor.
   ``I don't want to wake up like that again,'' Carroll said. ``I'm
still scared. It was something to see.''
   The snake apparently was resting on a piece of plywood in the
rafters of Carroll's basement. As it crawled away, the plywood fell
and hit the basement floor.
   Carroll went down to investigate about 6:30 a.m. Monday and
found himself face to face with the snake.
   ``My first thought was to kill it, but I said, `no, I couldn't
do that,' 'cause if I had swung (a shovel) and missed, no telling
where it might have gone.''
   Carroll's wife, Peggy, called police, but when Officer Sherry
Lingerfelt arrived, she didn't feel real comfortable about handling
the creature.
   So Ms. Lingerfelt called her sergeant, Larry Stroud. The snake
didn't scare Stroud.
   Stroud got hold of the snake's head and he and Ms. Lingerfelt
put it into two large plastic garbage bags and brought it to the
police station.
   Police said they would auction the the snake if its owner
doesn't show up.
</TEXT>
