<FIRST>r a PM-SovietHumorists     10-03 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet Humorists,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets: Take Our Humor _ Please</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AB1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By YVETTE H. BLACKMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SCHENECTADY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What does a Soviet husband buy his
mother-in-law for her birthday? Radioactive apples from Chernobyl.
   Stroke patients at Sunnyview Hospital got a taste of that
not-quite-ready-for-prime-time Soviet humor Monday as a group of
humorists from the Soviet Union delivered one-liners and anecdotes.
   ``People are people everywhere _ except maybe politicians are
different,'' Andrey Benyukh, deputy foreign editor of the Moscow
humor magazine Krokodil, told the patients.
   Five Soviet satirists, cartoonists and editors of monthly humor
magazines published in the Ukraine, Estonia and Moscow are on a
two-week visit to the United States. The program was arranged
through a cultural exchange sponsored by the International
Association of Professional Bureaucrats, an organization of 1,700
humorists.
   The Soviets were at the Schenectady hospital to see its humor
program that's designed to help patients deal with their ailments.
   The group began its tour Thursday in Washington, D.C., and
arrived in Saratoga Springs on Saturday for a four-day visit to the
Albany area.
   With quips and anecdotes, these observers of America cracked up
patients and reporters during an impromptu news conference on the
contents of their recently published book, ``Soviet Humor: The Best
of Krokodil.''
   The collection of cartoons, with English translations, resulted
from a visit to the United States by a group of Soviets in 1987,
said James Boren, president of the organization.
   The compilation by 82 cartoonists offers sketches that are
political, satirical and, supposedly, funny to all cultures.
   Take, for instance, the one showing a husband and wife in their
living room with the silhouette of a man in the background. The cut
line: ``Relax dear, it's not the police. It's just burglars.''
   Then of course there was the Soviet variation of the American
``Mother-in-law-in-Trunk'' jokes.
   A lady is pictured selling two baskets of apples. Crimean apples
were trading slowly at a cheap 35 kopecks apiece. But overpriced
Chernobyl apples were selling like hotcakes at 5 rubles each.
   ``People are buying them for their mothers-in-law, their
bosses,'' the caption says.
   The openness under Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev has allowed
Soviet people to ``take up subjects which, until recently, we could
only discuss with our friends in our kitchens ... privately,'' said
Leonid Florentiev, foreign editor of Krokodil.
   He urged Gorbachev to continue to extend those freedoms.
   ``If you stop at this stage, it can easily be turned the other
way around. You have to go ahead to achieve some positive
results,'' Florentiev said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
