<FIRST>r w PM-Quayle     10-03 0672</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quayle,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle: US Not Backing off Star Wars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle says Soviet
officials are ``misreading the tea leaves'' if they think the Bush
administration is lessening its commitment to the Strategic Defense
Initiative.
   ``They better go back and read what we said and what the SDI
program is all about now,'' Quayle said Monday.
   The vice president created a stir last month when he said the
Reagan administration had indulged in ``political jargon'' when it
originally portrayed the SDI program _ also known as Star Wars _ as
a leak-proof, impenetrable anti-missile shield.
   The Soviets, in their latest strategic arms initiative,
conditionally dropped their insistence that Americans abandon plans
to deploy a space-based anti-missile system. But they reserved the
right to abrogate a strategic arms agreement on short notice if the
United States ever actually deployed such a system.
   Quayle, in an interview with The Associated Press and other news
organizations, said the concept of SDI had been scaled back in the
last 12 months of the Reagan administration.
   ``What we're talking about is a realistic SDI system,'' said
Quayle. ``If (the Soviets) view a phased deployment and a
redefinition of SDI as lessening of the commitment, they're
misreading the tea leaves.
   ``It's showing you can do it from a political point of view,
from a technological point of view and that President Bush is
serious about an SDI system,'' said Quayle, a stalwart SDI
supporter.
   Quayle, who returned Friday from a four-nation tour of Asia,
said the Bush administration may ask Congress to loosen
restrictions on foreign aid to allow the Philippines to beef up
internal security against communist insurgents.
   Quayle was instrumental in securing a similar waiver for El
Salvador after a visit to that strife-torn nation earlier this year.
   Quayle said a waiver of the restriction would ``help protect
American lives as we have become increasing targets'' in the
Philippines. Two Americans working at a U.S. military base were
ambushed and killed by Filipino terrorists shortly before Quayle's
arrival last Tuesday.
   The Philippines will receive almost $650 million in U.S. aid
next year. Quayle did not say how much he felt should be shifted to
internal security, but aides said the country needs basic equipment
including two-way radios for police cars in Manila.
   Philippines President Corazon Aquino agreed during Quayle's
visit to open negotiations in December on the lease agreements for
Clark Air Base, Subic Bay naval station and four other U.S.
military facilities. Those agreements expire in September 1991.
   Quayle said the United States hopes for a long-term, indefinite
extension of the leases. Setting a date for closing the bases would
send the wrong signal to investors looking for signs of stability
in the Philippines, he said.
   ``There is a very vocal anti-American community in the
Philippines,'' Quayle said. ``I don't put everyone that's
anti-American in the terrorist camp. ... It's a combination of
anti-Americanism plus pro-Philippine and self-respect and
self-dignity.''
   But just ``traveling the streets of Manila'' and seeing its
poverty underscores the need for economic development, he said.
   ``I think we are a stabilizing force in the Philippines, and
stability is what investors and people look to,'' said Quayle, who
also visited Japan, South Korea and Malaysia on his fourth foreign
trip of the year.
   On other issues, Quayle:
   _Shrugged off a question about his low standing in public
opinion polls. ``I'm gratified for the president's good standing in
polls. That's my concern right now. I got plenty of time to worry
about my own,'' said the 44-year-old vice president.
   _Declared the United States' main goal in Cambodia is to bolster
the non-communist resistance and prevent the ``mass murderers'' of
the Khmer Rouge from regaining power.
   _Said the government of China must change its attitude about the
massacre of pro-democracy demonstrators in Tiananmen Square last
June. ``The problem is China continues to perceive that nothing
happened, or whatever happened is nobody's business, and therefore
it's for us to change, not them,'' Quayle said.
</TEXT>
