<FIRST>r w PM-Navy-Iowa     10-03 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Navy-Iowa,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Admiral Flies to Mediterranean for Hearing for Iowa Officers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The commander of the Atlantic Fleet's Naval
Surface Force is conducting a disciplinary inquiry aboard the USS
Iowa, the battleship on which 47 sailors were killed in an April
explosion, Pentagon sources say.
   Vice Adm. Joseph S. Donnell III is conducting the non-judicial
inquiry to determine whether the captain and several other officers
should be punished, the sources told The Associated Press Monday.
   The Navy said after a lengthy study that gunner's mate Clayton
Hartwig ``most likely'' caused the explosion in the battleship's
No. 2 gun turret by inserting a detonator between two powder bags
   But the investigation led by Rear Adm. Richard Milligan also
alleged numerous lax procedures aboard the ship, including
unauthorized experimentation with extra-strength gunpowder and
projectile loads.
   Milligan said the officers had failed to qualify enough sailors
for their specific duties in the gun turret and that many safety
procedures had been circumvented.
   He recommended that Capt. Fred Moosally and four other
high-ranking men be relieved and disciplined. However, his
superiors decided the men should receive non-judicial punishment
through the mast procedure.
   Donnell, who was one of the endorsing officers of the final Iowa
report, countered Milligan's recommendation that the five men be
removed, arguing that the infractions amounted to ``a failure of
leadership'' on the captain's part but were ``a marked departure
from otherwise outstanding performance.''
   Donnell is expected to conduct his inquiries separately for each
of the men, and the procedures are expected to last several days, a
Pentagon source said. The USS Iowa is in the Mediterranean.
   Besides Moosally, the men include the ship's executive officer,
the weapons officer and a master chief petty officer who was found
to have experimented with the gun firings.
   The gunnery officer requested and received a transfer. A
separate procedure is expected to be conducted for him later, the
source said.
</TEXT>
