<FIRST>r w PM-US-Cambodia     10-03 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Cambodia,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Defends Indochina Policy Against Congressional Criticism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration says it hopes the
Soviet Union will help restart the stalled peace process in
Cambodia and ease the threat of revived civil war there.
   David F. Lambertson, deputy assistant secretary of state for
East Asian and Pacific affairs, spoke of a ``more constructive
Soviet role'' in Indochina after recent ``useful discussions about
Cambodia'' with Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze.
   Testifying before a Senate Foreign Relations subcommittee
Monday, Lambertson defended the U.S. policy of seeking a settlement
in Cambodia by backing Prince Norodom Sihanouk and continued
political and diplomatic isolation of Vietnam.
   He said the United States wants Moscow to press its allies,
Vietnam and the Vietnam-backed Cambodian government, to compromise
with Sihanouk and reverse the trend ``toward a military option'' in
Cambodia.
   Lambertson blamed the breakdown of the Paris peace conference on
Cambodia in August on what he called ``Vietnamese intransigence.''
   ``We plan to steadfastly maintain our support for the diplomatic
and economic isolation of Vietnam,'' he said.
   But East Asian and Pacific affairs subcommittee Chairman Alan
Cranston, D-Calif., accused the administration of pursuing a
``morally bankrupt'' policy of backing Sihanouk's demand to include
in an interim Cambodian government the communist Khmer Rouge,
blamed for the loss of more than a million Cambodian lives when
they ruled from 1975-78.
   Monday's hearing was part of a search for new policy approaches,
Cranston said.
   Khmer Rouge rule, dubbed Cambodia's era of ``the killing
fields,'' was followed by an 11-year Vietnamese occupation of
Cambodia that ended last month.
   Dith Pran, the Cambodian-born New York Times photographer whose
escape from his homeland was portrayed in the movie ``The Killing
Fields,'' testified that collapse of the Paris conference means
``Cambodians are being forced by their leaders to go to the killing
fields again.''
   Sihanouk, the other non-communist Cambodians and the Association
of Southeast Asian Nations all ``maintain that leaving the Khmer
Rouge completely out of the interim regime ... is certain to result
in a bloody civil war,'' Lambertson said.
   But Dith Pran said including the Khmer Rouge in Cambodia's
future government would be like allowing high-ranking Nazis in a
post-World War II German government.
</TEXT>
