<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     10-03 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Boosts Disabled Veterans' Benefits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bill approved by the House would give about
2.5 million disabled veterans and their survivors a 4.9 percent
cost-of-living increase in benefits.
   The increase, approved by the House on Monday and effective Dec.
1, would raise from $1,468 to $1,539 a month the basic benefit
payment for a veteran with 100 percent disability. Maximum monthly
benefits would increase from $2,559 to $2,684.
   The increases will raise the annual cost of veterans' disability
and survivor benefits _ now estimated at $10.2 billion _ by $398
million in fiscal 1990, which began Sunday, and by $525 million in
fiscal 1991, according to the Congressional Budget Office.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Legislative Battle Builds Over Development in the Desert</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers, miners, developers and
environmentalists are clashing over legislation that would
designate about 9.5 million acres of California land as wilderness
and national parks.
   ``We need to draw clear lines that development can work around
while saving some lands as parks and wildernesses,'' sponsor Sen.
Alan Cranston, D-Calif., told a crowded hearing Monday conducted by
the Senate Energy and Resources subcommittee on public lands,
national parks and forests.
   Congress in 1976 enacted the Federal Land Policy and Management
Act, which established the California Desert Conservation Area. The
Bureau of Land Management developed a management plan for the
California desert to balance the demands of environmentalists,
hunters, miners, ranchers, energy developers, tourists and the
military.
   However, Cranston said the BLM has ``failed to protect important
desert resources.''
   Citing a report by the General Accounting Office, Cranston said
the investigative arm of Congress found that the bureau ``has
frequently allowed the needs of competing interests, such as
recreation and commercial use, to take precedence over wildlife
interests when conflicts have arisen.''
   The bureau disputed that charge.
   ``GAO's report presents only a partial picture of BLM's wildlife
activities in the California desert,'' said Cy Jamison, director of
the bureau.
   Robert A. Sanregret, a representative of the Western Mining
Council Inc., said the legislation ``would destroy thousands of
private businesses and would, literally, make thousands of citizens
homeless.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev may face
a revolt among rank-and-file Communist Party members, but his
reforms are likely to survive, according to a senior CIA analyst.
   ``Even if there is a temporary setback, I think the process of
reform will continue,'' Marc Zlotnik of the CIA's Office of Soviet
Analysis said Monday in a lecture at the Kennan Institute for
Advanced Russian Studies.
   His remarks reflected a general sense of uncertainty among
experts over the course of Soviet politics in the short term after
four years of often tumultuous reform since Gorbachev came to power.
   Asked to comment on Gorbachev's own description of a deepening
economic and political crisis and reference to rumors of a
conservative coup in Moscow, Zlotnik said: ``Some spark could set
things off ... to topple the senior leadership. But no one is in a
position to predict when it will come and whether it can be put out
quickly.''
   ``The crisis is really serious,'' Zlotnik said. ``But so far, I
think it is being managed pretty well.''
</TEXT>
