<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-89 0305EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     10-03 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Stocks Slip</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with Nikkei, dollar closings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed higher against the Japanese yen
in Tokyo Tuesday despite intervention by Japan's central bank,
while stock prices slipped.
   The dollar opened at 139.72 yen, up 0.42 yen from Monday's close
of 139.30 yen, and closed at 140.65 yen, up 1.35 yen. It traded in
a range of 139.70 to 140.68 yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-share Nikkei Stock Average
lost 256.60 points, or 0.72 percent, to close at 35,366.37 points.
   Currency traders said the Bank of Japan intervened several
times, selling dollars for yen at about the 140-yen level.
   ``The dollar was moving slightly upward as market players
corrected their dollar-holding positions,'' said a trader with the
Bank of Tokyo, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   He said participants were buying back dollars they had sold
earlier, following talks last week among monetary officials from
seven key currency nations, known as the Group of Seven. The
officials agreed to strengthen coordinated monetary intervention to
push the dollar lower.
   Tokyo investors were focusing on selling West German marks and
buying the yen, thus helping the dollar to strengthen against other
major currencies, the Bank of Tokyo trader said.
   But he said the Bank of Japan was likely to prevent a further
rise in the dollar.
   The amount of the Bank of Japan's purchases was not immediately
known. The central bank does not normally comment officially on its
market intervention.
   On the stock exchange, traders said many participants stayed on
the sidelines watching the currency market.
   Dealers said the weakening yen discouraged Japanese investors,
and the Nikkei index fell as they sold to take profits.
   An analyst for Yamaichi Securities, who spoke on condition of
anonmyity, said institutional investors also held back because of a
lack of trading focus.
</TEXT>
