<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-89 0417EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CleanAir-Reax     10-03 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Clean Air-Reax,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Automakers Criticize to Plan for Strict Exhaust Controls </HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Clean Air, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRETEL WIKLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Automakers criticized a congressional proposal to
extend California's tough auto exhaust standards to the entire
country as needlessly expensive and of doubtful value.
   The California rules ``were adopted for a unique part of the
country with a unique problem,'' said William Noack, director of
General Motors Corp.'s media relations office in Washington. ``Why
bring standards for that part of the country nationwide when the
need for them is not there?''
   The proposal emerged Monday from a subcommittee of the House
Energy and Commerce Committee on a 22-0 vote. It virtually assures
some form of tough new tailpipe emission controls, because the
Senate's clean air legislation is even stricter.
   Under the House plan, passed as a proposed amendment to a clean
air bill put forth by President Bush, California-style controls
would be phased in beginning with 1994 models and be in effect in
all states by 1996.
   Noack said the subcommittee plan wouldn't make the air any
cleaner than the administration plan, but will cost the consumer
more.
   The Environmental Protection Agency has estimated the additional
emission controls would add $100 to the cost of each car.
   Ford Motor Co. Vice Chairman Harold Poling said his company
supported Bush's proposal, despite some reservations.
   ``However, this action goes well beyond that proposal,'' Poling
said of the subcommittee plan. Though the provisions would make
auto standards far more stringent, they would improve air quality a
mere 1 percent compared with Bush's proposal, he said.
   Poling also said there are serious safety questions about vapor
recovery systems that would be mandated under the provisions.
   Chrysler Corp. spokesman Tom Houston also criticized
subcommittee proposal. ``First, the proposed standards stretch the
limits of technological feasibility, and we presently lack
assurance that these standards can be met at the levels of
reliability and quality the American public demands,'' Houston said.
   Andy Bucksbaum, executive director of the Public Interest
Research Group in Michigan, praised the proposal.
   ``We're very encouraged by this compromise,'' Bucksbaum said.
``It's an excellent first step particularly in area of controlling
smaller pollutants.''
</TEXT>
