<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     10-03 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Stocks Down In Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar, after a six-day decline, rose sharply
against the Japanese yen in Tokyo today despite intervention by
Japan's central bank, while stock prices fell.
   The dollar closed at 140.65 yen, up 1.35 yen from Monday's close
of 139.30 yen. It opened at 139.72 yen and ranged between 139.70
and 140.68 yen.
   The dollar had fallen 5.70 yen in six trading days before
today's rebound.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-share Nikkei Stock Average
lost 256.60 points, or 0.72 percent, closing at 35,366.37 points.
   Currency traders said the Bank of Japan intervened several times
in the morning, selling dollars at about the 140-yen level, but did
not act in the afternoon, and the dollar rose quickly in the last
half-hour of trading.
   It was not immediately known how much the central bank sold. The
bank normally does not comment on its exchange market activities.
   ``There was no real reason to buy dollars, but the market still
seemed to be short of the currency. It looks like the market will
continue to support the dollar,'' said Minori Takeuchi, a trader at
Chemical Bank.
   Many players were sitting on the sidelines, awaiting the results
of a meeting of West Germany's central bank on Thursday, she said.
   There have been rumors that the bank will raise interest rates.
   Tokyo investors were focusing on selling West German marks and
buying yen, thus helping the dollar to strengthen against other
major currencies, said a Bank of Tokyo trader on condition of
anonymity.
   On the stock exchange, ``The rebound of the dollar didn't do
much to help the sentiment of the market,'' said a dealer at
Kleinwort Benson Securities, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
He said many investors were sitting on the sidelines watching the
currency markets.
   ``Many people seemed content to lock in the short-term gains of
the past few days,'' he said, referring to sales for profit-taking.
   Stocks that were strong last week, including securities,
insurance, railway and retailer sales issues, fell back.
   Shares in some smaller companies and warehousing firms rose
strongly.
   ``It wasn't all doom and gloom. It was mostly the big stocks
that were being hit'' in the market's decline, the trader said.
</TEXT>
