<FIRST>r a PM-HeroinOverdoses     10-03 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Heroin Overdoses,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Tar Heroin Leads to Overdoses, Deaths</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN MACLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rash of overdoses and deaths attributed
to particularly potent chips of ``black tar'' heroin has addicts
and occasional users alike terrified and frantically seeking
treatment, officials said.
   From Friday through Monday, three people died and dozens of
others were treated after they literally were knocked off their
feet and rendered unconscious after injecting themselves with the
most-popular form of heroin in the drug world.
   ``It's the talk of the neighborhood,'' said Eddie Franks,
director of the Facts on Crack program at Glide Memorial Church in
the Tenderloin district, where most of the overdoses occurred.
   ``What we're here for now is prevention and support while this
epidemic is going on,'' Franks said, adding that a 24-hour crisis
telephone line has been set up and will operate as long as
necessary.
   Police Inspector Sam Osborne said a dealer probably forgot to
mix the heroin with other materials to dilute its strength, which
normally is 6 percent to 9 percent pure.
   Tests showed the heroin had a 36 percent to 38 percent purity,
said Lt. Jim Mollinari. Since overdose cases fell off sharply, he
said, ``My guess is there's probably not much more out there.''
   Black tar, named for its color and gooey appearance, has become
the most commonly used heroin by San Francisco's estimated 15,000
to 18,000 addicts since coming on the scene about seven years ago,
said Dr. Alex Stalcup, medical director of the Haight-Ashbury Free
Clinic.
   It sells for about $20 a bag that can be broken into several
shots.
   The clinic generally treats about 120 people daily and turns
away about 10 or 15. Within a couple of hours Monday, it had turned
away almost 40, he said.
   ``The people who buy street heroin are literally playing with
their lives,'' he said.
   The fatalities were said to be men ages 35, 41 and 43. The San
Francisco Coroner's Office did not release names.
   Last week, federal Drug Enforcement Administration agents seized
2 kilos of black tar heroin at hotels near San Francisco
International Airport.
</TEXT>
