<FIRST>r a PM-Scotus-BristolBay     10-03 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Bristol Bay,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Efforts to Prevent Oil Drilling in Alaska's Bristol Bay Shift to
Congress</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Scotus Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alaska's efforts to prevent oil and gas
exploration in the rich fishing grounds of Bristol Bay focused on
Congress as the U.S. Supreme Court declined to hear the state's
latest appeal.
   The court Monday left intact rulings that allowed the federal
government to sell $94 million worth of exploratory leases last
year on 5.6 million acres of the bay off southwest Alaska.
   ``It means, as we suspected, that the battle has shifted to
Congress, which is moving in the direction of protecting Bristol
Bay from development,'' said Randall Weiner, executive director of
the environmental group Trustees for Alaska.
   State Attorney General Douglas Baily said he was not surprised
by the court's action: ``We've been focusing on Congress, in part,
because we didn't want to trust all of our eggs in the basket of
the Supreme Court.''
   State officials, environmental groups and fishing organizations
have said the relatively small chance of finding large amounts of
oil under Bristol Bay is not worth the risk of an oil spill to fish
and wildlife.
   They also contend that a spill would do more environmental harm
there than the Exxon Valdez spill did to Prince William Sound. The
March 24 tanker disaster, the nation's worst oil spill, forced the
closure of several fishing areas.
   Bristol Bay supports the world's largest red salmon fishery,
worth more than $1 billion annually, and the largest herring
fishery in U.S. waters. It also is home to a majority of the
world's northern fur seals, the Pacific Gray whale population, and
millions of seabirds, geese and ducks.
   ``Bristol Bay is the only place we've opposed oil development,
and for one chief reason _ the risk to the fishery isn't worth the
potential oil spill,'' said Gov. Steve Cowper. ``The court's action
is disappointing, but shouldn't be a surprise to anyone.''
   An agreement in a House-Senate conference committee last week
would prohibit any drilling in the bay for a year, and require the
Interior Department to consider buying back the leases.
   Under the plan, any buy-back recommendation would be tied to the
results of an Interior Department study of the effects of the Exxon
Valdez spill. That study also would look at the adequacy of
spill-contingency plans for Bristol Bay development. Only Congress
could authorize the repurchases.
   The agreement is contained in the department's fiscal 1990
spending bill, which was expected to return to the House today and
the Senate by Wednesday for final approval, said Jane Robbins,
press secretary for Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska.
   The studies and Interior's recommendation are due by March 1991,
meaning no exploration is likely in Bristol Bay before then.
   Sue Flensburg, director of the Bristol Bay Coastal Resource
Service Area in Dillingham, said the congressional moratorium and
eventual repurchase of the leases represent the last chances to
protect the bay.
   ``At this point I'm pretty confident that it will make it
through the appropriations bill, and that's about the best we can
hope for at this point,'' she said.
   Weiner said the congressional effort is more significant in
light of Monday's court action.
   ``Bristol Bay is one of the world's most productive fisheries
and home to seven species of endangered mammals,'' he said. ``It's
one of the last places in this country that should be developed for
oil.''
</TEXT>
