<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-89 0528EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SouthAfrica     10-03 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government-Opposition Talks Over Rent Boycott Called Breakthrough</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government officials have for
the first time negotiated with leading anti-apartheid leaders about
ending the 3-year-old rent boycott in Soweto, the country's largest
black township.
   Business Day, a Johannesburg daily, today described the talks as
the highest-level bargaining session ever held between the
white-controlled government and major anti-apartheid activisits.
   It quoted one unidentified activist as calling Monday's parley,
in which the government offered to waive some unpaid rent, ``an
unprecedented breakthrough'' because the activists were accepted as
primary negotiating partners.
   The boycott has been one of the most effective protests by
blacks since a national state of emergency was declared in June
1986.
   Soweto, home to an estimated 2.5 million blacks on the outskirts
of Johannesburg, has been the hardest-hit of several townships
affected by rent boycotts. It has lost more than $100 million in
revenue.
   The government delegation, led by Transvaal Province
administrator Danie Hough, met in Pretoria with Soweto city
councilors and prominent activists, including Anglican Archbishop
Desmond Tutu; the Rev. Frank Chikane, general secretary of the
South African Council of Churches; and Albertina Sisulu,
co-president of the United Democratic Front anti-apartheid
coalition.
   Hough said the activists ``have a very important role to play''
_ an unusual government acknowledgement of the influence enjoyed by
militant leaders within black communities. He said the delegations
would meet again.
   The government could not accept demands to write off all unpaid
rent, but a partial waiver could be negotiated, Hough said.
   He offered to negotiate ways to transfer ownership of rented
houses to their occupants, another demand of the activists.
   Hough said a demand that Soweto and Johannesburg be unified to
share tax revenue was ``probably impractical.''
   Chikane, the activists' spokesman, said the meeting showed that
``we can resolve problems by talking rather than relegating the
solution to the police.''
   Police have tried periodically to evict boycotters from their
homes. One such campaign, in August 1986, led to confrontations in
which more than 20 blacks were killed by police gunfire.
   Under apartheid, South Africa's 28 million blacks have no vote
in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
