<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-89 0530EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CarnegieHall     10-03 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Carnegie Hall,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Archivist Searches for Memorabilia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL STIEG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carnegie Hall's archivist says he would ``give
anything for a ticket from Opening Night'' in 1891 to add to the
souvenirs being collected for the hall's 100th anniversary.
   Gino Francesconi says he knows an original ticket is out there
somewhere.
   ``I was told by a collector that he had seen it five or six
years ago,'' he said Monday.
   Photos from pre-1920 and posters from before 1960 still are
needed, Francesconi said.
   ``Most of those are just hanging on people's walls. I can't
believe that there aren't posters of Mark Twain, Woodrow Wilson,
Toscanini out there,'' Francesconi said.
   The call for historic items already has turned up other goodies,
including the silver trowel used by Andrew Carnegie's wife, Louise,
to lay the cornerstone in 1890 and a ribbon that was cut on opening
night in 1891.
   Bennie Goodman's daughter, Rachel Edelson, donated one of her
late father's clarinets, and lots of photographs and recordings
have surfaced.
   The items will be shown in special exhibitions in 1990 and 1991,
and some eventually will be displayed in a Carnegie Hall museum.
   Francesconi has most of the house programs, but is missing those
from 1892-98, 1928-37 and 1944-47.
   ``There are things out there that people assume we have,'' he
said. ``Maybe once upon a time we did, but when the hall was
threatened with demolition in the late 1950s, we know stuff
disappeared. They wanted to take souvenirs before Carnegie Hall was
gone for good.''
   Francesconi is also hoping to turn up correspondence relating to
the hall.
   ``People have responded from all over the country, it's just
been fantastic,'' he said. ``But we're fighting the clock now _
we've given ourselves until March to look for material.''
</TEXT>
