<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-89 0541EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-Young-Paternity     10-03 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Young-Paternity,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Out-of-Court Settlement Reached in Young Paternity Suit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRETEL WIKLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Coleman Young has agreed to pay $11,700 a
year and create a $150,000 education trust for a 6-year-old boy to
settle a paternity suit, a judge announced.
   The out-of-court settlement was called generous by lawyers for
both sides and resolves the matter five weeks before Detroit's
mayoral election, in which Young is seeking a fifth term.
   Under terms of the settlement, announced Monday by Chief Wayne
Circuit Court Judge Richard Kaufman, Young will pay $225 a week _
$11,700 annually _ to Joel Loving until he turns 19. He also will
set aside enough money to create a $150,000 trust for the boy's
education.
   ``We feel that it's a rather good settlement for Joel Loving,''
said Noel Keane, lawyer for the boy's mother, Annivory Calvert.
``We have virtually established his welfare through age 18 and
certainly given him a nice little stipend to start his life.''
   Calvert, 34, a former Detroit city official who is now director
of public works for the city of Fontana, Calif., sued Young in
January. In May, laboratory tests proved the four-term, 71-year-old
mayor was the boy's father.
   ``From this point on, I'll be able to get on with the rest of my
life,'' Calvert said.
   Lawrence Charfoos, Young's lawyer, also said the settlement was
generous.
   The mayor ``has done as fine a job of taking care of his son as
any son can ask of a father,'' he said.
   The trust will pay $10,000 installments each year from the boy's
19th through 24th birthday. When he turns 25, the trust will
terminate and he will receive the remaining $90,000. The payments
require the boy, who turns 7 on Oct. 18, him to pursue a
post-secondary education, Keane said.
   ``We hope beyond (the money) Young will establish a father
relationship,'' Keane said.
   Charfoos said Young's relationship with his son is ``obviously a
significant concern'' but wouldn't discuss what Young plans to do.
   The settlement means Young's income tax returns will remain
private, along with the amount of money in his campaign coffers,
estimated to be about $5 million before the primary.
   The mayor is running for a fifth, four-year term against Tom
Barrow, an accountant whom Young defeated soundly four years ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
