<FIRST>r a PM-HershLibelTrial     10-03 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hersh Libel Trial,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kissinger Testifies for Plaintiff at Libel Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI T. PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Secretary of State Henry Kissinger,
testifying in a libel lawsuit against a Pulitzer Prize-winner
Seymour Hersh, said he doesn't believe former Indian Prime Minister
Morarji Desai was a CIA informant.
   But under cross-examination in U.S. District Court Monday,
Kissinger admitted he couldn't be absolutely sure Desai didn't
provide information to the CIA because he wasn't told the names of
informants.
   Kissinger was subpoenaed to testify in the $100-million libel
trial brought by Desai against Hersh.
   Desai contends Hersh, 52, libeled him in his 1983 book on
Kissinger, ``The Price of Power.'' Hersh wrote that Desai was a
paid informant for the CIA and a valuable ``asset'' to the U.S.
government during the administrations of Lyndon Johnson and Richard
Nixon.
   To prove libel, Desai's attorneys must convince the six-member
jury that Hersh knowingly printed false, negligent or malicious
material about Desai.
   Desai, 94, is too ill to attend the trial and gave his
deposition previously via 81 hours of videotape.
   Kissinger testified Monday that Desai was not a CIA informant.
He said he had been told by former CIA Director Richard Helms that
he ``was on safe ground'' in saying that.
   ``To the best of your knowledge did Mr. Desai provide any
intelligence information to the United States in 1971?'' asked
plaintiff's attorney Cyriac Kappil.
   ``Not to the best of my knowledge,'' said Kissinger.
   Kissinger testified that in 1971, the U.S. government believed
India was about to invade West Pakistan, now known as Pakistan,
based on intelligence reports. Kissinger became national security
advisor in 1969 and served as secretary of state from 1973 to 1977.
   Under cross-examination by Hersh's attorney, Kissinger said he
wasn't told the names of paid CIA informants.
   ``You don't know the name of a single person who's gotten such
funds, correct?'' questioned defense attorney Bud Nussbaum.
   ``Correct,'' Kissinger replied.
   ``Is it correct that you don't know whether, in fact, government
officials said that to Mr. Hersh?'' Nussbaum later asked, referring
to Hersh's contention that government sources had identified Desai
as a paid informant.
   ``Or whether they existed,'' Kissinger replied. ``I know nothing
about them.''
   Kissinger was the awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 1973 for his
part in ending the war in Vietnam.
   Hersh won the Pulitzer Prize for international reporting in 1970
for his reporting on the My Lai massacre in Vietnam.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
