<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold 1stLd-Writethru a0499 10-03 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0499,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Little Changed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvs, `In Tokyo...' to CORRECT closing yen rate
in Tokyo; Pickup 4th, `Dealers in...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose in early European trading today
despite earlier interventions by the Bank of Japan in East Asian
markets.
   Gold prices were little changed.
   Foreign currency dealers said repeated dollar sales by the Bank
of Japan, estimated in the market to total $800 million, did little
damage to the dollar-yen rate.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose 1.35 yen to a closing 140.65 yen.
Later, in London, it was quoted at 141 yen.
   Dealers in Europe said the market is unwilling to shift
positions much ahead of the Thursday meeting of the Deutsche
Bundesbank's central bank council, which is expected to hike key
German rates by at least half a point.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Monday:
   _ 1.8827 West German marks, up from 1.8750
   _ 1.6335 Swiss francs, up from 1.6240
   _ 6.3885 French francs, up from 6.3595
   _ 2.1248 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1140
   _ 1,377.22 Italian lire, up from 1,366.50
   _ 1.1775 Canadian dollars, up from 1.7772
   In London, the dollar rose slightly against the British pound.
It cost $1.6106 to buy one pound, compared with $1.6175 late Monday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $365.50 a troy ounce,
compared with late Monday's $366.50. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $365.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $365.40 down from $366.40 late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 75 cents to close at a bid
$366.50.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.23 a troy
ounce, unchanged from late Monday.
</TEXT>
