<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-Activist     10-03 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Activist,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abie Nathan Sentenced to Six Months for Meeting Arafat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARIEH O'SULLIVAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAMLE, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge sentenced Israeli peace activist
Abie Nathan today to six months in prison for violating an Israeli
law by meeting with PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat.
   Nathan, who pleaded guilty to the charge last week, said he
would fight to overturn the law ``even from my prison cell.'' He
received a one-year suspended sentence in addition to the jail term.
   The 63-year-old Nathan operates the pirate radio station ``Voice
of Peace'' from a ship in the Mediterranean.
   Dressed in black pants and a black shirt, Nathan stood silent as
Aharon Fass, deputy president of the Ramle Magistrate's Court, read
the sentence.
   He told reporters later that his jailing would not halt his
efforts for Arab-Israeli peace.
   ``If somebody thinks I'm going to stop ... they're in for big
surprises,'' he said. ``I hope that public opinion and the people
in the streets will understand that this law is an obstacle to
peace.
   ``I will continue even from my prison cell to protest against
this law ... and immediately after prison I shall continue to speak
to the enemy,'' he said.
   The sentencing came as arguments raged in Israel's coalition
Cabinet over whether to agree to Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's
call for Israel to hold peace talks with Palestinians approved by
the PLO.
   Israel refuses to negotiate with the PLO, which it calls a
terrorist organization.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc opposes
meeting a PLO-approved delegation, but the left-leaning Labor Party
accepts the plan.
   The meetings would be a first step toward resolving the
21-month-old Palestinian uprising against Israeli rule of the West
Bank and Gaza Strip. AT least 575 Arabs and 40 Israelis have died
in the revolt.
   Nathan pleaded guilty Wednesday to meeting with Arafat and other
PLO activists in Tunisia and France in September 1988.
   He told the court he knew he was violating a 1986 amendment to
the anti-terror law that prohibits holding meetings with terrorist
organizations.
   The court ruled that Nathan could start his sentence after the
Yom Kippur Jewish holiday on Monday.
   Nathan faced a three-year sentence but the few people convicted
as violators have had sentences commuted to public service. The
judgment said Nathan had more responsibility as a public figure.
   Defense lawyer Pinhas Marinsky said Nathan would not appeal the
sentence.
   The court judgment said of Nathan, ``No matter the good of his
intentions or his motives, it cannot release him of his criminal
responsibility ... In a democratic state, it's inconceivable to
take the law into your own hands.''
   Nathan is best known for his dramatic trip to Cairo in 1964 to
try to persuade Egypt to make peace with Israel. In 1978, he went
on a 45-day hunger strike to protest building Jewish settlements in
the occupied territories.
   The Indian-born Nathan first met Arafat in 1982 when he traveled
to Lebanon during the Israeli siege of Beirut in an unsuccessful
attempt to gain freedom for a captured Israeli soldier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
