<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-89 0837EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SalemBombs     10-03 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salem Bombs,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Says Man Planted Bombs Out of Rivalry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBBIE NEWBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ALBANY, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man on trial on charges of planting 13
bombs around buildings and bridges was motivated by a rivalry with
a legislator who long ago beat him out for roles in high school
plays, a prosecutor said.
   ``This is a drama that started a number of years ago,''
Assistant U.S. Attorney Robert Stanley Powell said during opening
arguments Monday. ``It started in the mind of John Marion Hubbard,
a non-conformist who didn't believe in authority.''
   Hubbard, 31, is charged with making and planting the bombs found
in 1988 in Salem, a community of 6,000.
   None of the bombs exploded, but three ignited and fizzled. No
one was injured.
   Hubbard could be sentenced to 285 years in prison if convicted
of conspiracy, illegal possession of dynamite, 14 counts of making
bombs and 13 of attempting to destroy buildings and bridges used in
interstate commerce.
   ``This was a cowardly, terroristic act that held the city
hostage,'' Powell said. ``It still holds the city hostage.''
   Defense attorney Paul J. Watts contended the government's case
was based largely on circumstantial evidence and ``exaggeration,
drama, theatrics and no substance.''
   Powell said the government would introduce tape recordings in
which Hubbard boasted there were only two people in Salem smart
enough to manufacture the bombs _ he and Jerry Conrad, 42, who
worked with Hubbard at a factory.
   Conrad was convicted Sept. 5 on the same counts Hubbard is
charged with and was expected to testify for the government in
Hubbard's trial.
   Powell said the largest of the 13 bombs, containing 54 sticks of
dynamite, was found behind the law office of state Rep. Frank
Newkirk Jr. The prosecutor said Hubbard had a rivalry with Newkirk
that dated to their high school days, when they competed for
theater roles.
   ``He was traditionally beat out in almost every instance by
Frank Newkirk Jr. The feelings built up in Hubbard,'' Powell said.
   The prosecutor said Hubbard regularly wore camouflage. ``He
calls himself a survivalist. He calls himself antagonistic. He
calls himself a radical, and that's what he is,'' Powell said.
   Watts told jurors they would have to decide whether the devices
found around Salem were ``in fact bombs or were they something
designed to scare.''
   Watts said his client has ``a boatload of emotional problems and
substantial alcohol problems. When he's drinking, he brags, he
lies, and he exaggerates.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
