<FIRST>u i PM-Israel     10-03 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir Aide Suggests Labor-Likud Compromise In The Works</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top aide to Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir
said today that Israel's two governing parties may head off a
crisis over the Egyptian peace plan by agreeing to hold talks on
the issue with Americans and Egyptians.
   In Tokyo, visiting PLO chief Yasser Arafat told the Japanese
prime minister that the PLO favors opening Israeli-Palestinian
talks through Egypt, officials said. Israel expressed
disappointment over Japan's invitation to Arafat.
   A compromise between the center-left Labor Party and the
right-wing Likud bloc could defuse a tense situation before an
inner Cabinet meeting Thursday on Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak's offer to arrange preliminary peace talks between
Palestinians and Israelis.
   The compromise also could reduce American pressure on Israel to
accept Mubarak's peace efforts. Mubarak met Monday in Washington
with President Bush, and said Israel should not squander a ``golden
opportunity'' for peace by rejecting his plan.
   In the occupied territories, meanwhile, troops today clashed
with Palestinian stone-throwers, wounding four people, one
seriously, Arab reports said. The army said it was checking the
reports.
   At least 123 Palestinians have been killed by fellow Arabs as
suspected collaborators during the 21-month uprising against
Israeli occupation. More than 580 others have died in clashes with
soldiers and Israeli civilians. Forty Israelis have been slain.
   The political feud in Israel centers on objections by Likud,
headed by Shamir, to U.S.-backed Egyptian proposals for Israel to
negotiate with a team of Palestinians before holding elections in
the occupied territories.
   Labor, headed by Finance Minister Shimon Peres, supports the
Egyptian idea, believing it the only way to break an impasse in the
peace process.
   Shamir balks at Egypt's proposal to include two Palestinians
deported by Israel in the delegation. He feels this would be
tantamount to opening the door to the Palestine Liberation
Organization, which Israel views as a terrorist group.
   Shamir's top political aide, Yossi Ben-Aharon, indicated in an
interview with army radio Tuesday that the prime minister may be
open to a compromise that would involve holding more exploratory
talks on the question.
   Asked whether Shamir would agree to a three-way meeting of
American, Egyptian and Israeli representatives over the composition
of a Palestinian delegation, Ben-Aharon replied:
   ``Theoretically yes, because it sounds reasonable for such a
tripartite meeting to hold a preliminary discussion over carrying
out Israel's political initiative.''
   He stressed that any talks with Palestinians would require prior
agreement by the Arabs to Shamir's peace plan published last April,
which calls for elections in the disputed lands pending
negotiations for an interim settlement. He ruled out PLO
involvement.
   U.S. officials have been pressuring Israel to accept the
Egyptian proposals as a basis for continuing the stalemated peace
process.
   In Tokyo, a senior Foreign Ministry official said Arafat told
Prime Minister Toshiki Kaifu he ``positively appraised'' an
agreement by Bush and Mubarak to promote the peace process and to
support Mubarak's peace plan.
   The PLO has not yet issued an official position on Mubarak's
plan. It objects to the fact that no mention is made of an
independent Palestinian state.
</TEXT>
