<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Yeltsin     10-03 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Yeltsin,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Party Leaders Had Nothing to Do with Yeltsin Article</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist leaders had nothing to do with the
reprinting of an article that accused maverick Boris N. Yeltsin of
going on a drinking and buying binge in the United States, a
Politburo official said.
   The Communist Party daily Pravda reprinted the biting article
from the Italian newspaper La Repubblica on Sept. 18 in what many
Yeltsin supporters saw as an effort by party leaders to discredit
the burly, silver-haired populist.
   Several days later Pravda apologized, saying the allegations in
the story had not been proven.
   In an interview broadcast Monday on official television,
Politburo member Vadim A. Medvedev denied that top party officials
put Pravda up to publishing the article.
   ``No instructions were given to the Soviet press,'' Medvedev
said in a summary of his remarks distributed by the Tass news
agency.
   Other newspapers were discouraged from publishing the same La
Repubblica piece, he said.
   Yeltsin, elected to the the new Congress of People's Deputies,
has rankled Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and other top
leaders with persistent calls to push Gorbachev's reform program
faster, and has accused the party apparatus of organizing a
campaign to try to discredit him.
   He was forced out of his job as Moscow Communist Party chief in
November 1987 after criticizing the party at a Central Committee
meeting, and later lost his post as a candidate, or non-voting,
member of the ruling party Politburo.
</TEXT>
