<SECOND>PM-Poland, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0521,0617</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Party Tries to Fit Into New Poland</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 11th graf, `The party ...' with quotes
from party secretary.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party leaders began meeting
today to discuss ways to overhaul their image and win support of a
citizenry that has embraced the new Solidarity-led government.
   The party, the first ever to lose control of a Soviet bloc
government, is even considering changing its official name _ the
Polish United Workers Party _ as part of its effort to improve its
standing with the populace.
   Opposition candidates virtually swept all seats available to
non-Communist candidates in June's partially free elections.
Pro-Solidarity lawmakers eventually put together a coalition with
parties that were once allied with the Communists, resulting last
month in the first non-Communist government in the East bloc.
   In 1993, elections are to be fully democratic, and the
Communists are trying desperately to find a place in the new
Poland, which is embracing democratic reforms in a scramble to
salvage its collapsing economy.
   A survey released at the start of today's Central Committee
plenum showed that fully 72 percent of the party members favor
changing its name to reflect a change in image and purpose.
   Party leaders were expected to set a date and an agenda for a
party congress, which would enact the changes recommended by the
Central Committee. The congress would be a meeting of 1,000 to
2,000 delegates elected from among the 2 million rank-and-file
party members.
   The congress is expected to be set for mid-February, said a
party official, demanding anonymity.
   The party official said the internal party survey, in which more
than half the members took part, showed there was a strong danger
that the party could split.
   Party chief Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski has warned that a split could
end the party. Accordingly, the plenum has adopted the slogan
``Unity at Any Price.''
   The official described the split within party ranks as being
between the leadership and the rank-and-file members, who favor
radical reform, and the ``middle level'' party organizers who want
to maintain a traditional party.
   The party official said the goal is to create a party that will
be attractive to voters in the 1993 elections. The party hopes to
do well enough in the voting to emerge as the dominant partner in a
leftist coalition, he said.
   Party Secretary Leszek Miller said the party is inviting society
to ``create the party with us,'' and that the party must strive to
find an identity which will give it a popular base.
   ``The question is whether the Polish United Workers Party can
fulfill the aspirations of the part of Polish society which is
left-leaning,'' he said.
   The plenum also is expected to support internal party democracy,
a state-dominated economy for Poland, and instigate a shakeup of
the ruling Politburo. It would be the second leadership shuffle
since July, the official said.
   ``If we remain in unity for three months, then we exist and we
will win,'' the official said. ``If the party is destroyed, then
the left does not exist for practical purposes for many years.''
   The pro-Solidarity newspaper Gazeta Wyborcza reported today that
the draft resolution for the plenum called for development of a
``humanitarian, democratic and effective socialism.''
   On the economic front, the draft favors a multi-sector economy
dominated by the state-run economy. It opposes selling off state
enterprises, a chief economic goal of the Solidarity-led government.
   The draft also ``obliges all party cells to create conditions
for free expression of different views,'' the newspaper said.
</TEXT>
