<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Abortion 1stLd-Writethru a0480 10-03 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Abortion, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0480,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stevens Disqualifies Self from Abortion Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs grafs 3-5 with six new grafs to indicate Justice O'Connor
still key vote; picks up 6th graf pvs, The law could force.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the Supreme Court's abortion rights
supporters is not taking part in a key abortion case before the
court in its 1989-90 term.
   Justice John Paul Stevens disqualified himself from the Illinois
case, one of three the high court is considering this term, for
unstated reasons, court spokeswoman Toni House said Monday.
   Stevens had not disqualified himself when the justices agreed
last July 3 to review the case. But a minor court order issued
Monday in the Illinois case, which deals with abortion clinic
regulations, noted that Stevens did not participate.
   His absence will not change the outcome of the case if the
justices line up as they did last July when voting 5-4 to let
states make abortion harder to get.
   Stevens was one of the dissenters.
   Justice Sandra Day O'Connor still is the key vote. If she votes
against the Illinois law, the outcome could be a 4-4 ``pro-choice''
victory. If she votes in favor of the law, the outcome could be a
5-3 anti-abortion victory.
   A 4-4 split would not set any legal precedent outside Illinois.
   The case focuses on a state law that would require abortion
clinics to add services and equipment now found only in hospitals.
   The law could force many clinics to close down, and could add up
to $50 to the cost of an abrtion performed in the first three
months of pregnancy.
   In invalidating the law, lower courts said it violated a portion
of the 1973 ruling in Roe vs. Wade that limited state regulation
over first-trimester abortions.
   Illinois officials are not asking the justices to use the
Illinois case to reverse Roe vs. Wade, but legal experts say the
court's ruling could chip away at the trimester-by-trimester
approach taken in the 1973 decision.
   The two other abortion cases under high court study this term
focus on parental notification requirements for unwed minors
seeking to end their pregnancies in Minnesota and Ohio. Stevens has
not disqualified himself from those cases.
   The Illinois case is Turnock vs. Ragsdale, 88-790.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
