<FIRST>r a PM-EnforcedDemocracy     10-03 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Enforced Democracy,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Stop Cars to Round Up Town Meeting Quorum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It took a police roundup on Main
Street to get a quorum of 50 for a Town Hall meeting in this
village in the Berkshires.
   Town officials appealed to officers when faced with a room of
empty seats for Monday night's meeting on whether Stockbridge
should join an area recycling pact.
   Police Chief Richard Wilcox stationed cruisers with lights
flashing in front of Town Hall and had officers pull over cars and
check for Stockbridge citizens. Anyone who admitted living here was
escorted into Town Hall.
   Emergency calls also went out to two fire companies and a
parent-teachers meeting at the school in this small town used by
Norman Rockwell to illustrate the ``Freedom of Speech'' in his
series of paintings ``The Four Freedoms.''
   ``After a brief cattle drive we rounded up the 32 we needed,''
Wilcox said today.
   The chief said that officers learned from previous roundups not
to let citizens talk their way out of attending.
   ``We hear more excuses than the judge does when someone comes
before him with a traffic ticket,'' he said. ``You'd be amazed how
many people are in the pajamas at 8 p.m. when you telephone.''
   Once inside, the reluctant participants didn't have to tarry. It
took citizens less than 15 minutes to approve the plan.
   ``Monday night football is a lot of competition when there's
nothing special on the town meeting agenda,'' Wilcox said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
