<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-89 1045EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Colombia     10-03 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Reportedly Will Approve Extraditions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STAN YARBRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court will vote to approve
President Virgilio Barco's decrees allowing extradition of top drug
suspects to the United States and confiscation of their property,
national television reported.
   The television program TV Hoy, quoting court sources, reported
Monday night that a majority of 24 justices on the Court supported
the decrees.
   The deadline for the court to rule was today, but normally
several days pass before court rulings are made public.
   Seven bombs exploded in Colombian cities Monday night, two in
the Carribbean coast city of Barranquilla, three in the port city
of Santa Marta and two in the capital of Bogota, national police
said.
   Two people were injured in Barranquilla and two more in Santa
Marta, the police said. They were part of a daily wave of bombings
presumably set by drug traffickers.
   A Supreme Court ruling allowing extraditions would strengthen
the Barco administration in its war against the drug lords, and
would help allay fears that the court could undermine the anti-drug
crackdown.
   TV Hoy said, however, that the court would declare
unconstitutional an additional decree allowing the Colombian army
to raid drug traffickers' property at will.
   It said the court will support the government's right to
confiscate property from drug traffickers but will require that it
go through judicial channels.
   The court will not decide on the legality of property already
seized, leaving that issue for lower courts, TV Hoy said.
   As of a week ago, the army had seized 1,056 homes, ranches,
mansions office buildings and other property allegedly belonging to
drug traffickers.
   The administration's main weapon in the drug war is its power to
extradite suspected drug figures who have repeatedly shown their
ability to escape justice in Colombia.
   The United States has a list of 80 Colombians it wants
extradited to face drug charges, but it has disclosed the names of
only the top 12.
   In 1984 the Supreme Court, ruling on a technicality, declared
extraditions to the United States unconstitutional.
   The court has not dealt favorably with other important Barco
decrees. Before Barco declared war on the traffickers Aug. 19, the
court had knocked down seven decrees he issued in attempts to deal
with both guerrillas and drug traffickers.
   The most important of earlier decrees declared unconstitutional
was one creating a special tribunal within the Supreme Court to
deal with drug trafficking and other cases that present security
problems for lower court judges.
   Barco wanted to remove certain cases from the jurisdiction of
the lower court judges, who often have been threatened or killed
while handling drug trafficking cases.
   In the last 10 years 220 court employees, including 41 judges,
have been killed, many of them by drug traffickers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
