<FIRST>u i PM-Cambodia     10-03 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cambodian Guerrillas Battle For Northwestern Town</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NATE THAYER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ARANYAPRATHET, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cambodian guerrillas battled to
take a government-held town in northwestern Cambodia today, Western
and guerrilla sources said.
   The Khmer People's National Liberation Front and two other
guerrilla factions launched what they called a ``general
offensive'' against the pro-Hanoi government on Saturday. They
claimed to have overrun three towns and many other military
positions.
   The guerrillas called it their biggest victory in about 11 years
of guerrilla warfare.
   Vietnam, which previously fought alongside Cambodian government
forces after invading the country in 1978, says it withdrew its
troops a week ago.
   Thailand's Foreign Ministry claimed today that it held five
Vietnamese soldiers in Thailand's Chanthaburi province who were
captured in Cambodia since the pledged pullout.
   However, the Thai navy, which is responsible for the southern
part of Thailand's border with Cambodia including Chanthaburi, said
this was untrue.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Prachadavi Tavetikul said he planned
to show the Vietnamese to the press on Thursday, even though Capt.
Buncherd Phunchoren, a Royal Thai Navy spokesman, said there had
been no arrest or detention of any soldier since Sept. 20.
   In the Thai border town of Aranyaprathet heavy shelling and
automatic weapons fire could be heard all day to the north and to
the south across the border in Cambodia.
   Western sources on the frontier following battlefield movements
said the guerrillas were concentrating their forces on the town of
Kandoun, inside Cambodia some nine miles from Thailand. The sources
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The guerrillas also were attempting to prevent the resupply of
government positions, they said.
   No reliable reports of casualties have emerged either from the
guerrillas or the government. Phnom Penh official media have not
commented on the most recent fighting.
   Ieng Mouly, spokesman for the KPNLF in Bangkok, said the
offensive was a coordinated effort between the three guerrilla
factions; his own, those loyal to exiled monarch Prince Norodom
Sihanouk and the radical communist Khmer Rouge.
   The Khmer Rouge killed hundreds of thousands of Cambodians
during its rule from 1975 until its forces were ousted by the
Vietnamese in late 1978.
</TEXT>
