<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-89 1132EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SpermBanks     10-03 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sperm Banks,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>AIDS Prompts Ban on Sperm Donations From Homosexuals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gay men and intravenous drug users have been
barred from donating sperm in New York state because of worries
about AIDS.
   The regulations, which took effect this week, exclude any man
from donating to a sperm bank if he has had homosexual activity,
intravenous drug use or sex with a ``high risk'' person since 1977.
   The same people already are barred from donating blood in New
York state for the same reason, said Mary Anne Gardineer, Health
Department associate director for regulatory affairs.
   The regulations for the first time also require sperm banks to
obtain state licenses.
   ``Women who choose to undergo artificial insemination should not
be subjected to unnecessary risks for serious and even fatal
illnesses,'' Gardineer said.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome, which chiefly afflicts
homosexual men and intravenous drug users, is spread most often
through sex; needles or syringes shared by drug abusers; infected
blood, and from pregnant women to their offspring.
   Gardineer said there have been cases of infants who contracted
AIDS because of donated sperm, but she could not say how many.
   The prohibition was recommended by several doctors' groups.
   The rules require extensive medical background checks on donors
and tests on the donated sperm. All donations must be frozen for
six months, the time it takes for someone infected with the AIDS
virus to develop antibodies that show up in tests.
   The rules don't apply in cases where a man is donating sperm for
a specific woman, such as his wife, because donors have a right to
privacy, officials said.
   The growing popularity of artificial insemination made the rules
necessary, said Gardineer.
   In 1986, about 60,000 women gave birth as a result of artificial
insemination in the United States. She estimated there are five
sperm banks in New York state, but said the number isn't certain
because they haven't been licensed.
   New York state has 25,000 confirmed AIDS cases, about a quarter
of the nation's total. Most of them are in New York City.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891003-0091 </DOCNO>
