<FIRST>u w PM-TexasFugitive     10-03 0164</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Texas Fugitive,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marshal's Service Names Texan To `Most Wanted' List</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Marshals Service today named a Texas
Panhandle man convicted of killing a fellow inmate at the Texas
State Penitentiary to its list of the ``15 Most-Wanted'' fugitives.
   The Marshals Service said Emmett Franklin McSwain is an alleged
major manufacturer and distributor of illegal drugs throughout
Oklahoma, California, Louisiana and Texas.
   McSwain, 50, escaped from the Federal Prison Camp in Texarkana,
Texas, on Jan. 20, 1986, shortly after learning of his indictment
in Oklahoma City as a major illegal drug manufacturer and for
conducting a continuing criminal enterprise, the Marshals Service
said.
   At the time of his escape, he was serving a 10-year sentence for
possession with intent to distribute narcotics, officials said. He
also had been convicted of killing a fellow inmate at the Texas
State Penitentiary in 1970.
   Marshals Service Director Stanley E. Morris said that due to
McSwain should be considered armed and very dangerous.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
