<FIRST>r a PM-OilSpill     10-03 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Spill,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tanker Captain Says He Had No Lookout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The captain of a Greek tanker that hit a
reef and spilled 289,000 gallons of heating oil into Narragansett
Bay testified today he did not have the required lookout on the
bridge when entering the harbor.
   Iakovos Georgoudis, 43, of Greece also said maps made it unclear
exactly where ships are to pick up their harbor pilots to guide the
vessel into port. The vessel ran aground off Newport on June 23
before a pilot boarded.
   The captain of the World Prodigy told a board of inquiry
convened by the Coast Guard and the National Transportation Safety
Board that his company and Greek regulations required a lookout
when entering a harbor.
   ``There was no one,'' however, because the lookout had been sent
to help lower the ladder so the pilot could board, Georgoudis said
through interpreters.
   He said he was doing nearly all the work on the bridge at the
time of the accident, including lookout and navigator. ``I was
everything,'' he said.
   Georgoudis had refused to testify previously before the panel,
citing his right against self-incrimination. That no longer was an
issue after he pleaded guilty in August and September to state and
federal pollution charges.
   The captain was fined a total of $30,500. A charge of failing to
have a pilot on board was dropped as part of the plea bargain.
Authorities said the commonly agreed-on pickup point is actually
inside the area where state law requires a pilot.
   The tanker's owner, Ballard Shipping Co., pleaded guilty to a
misdemeanor and was ordered to pay $500,000.
   U.S. Attorney Lincoln Almond has said it was clear that
Georgoudis had too many duties at the time and the accident was
caused by negligence, not by recklessness.
   Gov. Edward DiPrete said $125,000 of Ballard's fine would be
used to help Rhode Island's fishing industry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
