<HEAD>With AM-Hugo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convoy of skilled laborers and garbage
trucks, dump trucks and other equipment will leave Pittsburgh this
weekend for a seven-day mission of mercy to hurricane-ravaged
Charleston, S.C.
   The caravan and 29 city employees had been scheduled to leave
Tuesday, but officials in Charleston, S.C., asked Pittsburgh to
delay the relief.
   ``They're afraid that after this week, people will forget about
them,'' said Deborah Liotus, an aide to Mayor Sophie Masloff.
   Pittsburgh plans to send refuse workers, roofers, electricians,
mechanics and other craftsmen. Front-end loaders, bucket trucks,
compressors, chippers and generators will also be shipped.
   ``We're trying to get some transport help from the Air Force,
but we're prepared to ship these things ourselves,'' said Public
Works Director Louis Gaetano.
