<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Babies     10-03 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Babies,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Intoxicated Infants Hospitalized After Medicine Mixup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine infants were hospitalized for severe
intoxication in Tel Aviv after mothers mistakenly gave them an
alcohol-based antiseptic instead of stomach medicine sold in
similar bottles, health officials said Tuesday.
   All the infants were about a month old and were being treated in
Tel Aviv's Sheba Hospital. Two were in the intensive care unit,
newspaper reports said.
   The Health Ministry issued a warning to mothers on Monday after
learning of the mix-up but said it will not order changes in the
packaging or labels on the bottles.
   Babic, a medicine commonly used to treat gas pains in infants,
is packaged in white plastic bottles that look like those
containing an alcohol-based antiseptic used externally.
   ``We warned mothers to pay attention to the labels,'' said
Health Ministry spokesman Gabi Zohar.
   Although the two products have different labels, the mothers
apparently confused the bottles while trying to give medicine at
night, the Yediot Ahronot daily said. It said a mother who realized
her mistake brought both bottles to the hospital.
   Zohar said it was unclear why the problem arose in the same area
of Tel Aviv at the same time, but the Jerusalem Post reported
similar problems earlier with the two products.
   The alcohol caused breathing difficulties, lowered the infants'
blood sugar and made them sluggish and sleepy.
</TEXT>
