<HEAD>Anne Pollard Makes Appeals for Help to Israeli Prime Minister</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anne Pollard, whose husband was convicted of
spying for Israel and is serving a life sentence in a U.S. prison,
has asked Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir to intervene with President
Bush on the American couple's behalf.
   Mrs. Pollard, also serving time in prison, said in a radio
broadcast Monday night: ``Johnathan and I are appealing to Shamir
to put an end to the Pollard affair once and for all.''
   A spokesman for Shamir's office said he was working to have them
freed ``on humanitarian grounds.''
   Jonathan Pollard, a former civilian intelligence analyst for the
U.S. Navy, was given a life term in 1987 for supplying classified
documents to Israeli agents.
   His wife spoke Monday night from a New York City apartment
during a furlough from a federal prison in Danbury, Conn., where
she is serving five years on related charges. She is to return to
the prison next week.
   Anne Pollard's father rented the apartment for her. She is said
to have a rare stomach disorder that has caused her to lose
considerable weight.
   She said the case could be resolved ``if the prime minister
would, either privately or openly _ and most importantly, candidly
_ discuss our case directly with President Bush. We strongly
believe this would be in the best interests of the United States
and Israel.''
   ``First and foremost, on behalf of my beloved husband Jonathan
and I, we wish to thank each and every citizen of the state of
Israel for their tremendous support of us throughout our plight,
and we are eternally grateful,'' she said.
   The Pollards have received support from some Jewish groups in
Israel and the United States that advocate Israeli government
intervention in the case.
   Mrs. Pollard spoke in English and an announcer translated her
remarks into Hebrew.
   The Israeli government has said it did not know of Pollard's
spying.
