<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-89 1239EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-GayClergyman     10-03 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gay Clergyman,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gay Clergyman Sues Norwegian Church Over Job Discrimination</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A clergyman Tuesday sued the state Lutheran
Church Council for denying him a job because he is a homosexual.
   Former hospital chaplain Jens T. Olsen, 41, was refused a job
with the council in March. Council spokesman Gunnar Vestermoen said
Olsen was not hired because he had lived with his homosexual
partner of seven years, in violation of church teachings.
   ``He was the first choice and was obviously well-qualified ...
but the council dropped him because he lived in a homosexual
relationship,'' said Vestermoen.
   The case went to court two days after a law took effect in
neighboring Denmark allowing homosexual couples to be registered as
``partners'' by civil authorities, with all the rights of married
heterosexual couples except adopting children. Eleven male couples
were ``married'' there Sunday.
   About 130 church workers, including clergymen, have supported
Olsen through petitions and newspaper advertisements.
   ``Support is warming up ... I am not alone within the church in
my views. The church discriminates against homosexuals,'' Oslen
told the Oslo newspaper Dagbladet.
   Supporters have cited a 1977 church decision to stop condemning
latent homosexuality to argue Olsen's case.
   ``It is meaningless ... to treat feelings and practice
differently,'' said theology professor Jacob Jervell. ``The council
accepts homosexuals but says it is wrong for them to live
together,'' he told Dagbladet.
</TEXT>
