<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-Marcos     10-03 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Marcos,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court to Consider Petition by Marcos Supporters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court agreed Tuesday to
consider a request that it nullify President Corazon Aquino's
decision not to let her predecessor, Ferdinand Marcos, be buried in
the Philippines.
   Imelda Marcos, the former president's widow, pledged to return
to the United States for trial on charges of embezzling Philippine
government funds if she was permitted to bury her husband, who died
Thursday in Honolulu at age 72, in the Philippines.
   Marcos ruled the archipelago for 20 years until a
civilian-military uprising drove him into exile in Hawaii in
February 1986.
   Several coups have been attempted by Marcos supporters. Mrs.
Aquino says the return of the body or of members of the family
could cause unrest.
   Philippine officials charge that Marcos, his family and
associates looted the country of up to $10 billion during his time
in power.
   Sen. Leticia Ramos-Shahani, who is related to Marcos but
supports Mrs. Aquino, urged Tuesday that the government begin
negotiations with the Marcos family toward allowing the former
president to be buried in the Philippines ``at the appropriate
time.''
   Mrs. Ramos-Shahani said Marcos should be buried in his home
province, Ilocos Norte, with the family allowed to attend the
funeral.
   ``The two parties should be given time to find a mutually
acceptable agreement,'' said the senator, who is the sister of
Defense Secretary Fidel Ramos amd head of the Senate committee on
foreign relations.
   Asked by The Associated Press how soon the body should be
returned, she said: ``One or two months.''
   Former Sen. Arturo Tolentino, Marcos' running mate in 1986, said
Monday the body could be flown directly to the international
airport at Laoag, capital of Ilocos Norte, instead of passing
through Manila. Laoag is about 250 miles north of the capital.
   Also Monday, Marcos supporters petitioned the Supreme Court to
overturn Mrs. Aquino's ban and allow Imelda Marcos and her three
children to bring the body to the Philippines. The court agreed
Tuesday to consider the petition, and Justice Teodoro Padilla said
the government was given 10 days to respond.
   Solicitor-General Francisco Chavez said the government would
argue that the issue is political, not legal, and that Mrs. Marcos
might use the opportunity to evade prosecution in the United States.
   Imelda Marcos has been prohibited from leaving the United
States, where she is to be tried in New York in March on charges of
embezzling Philippine government money and investing some of it in
the United States. The Marcoses were indicted in October and Mrs.
Marcos is free on $5 million bond.
   ``I will have to go back to New York because I have to face the
indictment,'' Mrs. Marcos told the Manila radio station DZXL in an
interview from Honolulu on Tuesday. ``What I am defending here is
not only the Marcos name, but the entire nation.''
   The government anti-graft court temporarily suspended
proceedings Tuesday in the first of 35 civil suits against Marcos.
Government lawyers said they would file a petition soon to
substitute either the Marcos estate or the late president's
executor as a defendant.
   In the appeal to the Supreme Court, Marcos supporters claimed
Mrs. Aquino's refusal to permit burial in the Philippines violates
the constitution. On Sept. 15, before Marcos died, the court ruled
8-7 that his return would be a threat to security.
</TEXT>
