<FIRST>r a PM-AbortionLegislation     10-03 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion Legislation,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abortion Restrictions Proposed in Pennsylvania</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE McGRAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of the Legislature's
anti-abortion forces today introduced a bill to put sweeping
restrictions on abortion.
   At a news conference, Republican Rep. Stephen Freind said the
legislation would directly challenge Roe vs. Wade and give the U.S.
Supreme Court another chance to overturn its 1973 ruling
establishing the right to an abortion.
   Earlier this year, the high court gave states broader powers to
restrict abortions. Freind's bill, which has the backing of
Democratic Gov. Robert P. Casey, could be the first to be adopted
since that ruling in July.
   The suburban Philadelphia legislator, who arrived at the news
conference under police guard and was picketed by abortion-rights
advocates, said his bill would:
   _ Require a 24-hour waiting period before a woman can have an
abortion.
   _ Outlaw all abortions after the 24th week of pregnancy except
to save the woman's life.
   _ Ban abortions by women who want to choose the sex of a child.
   _ Require notification of the spouse before a woman has an
abortion. The high court has previously rejected such notification
laws.
   ``We are very encouraged that the legislation will be passed by
the Pennsylvania Legislature,'' said Mary Beliveau of the
Pennsylvania Pro-Life Federation.
   Abortion-rights advocates today introduced their legislative
package, including a proposed constitutional amendment establishing
a right to an abortion.
   The pro-choice bills would also restore government funding for
poor women who have medically necessary abortions and would weaken
a law requiring parental notification or a court order before a
minor can obtain an abortion. That provision is not in effect
because it is under court review.
   While Pennsylvania's Legislature historically has opposed
abortion, pro-choice advocates said today that most Pennsylvania
voters support the right to choose.
   In a poll of 500 likely voters, the National Abortion Rights
Action League said 60 percent favored keeping abortion legal, while
33 percent wanted to outlaw it.
   ``This data shows how dramatically out-of-step Pennsylvania's
officials are with their constituents on abortion,'' said Kate
Michelman, the league's executive director. ``The political
atmosphere surrounding choice is more highly charged than ever. ...
Politicians in Pennsylvania who support abortion restrictions in
1989 may well be voted out of office in 1990.''
   The poll, taken Sept. 25-28 by Hickman-Maslin Research Inc., has
a margin of error of plus or minus 4.4 points.
</TEXT>
