<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-89 1358EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Haiti     10-03 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Haiti,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Cuts Salaries of President, Top Officials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ The government cut in half the
salary of Haiti's leader, and top officials' salaries were slashed
up to 33 percent in an effort to reduce the budget deficit, an
official newspaper said Tuesday.
   An Information Ministry communique published in L'Union, the
government's daily newspaper, said Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril's $10,000
a month salary has been reduced to $5,000. It said a 33 percent
salary cut would apply to Cabinet ministers, who earned $3,500
before the cut.
   The salary cuts, effective for six months starting Oct. 1, ``are
part of a strategy which aims at lessening the ills of the present
economic crisis,'' the communique said.
   A 20 percent salary cut was applied to top civil servants
earning $1,500 monthly, and 10 percent was deducted from the
salaries of public workers earning $1,000 monthly.
   The average annual income in Haiti is less than $300 a year.
   Haiti, one of the world's poorest nations, has a deficit of $60
million. The foreign debt is $800 million, three times more than
the annual budget. Government salaries account for 75 percent of
the budget, L'Union said.
   The move came a week after a 24-hour strike shut down virtually
all businesses and transport in the Caribbean nation of 6 million.
The strike was called by leftist and conservative groups to protest
austerity measures imposed to win a $26.5 million loan from the
International Monetary Fund.
   The day after the strike, Avril conceded the strikers' demands
were just but said he had no choice but to negotiate with the IMF
because ``we had a knife to our throat.''
</TEXT>
