<FIRST>r a PM-Westinghouse-Age     10-03 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Westinghouse-Age,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Ruling Upends Age-Bias Ruling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some 4,000 Westinghouse Electric Corp.
retirees who thought they had won $35 million in an age
discrimination suit may have lost it all as a result of a U.S.
Supreme Court ruling, a legal specialist says.
   The high court Monday overturned a lower-court ruling that the
Pittsburgh-based electronics and electric power giant had
discriminated against the retirees by forcing them to choose
between severance pay or early pensions.
   A judge had ruled in the retirees' favor and Westinghouse and
the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission, representing the
retirees, settled out of court in 1988 for $35 million, or an
average of $8,700 per person.
   But the EEOC backed out of the settlement in hope of a bigger
award in court. In the meantime, Westinghouse pursued the case to
the U.S. Supreme Court _ and won.
   ``It means they blew it. They got greedy, in my opinion,'' said
Dick Lauver, a Pittsburgh pension lawyer not involved in the case.
``They chose to forgo a very favorable settlement to get a
favorable court decision.''
   However, Donald Livingston, special assistant to the EEOC
general counsel in Washington, said the case ``is far from over.''
   ``There are still a number of areas for the court to decide,''
he said.
   EEOC spokeswoman Deborah Graham said the Westinghouse case was
the commission's biggest age discrimination settlement.
   Westinghouse said it was delighted with Monday's ruling.
</TEXT>
