<HEAD>Congressional Democrats Announce Aid Program for Poland Hungary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional Democratic leaders announced
today an aid program for Poland and Hungary that includes $887
million in food and other economic assistance and said they have
invited Solidarity union leader Lech Walesa to address a joint
meeting of Congress next month.
   Denouncing Bush administration aid efforts to date as ``grossly
inadequate,'' the Democrats proposed a package that also includes a
five-year moratorium on Poland's $2.5 billion debt to U.S. banks
and $1.4 billion in loans from international lending institutions.
   The package would include the authorization of $887 million in
U.S. food and economic aid over the next three years.
   This contrasts with the administation's commitment to date to
provide a total $255 million in assistance to the two East European
nations stuggling to discard communist rule and build democratic
institutions and free markets.
   The announcement came at a news conference held by House Speaker
Thomas F Foley, D-Wash., Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell,
D-Maine, and about 10 other Democratic figures in both houses.
   Foley and Mitchell said Walesa has been invited to speak before
a joint meeting of Congress on Nov. 15, one of the rare occasions
in U.S . history when such an assembly will have been addressed by
a person who is not a head of state or government.
   Rep. Lee Hamilton, D-Ind., said the legislation implementing the
aid package will be sped through Congress as quickly as possible in
light of the fact that Poland has nearly exhausted its foreign
currency reserves.
   He said the bill will urge the administration to seek a one-year
standby $700 million loan from the International Monetary Fund and
a $765 million loan from the World Bank.
   The legislation also will urge the White House to direct the
U.S. Treasury to make up to $1 billion available to Poland from
currency stabilization funds, Hamilton said.
   Hamilton said that of the $887 million authorization for U.S.
aid to Poland and Hungary, it is contemplated that Congress will be
asked to appropriate $415 million for the 1990 fiscal year which
opened on Oct. 1.
   The U.S. funds would be obtained by trimming other programs for
which funds have already been appropriated, Hamilton said.
   ``We intend to provide the leadership that has been lacking up
until now,'' Rep. John Dingel, D-Mich., told the news conference.
``The Bush program is grossly inadequate.''
   ``This is a new and meaningful initiative,'' Mitchell said.
``The administration's response to these historic events in Eastern
Europe has been woefully inadequate. In my viuew the
admimnistration has failed completely to understand the historic
nature of what has occurred.''
</TEXT>
