<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-89 1430EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Labor     10-03 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Labor,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kinnock Says Labor `Ready to Negotiate' With New Nuclear Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRIGHTON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leader Neil Kinnock said
Tuesday his Labor Party is ready to ``start being negotiators'' in
government following its renunciation of unilateral nuclear
disarmament.
   ``It is encouraging _ an inspiration _ to see the Labor Party
working together ... exuding to the British people the feeling that
we are fit to serve our country,'' Kinnock said in his keynote
address on the second day of the party's annual conference in this
south England resort.
   Kinnock, confident the weeklong conference will endorse a major
policy overhaul shifting the socialist movement to the center,
added that Britons ``respect us for the changes we have made and
are making.''
   Kinnock, who received a thunderous reception from the 1,500
delegates, has clamped down on Labor's left wing and transformed
the party's poll ratings in the past year.
   The party, consistently ahead in the polls since late spring, is
now in its strongest position since its third successive defeat by
Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's Conservatives in 1987. The next
election must be called by mid-1992.
   The new defense policy, stipulating that a Labor-led government
would give up British nuclear weapons only as part of a negotiated
arms deal, is part of the new policy. It also ditches some other
vote-losers, such as pledges of widespread nationalization.
   ``We seek the power ... to stop being spectators and start being
negotiators,'' said Kinnock during his speech.
   He said that because of deep divisions between East and West,
``security will continue to mean ... the security of negotiated
disarmament.''
   The stance represents a marked personal shift for Kinnock, 47,
who had been an ardent beliver in one-sided nuclear disarmament
since his student days.
   He accused Mrs. Thatcher of isolating Britain internationally,
citing her combative attitude toward the 12-nation European
Economic Community, her pressure for NATO to modernize its
short-range nuclear weapons, and her refusal to impose tough
sanctions against South Africa.
   ``It's not splendid isolation, or cunning, or sagacity, or
statespersonship,'' said Kinnock. ``It's a fundamental failure to
perceive and try to secure Britain's role in a rapidly changing
Europe and a rapidly changing world.''
</TEXT>
