<FIRST>r a AM-GeneralStore     10-03 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-General Store,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>Selectmen Trying to Sell Only Store</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAVOY, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This rural community has been trying to
unload its former town hall building for several years, while
hoping a new owner won't kick out the only store in town.
   ``There's nothing much I can do. It's their property,'' store
owner Norman C. Bates said in a telephone interview Tuesday.
   Bates, 58, who has been ill for some years, said he wouldn't
mind selling his business, although he doesn't feel town officials
appreciate the service he's provided.
   Bates has run the retail store for 35 years, paying the town
$100 a month rent.
   The store in this town of about 600, tucked into a fold of the
Berkshire Hills, is the only place to buy such necessities as bread
and milk, along with such traditional staples as penny candy, Bates
said. ``Some of it's a nickel or a dime now, though,'' he added.
   No one really knows how the store wound up in the old town hall
building, which was built in the early 1900s but has since been
replaced.
   ``That goes way, way back,'' said Selectman Chris Andersen. ``I
know that the upstairs part of the building has forever been a town
hall, that was closed down about three years ago because of fire
regulations.''
   ``That's where the town met and danced and ate and had their
meetings and everything,'' he said.
   Officials hoped a buyer would keep the store as a tenant,
although that was not a requirement of the sale. The closest town
is Adams, about eight miles away.
   Town residents first decided to sell the building and land in
1985, because it lacks the capital to make repairs.
   At first, a sale was delayed by a boundary dispute with the
next-door Savoy Baptist Church.
   After that was settled in 1988, voters put a special condition
on the sale that any buyer would have to continue to operate it as
a retail outlet. That effort to sell ended with no bids submitted.
   Now the building and land are up for sale without restrictions
and buyers would have to negotiate with Bates for the business,
Andersen said. No price was set for the store, he said.
   Store assistant Fran Kane said the store is in need of repairs,
particularly the leaking porch roof.
   She said Bates has suggested increasing the amount he pays the
town to get an official lease, making it worthwhile to do some
repair work. But, she said, that was rejected because of the desire
to sell.
</TEXT>
