<FIRST>r w AM-US-Nicaragua     10-03 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Nicaragua,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Gives Boost to Bush Plan to Aid Nicaraguan Elections</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: RETRANSMITTING a0643 to add overline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's plan for $9 million in U.S.
aid for the Nicaraguan elections moved ahead in Congress Tuesday
despite misgivings from Democrats who said the idea amounted to
blatant interference in another country's politics.
   The House Appropriations Committee, on a voice vote, sent the
measure to the full House after defeating a move to slash the
package to just $400,000 to pay for election observers. The House
was scheduled to take up the measure on Wednesday.
   Bush's proposal provides $5 million to the National Endowment
for Democracy, a quasi-governmental agency which promotes
democratic processes in other countries, and $4 million for other
``election support.''
   Some support could go directly to the opposition coalition
supporting presidential candidate Violeta Chamorro, who is
challenging Nicaragua's Sandinista-backed President Daniel Ortega.
   The panel earmarked portions of the $4 million for specific
organizations: $400,000 for an election observer team led by former
President Jimmy Carter; $400,000 for the Center for Training and
Election Promotion; and $250,000 for the Center for Democracy.
   One effect of the earmarks was to lower the maximum amount that
could go directly to the opposition coalition to about $1.5
million, with a like amount going to the Nicaraguan Supreme
Electoral Council as a tax required by Nicaraguan law.
   Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., called the package ``a turkey'' and
``misguided,'' but urged fellow Appropriations Committee members to
send the measure to the full House in accord with a promise to Bush
by the House Democratic leadership.
   Rep. Mickey Edwards, R-Okla., called the package necessary to
seize an opportunity ``to see whether democracy can be brought to
that country.''
   In a related development, House Intelligence Committee Chairman
Antony C. Beilenson, D-Calif., said the bill providing money for
the nation's intelligence agencies for next year contains no money
for covert U.S. involvement in the Feb. 25, 1990 election.
   The administration could undertake covert action only by coming
to Congress to ask for a transfer of money from other programs,
which would give lawmakers a chance to veto such a move, he said.
   ``Covertly supporting the opposition in Nicaragua would be
unwise as well as unnecessary and counterproductive,'' Beilenson
said in a Rules Committee hearing. ``We have accepted the
administration's statements that it will not embark on this path.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
