<SECOND>AM-Village Reappears,0124</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drowned Village Reappears in Dry Spell</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A village submerged 50 years ago during
construction of one of Britain's largest reservoirs has reappeared
after a spell of dry weather.
   The foundations of Derwent village showed up in Ladybower
Reservoir near Sheffield.
   The village was abandoned by its 170 people and its buildings
were demolished during the construction of the reservoir in
1937-1939, which serves the cities of Sheffield, Derby, Nottingham
and Leicester but flooded part of the Derwent river valley.
   Frank Long, a sailing instructor at Underbank Reservoir near
Sheffield, said water there had dropped from its normal 58 feet to
28 feet, forcing him to abandon the sailing program for the rest of
the year.
</TEXT>
