<FIRST>r a AM-APME-Janensch     10-03 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-APME-Janensch,0569</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper Editors Urged To Be `Fanatical' on Community Ties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's newspaper editors must be
``fanatical'' about developing ties to their communities if they
hope to reverse a slide in readership, the head of the Associated
Press Managing Editors said Tuesday.
   ``We must get closer to our communities,'' said Paul Janensch,
editor and general manager of The Rockland Journal-News in New York
City's suburban Rockland County, N.Y.
   ``Call it what you will _ customer obsession, putting the reader
first, serving the constituents _ we must do it better,'' he said.
``I firmly believe that if we build a strong rapport with our
communities, we will prosper. If we don't, we will fade away.''
   As he opened the annual APME convention, Janensch pointed to
figures showing that newspaper readership is declining.
   ``In 1967, about 73 percent of U.S. adults said they read a
newspaper every day,'' he said. ``Last year, the number was down to
51 percent.''
   Janensch said steadily declining readership ``confronts us with
the most serious problem facing newspapers today'' and said it even
hits markets where the economy is booming.
   ``If you are lucky enough to be in a growing market and your
circulation is going up, you may think you don't have a problem,''
he said.
   ``Wrong. Even where circulation is going up, net newspaper
penetration is going down. There are no exceptions.''
   Frequently lost in the daily pressure of publishing, Janensch
said, is the need to establish links between a newspaper and the
community.
   ``We all know the answer, but we lose sight of it solving our
day-to-day newsroom problems,'' he said. ``We lose sight of it
wrestling with budgets, performance evaluations and other
administrative matters.''
   ``Do you hear what the people in your community are saying about
your newspaper?'' he asked. ``Do you know what they like? Do you
know what ticks them off?''
   Surveying readers can't substitute for basics of business, such
as customer service, he said.
   ``Readership surveys can be useful, but they aren't enough,''
Janensch said. ``Surveys can't halt sliding readership unless the
editor and the editor's staff are fanatical about getting close to
the community.''
   While many are captivated by national news and big-name events,
most of America's newspapers survive by providing residents of the
community with information they need in their daily lives, he said.
   ``Is your newspaper first and foremost a local newspaper?''
asked Janensch. ``Do you care as much about the expansion of a
local business as you do about the national trade deficit?''
   In addition to building community ties, Janensch said, a
newspaper's staff must reflect the paper's market.
   ``Does your staff at all levels reflect the racial and ethnic
diversity of your target readership?'' he asked the editors. ``Are
about half of your staffers women? Do your staffers have roots in
the community?''
   Without that commitment to community, Janensch said, the steady
decline in newspaper readership will inevitably continue, costing
newspapers advertising revenue, and that in turn tightens budgets
and damages the news product.
   ``The New York Times might be able to survive with 10 or 15
percent of its primary market, but can you?'' Janensch asked
editors.
   The APME is an association of editors from member newspapers of
The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
