<FIRST>r i AM-JetIncident     10-03 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jet Incident,0229</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dutch Police Arrest Liberian Who Tried to Storm Cockpit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said Tuesday a Liberian man
tried to storm the cockpit of a jet on which he was being deported
but was stopped by crew members and arrested.
   No one was injured in the incident Monday, according to a police
spokesman. He said the KLM A-310 Airbus was forced to abort its
takeoff and return to the terminal at Amsterdam's Schiphol Airport.
   The police official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
the man was overpowered by the jetliner's cabin staff as he ran up
the aisle toward the cockpit.
   The suspect was being deported to Liberia following the
rejection by Dutch authorities of his asylum request here, the
spokesman said.
   There was no immediate word how many people were aboard the
Airbus, which seats at least 260 people. The suspect was not
identified, in line with Dutch police practice.
   According to Dutch Television, the man was not under police
guard when the incident occurred. It was not immediately clear
whether the cockpit door was locked.
   Liberia is one of several African nations from where large
numbers of asylum seekers have been flocking to the Netherlands.
   Dutch authorities have said many of the refugees aren't victims
of political repression but come to Western Europe for economic
reasons.
