<SECOND>BC-Bush-Panama,370</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the text of President Bush's remarks
in the Oval Office about the situation in Panama. He spoke to the
media at the outset of a meeting with visiting Soviet Defense
Minister Dmitri Yazov.
   Bush said he was bending his usual rules prohibiting questions
at photo opportunities, ``given the anxiety and the state of the
rumor mill.''
   Bush went on:
   ``The first concern that I have as president of the United
States is the safety of American citizens and of course that would
include American forces that are there under our treaty rights with
Panama.
   ``Secondly, there are a lot of rumors around. We are staying in
very close touch with South Com (Southern Command). We have very
able military officers who are advising us of the situation on the
ground.
   ``But beyond that I would simply add to the rumors if I
commented further. And we are watching the situation with the No. 1
priority the lives of Americans.
   ``There were rumors around that this was some American operation
and I can tell you that is not true.''
   Asked if he was willing to help the Panamanian Defense Forces,
Bush said:
   ``Again, that's part of the confusion. Nobody is sure what's
happening there. People on the ground have the best idea about that.
   ``But I would repeat in the hopes that it be conveyed instantly
to Panama: we have no argument with the Panamanian Defense Forces.
We have no argument with them. We've had good relations with the
Panamanian Defense Forces. Our argument has been, as has many other
countries, with Mr. Noriega who aborted the democratic will of the
people of Panama. And that's where our argument was and that's
where our argument is.
   ``And so if you can use all these cameras to get that message to
the people of Panama, I really think it would be a good thing for
peace and I think it would be a good thing in terms of a historic
relationship between our two countries that I value and that all
Americans want to see improved. So sally forth and do your best.''
   Bush refused to answer further questions.
