<FIRST>r a AM-FatalSwimLesson     10-03 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fatal Swim Lesson,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parents Settle Over Daughter's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEARWATER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parents of a 4-year-old who died after a
swimming lesson described as strenuous have settled a lawsuit
against instructors and a beach resort for nearly $1 million.
   ``We still can't believe it happened,'' said Patricia Myers, who
watched at poolside while instructors huddled over her daughter,
Amber Nicole Myers, after she lost consciousness during a 50-yard
swim.
   Amber was taking a swimming lesson in August 1987 from George
Symons and Michael Hatton at the Tides Hotel and Bath Club Resort
in North Redington Beach.
   According to the lawsuit, Hatton made her swim two laps in the
75-foot pool. During the second lap the child, who had tearfully
complained of fatigue, lost consciousness and stopped breathing
with an instructor only a couple feet from her.
   The mother of another child in the class and an instruction
performed cardiopulmonary resuscitation until paramedics arrived,
but Amber never breathed on her own again and was placed on life
support equipment. She was removed from the equipment eight days
later and died.
   Patricia and Stephen Myers filed suit against the instructors
and Gulf Beach, which owns the resort, alleging negligence. They
settled Monday for $950,000.
   The couple said they will wage a personal campaign for state and
national laws requiring instructors and lifeguards be certified in
lifesaving skills and CPR.
   Brian Harrington, attorney for the resort and the instructors,
said the instructors were certified in lifesaving and CPR, more
qualified than was required by either U.S. Swimming, a sanctioning
association, or Florida law.
   The last thing Mrs. Myers remembers is Amber asking: ``Mommy,
how much longer is class? I don't want to swim the long way.''
   ``I'll always have a problem with that,'' Mrs. Myers, 32, said
through tears.
   Family attorney Bob Carroll said the couple decided to settle
rather than take the matter to court this week because of the
stress a trial would bring. ``They would have been reliving this
thing 1,000 times.''
   Harrington said the hotel is looking at the swim program to see
if changes need to be made. Hotel management ``wanted to get all
this over and done with first,'' he said.
   Harrington denied there were serious flaws with the program.
``If it were so deficient, how did it function for 35 years,''
teaching 8,000 to 10,000 swimmers in three generations, without
another death, he asked.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
