<FIRST>r a AM-WorkSkills     10-03 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Work Skills,0654</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Commission to Boost U.S. Work Skills</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A commission of business, union and political
leaders announced on Tuesday plans to study ways to make U.S.
workers more competitive with those in other industrialized
countries.
   The 34-member Commission on the Skills of the American Workforce
will be chaired by Ira Magaziner, an international business
authority, co-chaired by former Labor Secretaries Bill Brock and
Ray Marshall, and will include New Jersey Gov. Thomas Kean and the
chief executives of Eastman Kodak, Corning Glass Works Inc., and
Apple Computer Co.
   The commission will study job skill development programs in
seven countries: the United States, West Germany, Sweden, Denmark,
Ireland, Japan and Singapore.
   According to Magaziner, the commission's final report, expected
next spring, will:
   _ Urge changes in U.S. secondary schools to ensure youngsters
graduate with job skills,
   _ Call for a ``second chance system'' for those out of high
school and out of work, and
   _ Urge creation of a system to update skills of existing U.S.
workers.
   ``The U.S. is in a race with time. From West Germany to
Singapore, those nations that are winning the economic war have
made the development and effective use of very highly skilled work
forces an indispensible part of their strategy,'' said Magaziner.
   ``The U.S. knows it is far behind in the schooling process, but
it has hardly begun to think about an equally pressing problem _
how to raise the skills of line workers already in the workforce,''
he said.
   Research is expected to take seven months, Magaziner said. The
project will consist of more than 2,000 interviews with plant
executives, employees and policymakers in those seven nations. It
is being funded by a $250,000 grant from Carnegie Corp. of New York.
   The commission is an initiative of the National Center on
Education and the Economy, in Rochester, N.Y., an organization
founded in 1987 as an outgrowth of ``A Nation Prepared: Teachers
for the 21st Century,'' a landmark Carnegie report widely credited
with shifting U.S. school reform toward empowering teachers and
restructuring schools.
   Marc Tucker, author of that report, is president of the
Rochester-based center.
   Besides Magaziner, Kean, Brock and Marshall, the commission will
include:
   Morton Bahr, president, Communications Workers of America;
Edward J. Carlough, president, Sheet Metal Workers of America;
Anthony P. Carnevale, vice president, American Society for Training
and Development; Paul J. Choquette, Jr., chief executive officer,
Gilbane Construction Company; Richard Cohon, president, C.N. Burman
Co.; Badi G. Foster, president, Aetna Institute for Corporate
Education; Thomas Gonzales, president, Seattle Community College
District; Sheryl Handler, president, Thinking Machines Corp.; Rear
Adm. W.J. Holland, Jr., president, Educational Foundation, Armed
Forces Communications and Electronics Association.
   Also, James R. Houghton, chairman, Corning Glass Works, Inc.;
former North Carolina Gov. James B. Hunt Jr., partner, Poyner &amp;
Spruill; John R. Hurley, vice president, Chase Manhattan Bank;
William H. Kolberg, president, National Alliance of Business;
William Lucy, secretary-treasurer, American Federation of State,
County and Municipal Employees; Margaret L.A. MacVicar, dean for
undergraduate education, Massachusetts Institute of Technology;
Sybil C. Mobley, dean, Florida A&amp;M University School of Business
and Industry; Eleanor Holmes Norton, professor of law, Georgetown
University;
   Also, Karen Nussbaum, executive director, National Association
of Working Women; Peter Pestillo, vice president, Ford Motor Co.;
Philip H. Power, chairman, Suburban Communications Corp.; Lauren B.
Resnick, director, Learning Research and Development Center,
University of Pittsburgh; Howard D. Samuel, president, Industrial
Union Department, AFL-CIO; John Sculley, chairman, Apple Computer
Inc.; William J. Spring, vice president, Federal Reserve Bank,
Boston; Anthony J. Trujillo, superintendent, Sweetwater Union High
School District, Chula Vista, Calif.; Laura D'Andrea Tyson,
Berkeley Roundtable on International Economy, University of
California at Berkeley; Thomas J. Watson, Jr., chairman emeritus,
IBM Corp.; Kay R. Whitmore, president, Eastman Kodak Co.; and Alan
L. Wurtzel, chairman, Circuit City Stores Inc.
</TEXT>
