<FIRST>r a AM-RespiratorySearch     10-03 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Respiratory Search,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pool Closed after Lifeguards Fall Ill with Rare Respiratory Problem</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WESTMINSTER, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal health officials will test
water from a city pool closed Tuesday in a search for the cause of
a rare respiratory problem diagnosed in four lifeguards.
   ``I have my fingers and toes crossed that maybe this will give
us the answers we're looking for,'' said Pierrette Ray, the city's
risk-management officer.
   Two lifeguards were diagnosed last month and two were diagnosed
last week with hypersensitivity pneumonitis, a rare allergic
reaction to prolonged exposure to various organic dusts and
chemicals.
   ``They're sick in that they feel tired all the time, just like
if you have a real bad case of the flu,'' Ms. Ray said.
   The four lifeguards also have runny noses and runny eyes. Three
were assigned other city jobs and one quit to return to school.
   ``In my mind there's no doubt there's a problem with the pool.
But we don't know what it is,'' said Dr. Cecile Rose of the
National Jewish Center for Immunology and Respiratory Medicine in
Denver. She diagnosed three of the four cases.
   The national Centers for Disease Control and Harvard University
Medical Center will test water samples shipped them Monday for a
small protozoa called acanthamoeba, which has been associated with
the disease, said Govinda Visvesvara, research biologist with the
CDC's division of parasitic diseases.
   Some types of the protozoa are resistant to chlorine.
   Water and air tests so far have turned up no cause for the
illnesses. Results of the additional tests were expected in two to
three weeks.
   The indoor pool was closed pending the additional test results
and to avoid any harm to the pool's 19 other lifeguards, who will
be tested, Ms. Ray said.
</TEXT>
