<FIRST>u w AM-Congress-Poland     10-03 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Poland,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats Invite Walesa to Address Congress, Outline Aid Package</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa was invited to
address a joint meeting of Congress Tuesday as Senate and House
Democrats announced an ambitious effort to help Poland and Hungary
make the leap from communism to democracy.
   Democratic leaders of both chambers dismissed President Bush's
$219 million package of initiatives in Eastern Europe as a
``grossly inadequate'' response to an historic opportunity to
bolster democracy and free enterprise in the region and to end the
40-year Cold War with victory for the West.
   They spelled out a legislative program _ with a potential total
value of more than $3.7 billion _ composed of loans from
international financial institutions, direct American aid and loans
and a five-year halt in Polish payments on its U.S. bank debt.
   ``Bold action today will be far less costly than timidity,''
said House Majority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo. ``For if we
hesitate, and the opportunity is lost, we will be paying for it for
a long, long time _ in an escalating arms race ...''
   Escalating the partisan attack on Republican inititives for
Eastern Europe, Gephardt said it is ironic that a government which
doubled U.S. military spending to respond to a Soviet military
threat, ``now seems curiously paralyzed, unable to respond to the
possibility of economic freedom, democracy and peace breaking out
in Eastern Europe ...''
   But Raymond Seitz, assistant secretary of State for European
affairs, denying such paralysis exists, said Poland's new plan for
restructuring its centralized economy is ``in many respects a
declaration of economic independence.''
   Seitz told a House Foreign Affairs subcommittee that a Polish
request for a $1 billion loan to stabilize the economy is ``under
very active review at very high levels. There will be a response to
that shortly.'' ''
   The invitation to Walesa to address a joint meeting of Congress
on Nov. 15 was extended by House Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash.,
and Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine.
   Walesa, who had already announced plans to visit the United
States, is expected to accept.
   Both Democratic leaders compared the proposal to the aid
announced so far by Bush, with Mitchell calling the president's
``woefully inadequate.''
   ``The Bush program is grossly inadequate,'' said Rep. John
Dingell, D-Mich. ``We intend to provide the leadership that has
been lacking up to now.''
   The Democratic aid package includes $887 million in new U.S.
economic and food assistance to Poland and Hungary, of which it is
contemplated that $415 million would be appropriated for use in the
1990 fiscal year which opened on Sunday.
   This would include some $125 million in immediate food aid.
   The plan builds on and expands the private-sector Enterprise
Fund proposed by Bush during his visit to Warsaw last summer. It
would help fund a host of small-scale projects, encourage joint
commercial ventures with Western corporations, and work to
establish private businesses in the two countries.
   The Democratic aid plan includes trade credit insurance, health
programs, scholarships and scientific and labor exchanges. It calls
for a coordinated aid effort by the Overseas Private Investment
Corp., the Peace Corps, the U.S. Export-Import Bank, the Labor
Department and the Environmental Protection Agency.
   It calls for the use of the Treasury Department's Exchange
Stabilization Fund to make available up to $1 billion in loans to
Poland.
   ``Our package will instruct the secretary to use that fund for
bridge loans to Poland, which they can use to repay debts, buy the
materials necessary for industrial restructuring, and jump start
their economy,'' Gephardt said.
   The plan would also give Poland breathing space by halting, for
five years, payments on its $2.5 billion debt to U.S. lending
institutions.
   Another element of the proposal would instruct U.S.
representatives to the World Bank and International Monetary Fund
to seek $1.4 billion in bridge loans for Poland and Hungary.
</TEXT>
