<FIRST>r w AM-US-Germans     10-03 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Germans,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Asks For Freer Flow Of Refugees</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Refugees, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration urged East Germany on
Tuesday to work out an agreement with West Germany permitting the
emigration of thousands of additional refugees who have flocked to
Bonn's embassies in Czechoslovakia and Poland.
   But the best solution, the Bush administration said, would be
for the East Germany to establish permament procedures for people
to travel ``without hindrance from their government.''
   Under an agreement between the two Germanys, more than 6,000
East Germans were admitted to West Germany over the weekend.
Afterward, thousands of additional would-be emigrants went to the
West German embassies in Prague and Warsaw trying to follow their
countrymen.
   However, the East German government said the agreement was a
one-time humanitarian arrangement and demanded that Bonn not allow
the second influx to stay in its embassies.
   The Bush administration, through State Department spokesman
Richard Boucher, came down Tuesday on the side of the refugees by
invoking the 1975 Helsinki agreement, a 35-nation accord that
pledged a freer flow of people and ideas between East and West.
   Having signed the accord, Boucher said, the East German
government is ``responsible to meet that commitment.'' The U.S.
official also praised West Germany for providing a home for fellow
Germans.
   But the statement read by Boucher also suggested that East
Germany, one of the strictest Communist states in Europe, could
help keep its people from leaving by undertaking reforms.
   ``We believe that in order to remove the conditions which caused
so many people to flee to the West, the GDR (German Democratic
Republic) leadership should institute reforms which will lead to a
political and economic system responsive to the population of East
Germany,'' Boucher said.
   He said the ``root cause'' of the situation was that people do
not want to live in East Germany.
   ``If you're going to have a way of resolving the situation in
the long run, there are going to have to be political and economic
reforms in East Germany that will make it a more livable place for
people.''
   Still, the U.S. official stressed the view that East Germans
under the Helsinki agreement have a right to go to the West.
Boucher said the agreement specified ``a very clear freedom to
travel and freedom of emigration.''
   On Capitol Hill, meanwhile, Assistant Secretary of State Raymond
G.H. Seitz reaffirmed U.S. support for the eventual reunification
of East and West Germany but said that reunification must be
approached cautiously.
   ``It is correct that the history of the 20th century is a
history in which the unification of Germany led to instability and
to war. History tells us to be very cautious,'' Seitz said at a
congressional hearing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891003-0147 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-89 2023EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Noriega-Charges     10-03 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Noriega-Charges,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutors Anxious to Put Noreiga on Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal prosecutor said Tuesday he was ready and
waiting to put Panamanian military ruler Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega on trial on drug trafficking charges if a coup attempt
resulted in his extradition.
   Noriega was accused in a February 1988 indictment here of
accepting $4.6 million from Colombia's Medellin drug cartel to
provide protection and services for traffickers smuggling cocaine
into the United States.
   He also faces a three-count marijuana-trafficking indictment in
Tampa.
   ``I am ready to try him as soon as his defense lawyers are
ready,'' U.S. Attorney Dexter Lehtinen said Tuesday.
   Noriega's attorney in Miami, Neal Sonnett, said he had no
comment on Tuesday's events in Panama, where soldiers opposed to
Noriega seized his headquarters.
   The Reagan administration once offered to drop the indictment if
Noriega would leave Panama, but that deal fell through.
   Now, Lehtinen said, ``The Bush administration is interested in
trying Noriega, and the major case against him is in Miami.''
   Other federal law enforcement officials said that without a
formal extradition order, Noriega might not be sent to Miami
initially, but could be detained at U.S. military bases. A formal
extradition treaty exists between the United States and Panama, but
it is not obligatory for either nation.
   The 12-count indictment against Noriega in Miami, upheld by a
federal judge in January, also includes charges against Medellin
cartel leader Pablo Escobar Gaviria.
   The indictment alleges that Noriega protected drug shipments
through Panama, arranged for cocaine-processing chemicals, allowed
traffickers to set up a processing laboratory in his country, and
laundered cartel profits through Panamanian banks.
   Noriega also allegedly sheltered some of the cartel leaders
after the assassination of Colombian Minister of Justice Rodrigo
Lara-Bonilla, according to the indictment.
   But at one point, the indictment said, he raided the cartel
laboratory, and Cuban leader Fidel Castro allegedly mediated the
resulting dispute between Noriega and the cartel.
   The Tampa indictment accuses Noriega of accepting $1 million to
allow the importation of 1.4 million pounds of marijuana.
   No one has been tried under either indictment.
</TEXT>
