<FIRST>u w AM-US-Angola 2ndLd-Writethru a0655 10-03 0769</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Angola, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0655,710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Angola Factions Take Their Battle to Washington</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 3rd graf with Mobutu to meet with Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angola's Marxist government and the U.S.-armed
rebels opposing it are waging their battle in Washington's public
relations arena this week.
   The Bush administration is holding open house for both sides,
scheduling meetings with Angolan Foreign Minister Pedro van Dunem _
despite the absence of diplomatic relations with his government _
and a White House visit with President Bush for Jonas Savimbi,
leader of the Angolan rebels.
   In addition, at the administration's urging Zairean President
Mobutu Sese Seko is paying a quick visit to Washington on Wednesday
and will meet with President Bush at the White House, officials
said. The officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
main agenda item would be Angola and the strains between Savimbi
and Mobutu.
   Mobutu, who has helped funnel U.S. arms to Savimbi's Union for
the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA), appears to have shifted
his allegiance in recent weeks, openly supporting Angolan President
Jose Eduardo dos Santos.
   The U.S. diplomatic efforts are designed to head off a final
collapse of Zairean-mediated truce accords reached last June
between Savimbi, one of the largest recipients of U.S. covert aid,
and the Soviet-backed government.
   The truce began coming apart soon after it went into effect, and
subsequent negotiations between the sides on a permanent agreement
ending their 14-year civil war have failed despite persistent State
Department efforts.
   UNITA is demanding free elections and a change in the country's
Marxist-oriented constitution.
   Savimbi, meanwhile, denies claims by Dos Santos that he agreed
to go into exile and to integrate his troops into Angola's army. He
says such contentions are a ruse to destroy UNITA politically after
the government failed to do so militarily.
   The two sides have refused to sit in the same room during
negotiations.
   In an interview after his arrival here, Savimbi said he was
prepared to meet with a high-level Angolan Foreign Ministry
delegation, which is due to arrive Wednesday.
   He also is urging a more active U.S. role in the negotiations
with Angola, similar to the American diplomacy last year that
helped bring about the complex agreement for the pullout of 50,000
Cuban troops from Angola and the granting of independence to
Namibia.
   Savimbi, who received his guerrilla training in China and until
last year got most of his military support from South Africa, is
aided by a powerful array of U.S. lobbyists and lawyers, led by the
firm of Black, Manafort, Stone and Kelly.
   His nearly week-long agenda is packed with meetings on Capitol
Hill, the State Department and White House, as well as with
reporters and with businessmen seeking a foothold in mineral-rich
Angola.
   Van Dunem, the Angola government's foreign minister, is coming
to Washington for only one day, and his lobbyists and supporters
have organized meetings with State Department officials and
reporters to press for U.S. recognition of his government. ``The
U.S. is the only Western country which still doesn't recognize
Angola,'' said Randall Robinson, director of TransAfrica which is
lobbying for recognition of Angola.
   In another salvo between the sides, UNITA supporters led by Sen.
Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, have asked Attorney General Dick Thornburgh to
investigate TransAfrica, accusing it of violating the Foreign
Agents Registration Act by accepting more than $2,000 from the
Angolan mission to the United Nations. ``I certainly never received
any money from Angola,'' Robinson said.
   Van Dunem's side-trip to Washington from the U.N. General
Assembly in New York is viewed by State Department officials as an
attempt to counter the effects of Savimbi's visit.
   A kit distributed by Fenton Communications, the firm that
handles Angola's public relations, includes a list of
demonstrations planned this week against Savimbi as well as copies
of recent newspaper articles critical of the rebel leader.
   Half-page ads this week in The Washington Post and The New York
Times, paid for by the Angolan government, said Savimbi was coming
here to press for more covert aid to augment the $40 million UNITA
is already getting.
   The ads cited an article in The National Review which described
UNITA as having ``a classic Marxist-Leninist structure with not a
vestige of democratic procedures.''
   A resolution introduced last week by 42 Democrats and 15
Republicans in the House calls on the Bush administration to
establish a liaison office in Luanda.
   But the administration, backed by conservatives such as Rep. Dan
Burton, has rejected granting any diplomatic ties until the
government agrees to hold free elections that would give UNITA a
shot at power-sharing.

</TEXT>
