<FIRST>r i AM-China-Defector     10-03 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Defector,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defecting Chinese Swimmer Leaves for United States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CINTY LI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chinese man who was arrested after requesting
political asylum in Hong Kong was allowed to leave for the United
States on Tuesday night, officials reported.
   A government spokesman said Yang Yang, 20, was released under a
discretionary section of the immigration code.
   Yang sought political asylum in the British colony after his
tourist visa expired in August. He said he had joined pro-democracy
marches in Hong Kong and feared authorities would jail him if he
returned to China.
   He got no response from the Hong Kong government, and
immigration officials arrested him Sept. 23 because his visa had
expired.
   A spokesman for the U.S. Information Service said the American
consulate received Yang's application and supporting documents
Tuesday and granted him a non-immigrant visa of limited duration.
   He refused to reply when asked what the U.S. response would be
if Yang asked for asylum.
   U.S.-Chinese relations have been strained since the U.S Embassy
in Beijing gave refuge to prominent dissidents Fang Lizhi and his
wife Li Shuxian soon after Chinese soldiers crushed the student
pro-democracy movement in June.
   Thousands of people involved in the movement were arrested.
   Five days after Yang's arrest, Taiwan issued an entry permit to
him under a policy of offering refuge to leaders of the
pro-democracy movemnt. Liang Yung-chang, director of the
semi-official Free China Relief Association in Taipei, said about
60 other mainland Chinese now in Hong Kong were eligible for
similar permits.
   Xinhua, the official Chinese news agency, issued a statement in
Hong Kong saying Chinese who had participated in pro-democracy
activities in Hong Kong would not face reprisals when they returned.
   Under the treaty between China and Britain, Hong Kong will
revert to Chinese rule in 1997.
</TEXT>
