<FIRST>r w AM-BushAmbassadors     10-03 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush Ambassadors,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush's Pick For Spain Ambassador Criticized But Easily Confirmed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate easily approved President Bush's
nomination of a Florida businessman to be ambassador to Spain on
Tuesday, but some Democrats used the occasion to accuse Bush of
abusing diplomatic posts as political rewards.
   The businessman, 55-year-old Joseph Zappala, is one of several
Bush appointees who have become lightning rods for accusations that
the administration is handing out ambassadorships to wealthy but
unqualified campaign contributors. However, the Senate confirmed
him on a 79-20 vote.
   Zappala, a St. Petersburg, Fla., real estate developer, is not
college educated, has no foreign service experience and does not
speak Spanish. He received an ``unqualified'' rating from the
American Academy of Diplomacy, a respected body which evaluates
ambassadorial nominees.
   But Democrats are quick to point out that he also gave a
reported $126,000 to Republican campaigns in recent years and
actively raised money for Bush's 1988 presidential bid.
   The nominee has shown ``no interest in the people, politics or
history of Spain,'' said Senate Foreign Relations Committee
Chairman Claiborne Pell, D-R.I. ``I am forced to conclude that the
main reason for Mr. Zappala's nomination was his fund raising ...
and contributions.''
   Sen. Paul Sarbanes, D-Md., a member of the Foreign Relations
panel, said Bush has appointed ``an unusual number'' of such people
to head embassies around the world. He said of 58 ambassadorial
nominations Bush has sent to Congress for confirmation, 22 have
been career foreign service officers and 36 have been political
appointees.
   ``To the world at large, this says the United States is not
serious about diplomacy,'' Sarbanes said during debate on the
nomination Monday. ``No other major industrial nation appoints its
nominees in this way.''
   In the case of Spain, Sarbanes noted, democracy is relatively
new, dating from the death of dictator Francisco Franco in 1975.
Recognizing the sensitivity of the position, presidents since then
have appointed only professional diplomats as U.S. ambassadors to
Madrid, he said.
   But Sen. Rudy Boschwitz, R-Minn., defended the nominee, saying
his background ``is far broader than that of many senators.''
Zappala's resume shows he has been an active GOP fund-raiser and
headed local charity and drug-rehabilitation organizations. ``He is
a businessman ... who has branched out far beyond the community
where he began,'' Boschwitz said.
   And Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla., argued that foreign governments
often are glad to host an ambassador who, while not a
foreign-policy expert, is a close friend of the president. ``There
are some indications that the government of Spain is pleased to
have that kind of direct connection,'' he said.
   Zappala barely survived the confirmation process in the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee, which voted 10-9 to send his name to
the full Senate. An exasperated Sarbanes then termed Zappala a
``political throwaway'' and said Bush might as well put the
diplomatic posts up for public auction and use the money to defray
the public debt.
</TEXT>
