<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-89 2102EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-S&amp;LBailout 1stLd-Writethru a0704 10-03 0594</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;L Bailout, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0704,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Scrutinizing Resolution Trust Corp.</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS last graf: `In its ...,' to UPDATE with new dollar figures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress, in its first review of the
two-month-old savings and loan bailout, is scrutinizing ethics
rules written for the agency created to sell failed institutions.
   The Resolution Trust Corp., created Aug. 9 when President Bush
signed the bailout legislation, has gotten off to a fast start,
closing 24 small institutions of the 275 insolvent thrifts under
its control in 33 states.
   The agency is reviewing bids on five large institutions, all
with $1 billion or more in assets, and hopes to dispose of them by
the end of next week.
   But members of the Senate and House banking committees, meeting
Wednesday, will be probing to see if the fast start is creating
growing pains and whether the agency is establishing procedures to
prevent another HUD-type scandal.
   ``We want to be very sure there are safeguards in place against
any kind of special interest activity that would use the side door,
the back door, special relationships, etc.,'' said Sen. Donald W.
Riegle Jr., D-Mich. and the chairman of the Senate Banking
Committee.
   The RTC last week issued an interim ethics code governing the
thousands of independent contractors it is expected to hire to
manage the real estate and other assets it is inheriting from the
thrifts.
   David C. Cooke, the agency's executive director, said the RTC is
trying to prevent improprieties but at the same time avoid defining
conflict of interest so broadly that it is difficult to hire
advisers and property managers.
   ``It's difficult,'' Cooke said in a recent interview. ``Many of
the really big acknowledged experts have potential conflicts. We
need advice on how to sell real estate and the same contractors
that would provide us advice ... are probably advising somebody
else who may be interested in buying that real estate.''
   The code prohibits contractors from self-dealing, favortism and
conflicts of interest and sets up an agency board to rule on cases
that aren't black and white
   In another safeguard, the management of the RTC is split in a
unique arrangement designed to prevent abuse. Policies are
formulated by a Cabinet-level board headed by Treasury Secretary
Nicholas F. Brady. But the actual operations are being carried out
by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., the independent agency
insuring bank and S&amp;L deposits, through a staff headed by Cooke.
   In the first few weeks of the RTC's existence, that structure
led to public squabbling between the FDIC and the adminstration
oversight board. Cooke said the tension was easing, but members of
Congress are still concerned.
   ``The one thing that's troubled me so far is the fighting
between (the FDIC) and the (oversight) board. ... Is that really
resolved permanently or is it just quiescent?'' said Rep. Charles
Schumer, D-N.Y., a member of a House task force appointed to
oversee the RTC.
   However, Cooke said, ``I think we're working that out. ... On
day one, there's a certain amount of tension because they may be
thinking one thing and we're thinking something entirely different.
Time is making that better.''
   In its first two months of existence, the RTC has spent $20
billion: $1.8 billion to close the 24 small S&amp;Ls; $8.3 billion to
handle the five large institutions and several other
not-yet-completed deals; $8.5 billion to replace high-cost
deposits; and $1.4 billion as a reserve fund to handle liquidity
problems at failed, but still open, thrifts, spokesman Steve
Katsanos said Tuesday.
</TEXT>
