<DOCNO> AP891003-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-89 1743EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-HousingMarch     10-03 0844</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Housing March,840</SECOND>
<HEAD>Homeless Converging On Washington For Housing March</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of people have begun
arriving in the capital to petition Congress and the Bush
administration to lift the homeless from the streets and make
housing more affordable for all Americans.
   Organizers remained coy Tuesday, as they have for months, about
the turnout they expect for three days of activities culminating in
a ``Housing Now!'' march Saturday on the national Mall.
   But the breadth of their sponsorship, coupled with a massive
planning effort dating to early in the year, could produce one of
the largest demonstrations Washington has seen in years.
   ``We're saying enough is enough,'' said Washington homeless
activist Mitch Snyder. ``Today the streets in Boston, New York and
Washington look like those in Calcutta. This demonstration is to
provide some will and some backbone to the administration and
Congress.''
   The march and related events, including a lobbying siege of
individual members of Congress by an estimated 4,000 people on
Thursday and Friday, is backed by more than 200 organizations,
including the AFL-CIO, the U.S. Conference of Mayors, the YMCA, the
YWCA, the National Urban League, Catholic Charities USA, the
Southern Christian Leadership Conference and the National
Organization for Women.
   More than 200 show business personalities and dozens of state
and local officials, including Gov. Richard Celeste of Ohio and
Mayor Raymond L. Flynn of Boston, also have lent their support. The
Hollywood contingent is led by actress Valerie Harper and actor Jon
Voight.
   Snyder, head of the Community for Creative Non-Violence, and
Barry Zigas, president of the National Low-Income Housing
Coalition, are among the principal organizers of the march. At a
news conference Tuesday, Zigas repeatedly declined to predict a
turnout, other than to say ``It's going to be a major, major
event.'' He said more than half the participants would actually be
homeless people, some of whom were walking from New York City and
Roanoke, Va. Huge caravans were en route, meanwhile, from Los
Angeles, Chicago and other major cities along the way.
   ``Everybody who is not fabulously wealthy has reason to be
here,'' said Snyder, who in the past has waged hunger strikes to
draw attention to the plight of the homeless. ``We demand that
Congress put its hands back in its pockets and come up with the $25
billion it cut from the housing budget back in 1981.''
   Jack Joyce, head of the International Union of Bricklayers and
Allied Craftsmen, said ``There has been a paralysis of leadership
on both ends of Pennsylvania Avenue on the housing problem. Housing
for the homeless is the most obvious of concerns ... but ordinary
people, working people, simply cannot afford housing today.''
   According to the U.S. Conference of Mayors, there are an
estimated 3 million homeless people in the United States today.
Though that figure has been repeatedly cited as gospel by march
organizers and some members of Congress, it is widely disputed. The
liberal Urban Institute, for example, said in 1988 that the
homeless numbered no more than 600,000.
   Other estimates abound. A recent report by the American
Affordable Housing Institute at Rutgers University said ``the
number of persons likely to be homeless on a given night vary from
655,000 to 4 million,'' and it put the annual growth rate of
homelessness and anywhere between 20 percent and 40 percent.
   Activists complain that the Reagan-Bush administrations cut the
budget authority for federal housing assistance programs by 77
percent _ from $32 billion to less than $8 billion a year _ and
cite that as the principal reason for the growing numbers of people
who sleep in bus stations, abandoned cars, cardboard boxes or on
heat grates.
   But the Department of Housing and Urban Development says that
while budget authority _ the spending limit _ was lowered, actual
spending increased almost 150 percent since 1978. Still, HUD's own
figures indicate that at least 25 million Americans spend more than
half their income on housing. Currently, one in four eligible poor
renters actually receives federal help.
   Some conservatives, including former President Reagan, have
argued that many of the homeless are mentally disturbed people who
are on the streets, not for lack of government or private
resources, but because of recent court decisions which prohibit
them from being institutionalized against their will.
   But the Rutgers study says that ``Unlike the former stereotype
of the Bowery Bum or the lone drifter, today's homeless are,
substantially, functioning adults and families with children. They
are a cross-section of our poverty population.''
   According to the Child Welfare League of America, Inc., between
500,000 and 750,000 children in the United States are homeless.
   Though all participating organizations have vowed their
activities will be peaceful, one of the more militant groups, the
National Union of the Homeless, has threatened to ``evict'' HUD
officials from their offices on Friday unless restitution is made
to the housing budget by those responsible for the department's
mismanagement scandal. NUH leader Leona Smith declined to specify
exactly what the group has in mind.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891003-0158 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-89 2108EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Fusion     10-03 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fusion,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Experts Urge Congress to Accelerate Fusion Energy Project</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leading experts on the potential for
harnessing the energy that makes the sun and stars shine told
Congress Tuesday the government should speed the pace of
experiments that could produce a breakthrough in the next decade.
   Harold P. Furth, director of the Princeton Plasma Physics
Laboratory, told a House panel that government leadership for the
magnetic fusion program was floundering just as scientists neared
the most important experimental stage in 40 years of work.
   ``At the moment, there is no schedule'' for beginning the next
key experiments, Furth told the House Science, Space and Technology
subcommittee on investigations.
   He said that while the United States has the wherewithal to be a
world leader in magnetic fusion research, ``we're suffering from
some kind of psychological block'' that prevents the nation from
making the necessary commitment.
   The United States has spent $5.5 billion in taxpayers' money
over the last four decades in pursuit of magnetic fusion energy _ a
self-sustaining reaction that releases energy when isotopes of
hydrogen are heated to temperatures hotter than the sun's core and
then fused. Magnetic fields are used to confine the isotopes.
   No one yet has proven the process to be commercially feasible,
but many believe it could be the major source of electricity
generation by the middle of the 21st century as the nation seeks to
lessen its dependence on fossil fuels.
   The next big step in fusion research, the experts told the House
Science, Space and Technology subcommittee on investigations, is
building a Compact Ignition Tokamak _ the world's first device
capable of producing a fusion reaction in which enough heat is
generated to sustain the reaction without further heating by the
machine.
   The Reagan administration had proposed that construction of the
Compact Ignition Tokamak start in 1992, but the Energy Department
in recent months has indicated it wants to spend less on the
machine and more on trying to determine beforehand whether it would
work. It has not set an official timetable for construction.
   Furth and other experts said building the $400 million machine
was vitally important to the program, even if the machine's success
could not be assured in advance.
   David O. Overskei, senior vice president of the fusion division
of General Atomics, told the panel that achieving a self-sustaining
magnetic fusion reaction was possible in the 1990s and ``will put
us on the threshold of fusion energy production.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
