<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-89 2039EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AIDSVirus     10-03 0632</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Virus,0647</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctors Find First Western U.S. Case of Type 2 AIDS Virus Infection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first western United States case of a
rare type of AIDS infection was diagnosed in a man who had sex with
20 to 40 women here since 1979, but the risk to his lovers is
fairly low, doctors said Tuesday.
   The man, who hasn't developed AIDS, ``is definitely the first
case I know of on the West Coast'' of infection by HIV-2, a
relative of the AIDS virus which is rare in this country compared
with the main AIDS virus, HIV-1, said Dr. Thomas O'Brien, an
epidemiologist at the national Centers for Disease Control.
   Until now, only seven cases of HIV-2 infection had been
confirmed in the United States _ three in Massachusetts and one
each in Connecticut, Rhode Island, Florida and New Jersey _ and
three of the patients developed AIDS symptoms, O'Brien said by
phone from Atlanta.
   Almost all the patients imported the virus from West Africa,
where HIV-2 is endemic.
   Of the West Coast man's lovers, ``We've identified one
individual with whom he had multiple unprotected sexual contacts
over a long period of time, and that person has been tested and is
not infected with this virus. That is reassuring,'' said Dr. Peter
Kerndt, Los Angeles County's director of AIDS epidemiology.
   A second lover also is uninfected, but officials expect to
locate only two or three more of the 20 to 40 women with whom the
man had sex since he moved here in 1979 from the West African
nation of Sierra Leone, Kerndt said.
   The infected Los Angeles resident is in his 30s, works full-time
and attends school part-time. Officials withheld his identity. He
has refrained from sex since learning three months ago he might be
infected with HIV-2, said Dr. David Ho, AIDS virology laboratory
director at Cedars-Sinai Medical Center.
   ``This man is a pretty decent person,'' Ho said. ``He's had a
couple of traceable contacts and they are negative (AIDS-free). But
he had multiple other non-traceable contacts _ one-night stands.
He's fully cooperative, but he doesn't know these other women he
had casual sex with.''
   A private doctor referred the man to Cedars-Sinai for AIDS
testing, but he wasn't hospitalized, Ho said.
   HIV-2, or human immunodeficiency virus type 2, was first
described in 1985 in West African prostitutes who had no symptoms,
then was reported in 1986 in two West Africans who suffered AIDS,
O'Brien said.
   HIV-1 and HIV-2 both can cripple the body's ability to fight
disease, leading to fatal infections and cancers.
   ``The question that remains is whether it (HIV-2) can lead to
immunodeficiency as quickly or as often as HIV-1,'' which has
caused AIDS in more than 105,000 Americans, killing some 61,000 of
them, O'Brien said.
   The infected Los Angeles man has very low levels of HIV-2 in his
blood, so ``the risk of transmission in casual sexual contacts is
very low,'' Kerndt said.
   He said the man may have been infected before coming to the
country in 1979 or during a visit home in 1983.
   Kerndt said the infected man never donated blood, ``has not used
drugs intravenously, nor has he engaged in any homosexual
activity.''
   So far, the risk to the blood supply is considered low because
blood bank guidelines prohibit blood donations by West Africans,
and because the test used to detect blood infected with HIV-1 can
detect 85 percent to 90 percent of samples of blood infected with
HIV-2, Kerndt said.
   HIV-2 and HIV-1 are equally common in the Ivory Coast, and HIV-2
may be more common in Guinea Bissau and perhaps Senegal, O'Brien
said, adding that HIV-2 infection also has been reported in Europe,
South America and other parts of Africa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
