<FIRST>r i AM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0677 10-03 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0677,0524</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Party Calls Congress for January</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to include Nalec quote; picks up 6th `Seventy-two
percent...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communists decided Tuesday to hold a
congress in January, which could be their last because a poll of
members indicates 72 percent want the party completely reorganized
and given a new name.
   The Eleventh Party Congress was scheduled for Jan. 27 by a
resolution accepted at a one-day meeting of the Central Committee.
The committee also called for congress delegates to be elected
under new democratic rules.
   The party, officially called the Polish United Workers Party,
was established in its current form in 1948.
   After crushing election losses this year, party leaders seem
determined to rename the party and create a broader leftist
political organization that would include socialists and social
democrats.
   ``People from under different shades of the red banner'' should
be able to ``find their place in it,'' party Secretary Leszek
Miller told the committee Tuesday. The party should become ``open
to reality and to the challenges that the future brings,'' he said.
   Tomasz Nalec, who represents a reformist club within the party,
said the full party meeting should be considered ``the founding
congress of a new party of democratic socialism.''
   Seventy-two percent of party members polled over the past month
favor changing the party's name, charter and program, according to
partial results announced at the plenum's opening. The survey
involved more than 1.1 million of the 2.1 million party members.
   Officials of the party, seeking to recast its identity since
overwhelming losses to Solidarity in June's first-ever democratic
parliamentary elections, say it must change to survive.
   Politburo member Marian Orzechowski has said the party should
rename itself the Polish Socialist Party of the Working People.
   The key changes are to be made at the congress, expected to be
made up of 1,000 to 2,000 elected delegates under the leadership of
First Secretary Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski.
   A communist official who briefed reporters before the plenum on
condition of anonymity also said another shakeup in the party's
ruling Politburo was expected. It would be the second since July.
   Miller, discussing preparations for the congress at the plenum,
said the party planned open, competitive election campaigns for
congress delegates in order to get the public interested in the
party's affairs.
   The party is inviting society to ``create the party with us,''
he said, and the party must strive to find an identity which will
give it a popular base.
   ``The question is whether the Polish United Workers Party can
fulfill the aspirations of the part of Polish society which is
left-leaning,'' he said.
   The pro-Solidarity newspaper Gazeta Wyborcza reported Tuesday
that the draft plenum's resolution favored a multi-sector economy
dominated by development of the state-run economy. The draft
opposed privatizing and selling off state enterprises, a chief
economic goal of the Solidarity-led government, the newspaper said.
   The draft also ``obliges all party cells to create conditions
for free expression of different views,'' the newspaper said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
