<DOCNO> AP891003-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-89 2128EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-APME-Hammond     10-03 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-APME-Hammond,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Historian Sees `Community of Interest' in War Coverage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ``community of interest'' between
government and the news media often limits war coverage, a
historian who has studied Vietnam War reporting told newspaper
editors Tuesday.
   Military historian William Hammond has stirred controversy with
his book ``The Military and the Media'' by contending that,
overall, news accounts of the Vietnam War gave a better picture of
that conflict than did official reports.
   But he says the news media passed over some major stories.
   ``The media is much less an outsider from the government than,
perhaps, it might think,'' Hammond told the annual convention of
the Associated Press Managing Editors. ``There's a tremendous
interplay between the government and the media. Not only do
individuals constantly go from the media into government, or from
the government into media ... but there is a community of interest
here.''
   Hammond, a historian at the Army Center of Military History in
Washington, said reporters operated with self-imposed limitations
in reporting the Vietnam War, to avoid burning bridges with
military authorities.
   ``He's going to have to be back over there again dealing with
them to get some more news,'' he said.
   Nonetheless, Hammond said, news accounts sometimes informed
senior military commanders of what actually was happening in the
war.
   ``Sometimes the commander high up the chain of command is the
last one to find out anything,'' he said.
   News coverage often prompted a change in tactics that benefited
the war effort, he said.
   ``In this case, media coverage actually extended the vision of
the commander, and he was able to make a response that was very
important to the overall goal of the American military in Vietnam.''
   But major stories that would have bruised the Army's image went
largely unreported, including the persistent problems of the M-16,
the primary infantry weapon used in the war, he said.
   Far from assisting in the war, that lack of reporting may have
damaged the military effort because there was no call for changes
to the M-16, Hammond said.
   ``The press in Vietnam did not pick up the story with any
consistency,'' he said. ``What happened? The military never had any
kind of a prod to do much about repairing the weapon.''
   The APME comprises news executives of the member newspapers of
The Associated Press, the newsgathering cooperative.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891003-0168 </DOCNO>
