<FIRST>u a AM-People-Hurt 1stLd-Writethru a0742 10-03 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Hurt, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0742,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Rules There Was No Common-Law Marriage</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, `State Supreme ..., to restore first reference
to dancer Sandra Jennings; SUBS 9th graf, ``Let five .. ., to CLARIFY that
State Supreme Court is a trial-level court.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY25</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dancer who claimed she was actor William
Hurt's common-law wife and entitled to half his money could not
consider their relationship a marriage because living together is
not the same thing, a judge ruled Tuesday.
   State Supreme Court Justice Jacqueline Silbermann ruled that
although Sandra Jennings lived with Hurt and had a child with him,
a marriage did not exist, even during the time they were in South
Carolina, which recognizes common-law marriage.
   ``Absent proof of a mutual agreement to be married, an agreement
to marry cannot be inferred from the fact that the parties were
living together,'' Silbermann wrote. ``The contrary is true.''
   She also said the relationship was illicit when it began because
Hurt was married, and did not become legitimate simply because he
got divorced.
   The 14-page decision did not deal with financial support for
Jennings and the couple's 6-year-old son, Alexander Devon Hurt.
Hurt currently pays $60,000 to $65,000 a year to Jennings and the
boy. Before the trial, he refused to increase the amount and
Jennings petitioned for $16,000 a month, which Silbermann rejected.
   ``I am thankful for the ruling received today, which is a
vindication of everything I have said.'' Hurt said in a statement
issued by his publicist.
   ``I felt that I simply could not continually give in to the
pressures that have been constantly put on me for more and more
money and other accommodations from Sandra Jennings and others,''
the statement said.
   Jennings' lawyer said he would appeal the ruling because he felt
the judge was ``madly in love'' with Hurt.
   ``Let five judges who are all men decide this, not one woman who
is impressed by a movie star,'' A. Richard Golub said. In New York,
the State Supreme Court is a trial-level court.
   Silbermann is ``so madly in love with this defendant, Bill Hurt,
that we never could have gotten a fair shake. All her rulings came
down that way. If we had won, I would have been shocked,'' he said.
   Jennings met Hurt in Saratoga, N.Y., in the summer of 1981 when
he was 31 and a rising star and she was a 24-year-old ballerina
with the New York City ballet. Although she knew he was still
married to actress Mary Beth Hurt, Jennings began living with Hurt.
They had a child less than a year later.
   Jennings based her lawsuit on four of the 10 weeks she spent
with Hurt in Beaufort, S.C., during the winter of 1982-83 while he
was there filming ``The Big Chill.''
   Some of Hurt's other movies include ``Body Heat,'' ``Children of
a Lesser God,'' ``Kiss of the Spider Woman,'' ``Broadcast News''
and ``The Accidental Tourist.'' He won an Oscar in 1986 for
``Spider Woman.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
