<DOCNO> AP891003-0169 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-89 1847EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-HUD-Analysis     10-03 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD-Analysis,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>This Time, Proposals to Reform HUD Will Have an Audience</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-HUD Probe, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>An AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many of the reforms Jack Kemp proposed Tuesday
for the Department of Housing and Urban Development were suggested
to Congress more than five years ago by the General Accounting
Office, but fell on deaf ears.
   Lawmakers are listening now.
   Report after report of scandal and mismanagement at the
department during the Reagan administration have made HUD big news,
creating an impetus for reform and giving new housing secretary
Kemp a high-profile platform from which to promote his housing
initiatives.
   Still, the Democratic-controlled Congress is unlikely to accept
all of Kemp's ideas and almost certain to use tales of huge fees
paid to Republican consultants to try to pressure Kemp and the Bush
administration to back up their outrage over the scandals with more
money to house the victims of the mismanagement.
   Kemp was quick Tuesday to credit Congress for many of his
recommendations and hail the bipartisan spirit with which lawmakers
have been investigating past abuses. He was equally quick to assess
the political impact of the problems, believed to have cost the
government more than $6 billion.
   ``This problem has turned out to be, I believe, and will turn
out to be, a blessing in disguise because it's giving us an
opportunity to get back on the right track,'' Kemp told reporters.
   There's no disagreement on that point, but there are myriad
views on just what ``the right track'' should be.
   For example, Kemp proposed eliminating the Section 8 Moderate
Rehabilitation Program. Many in Congress support the program and
were successful in fighting back repeated efforts by Reagan to kill
it.
   This year has brought reports of widespread influence peddling
in the program, allowing millions of dollars to be steered to
former HUD officials and developers who hired GOP constultants.
   But many prominent Democrats still believe that the program is
the best way to rehabilitate housing for low-income families and
the elderly and think that restrictions on lobbying and a
competitive financing process would end the abuses. Many of those
same Democrats also suspect the administration will use the
scandals to shrink or eliminate other HUD programs Congress favors.
   ``It's extremely important we do not allow the scandal during
the previous administration, the mismanagement, the lost billions,
to drive us into giving up the goal, which is to provide
affordable, safe, healthy, reasonable housing for tens of millions
of American families,'' said Rep. Thomas Lantos, D-Calif., and the
chairman of the House subcommittee investigating HUD.
   Ideological fights over housing programs will no doubt continue
and probably will block any major redirection of housing policy in
the short term.
   But the scandals _ Kemp's ``blessing in disguise'' _ and his
involving Congress in the drafting of his reform package likely
will prevent fights over the management aspects of Kemp's plan so
big that they must be settled in Congress.
   ``You can't let ideology get in the way when you have an
opportunity like this,'' said Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., a
member of the Lantos subcommitee. ``People are paying a lot of
attention to this now and there's a lot of momentum I sure don't
want to lose.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   John King covers the congressional investigation of the
Department of Housing and Urban Development.
</TEXT>
