<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia     10-03 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Official Demands Namibia Police Unit Disband</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An official of the U.N. monitoring
force said Tuesday the demobilization of a controversial police
unit over the weekend was not conducted properly and must be done
again.
   Fred Eckhard, chief spokesman for the multinational force, said
procedures used by territorial police to demobilize the former
Koevoet counterinsurgency unit Saturday were ``not at all
satisfactory.''
   Eckhard said only 900 of Koevoet's estimated 1,200 former
members showed up for the demobilization at a northern police base,
and no steps were taken to identify them or ascertain the
whereabouts of their weapons.
   Since arriving in April to monitor Namibia's transition to
independence, U.N. officials have sought to deactivate all police
who served with Koevoet _ which means crowbar in Afrikaans _ during
a 23-year war between South African-led security forces and
pro-independence guerrillas.
   The unit, made up of black Namibians commanded by white
officers, was accused of atrocities during the war and of harassing
guerrilla supporters since April, when its members were integrated
into the regular police force.
   Gerhard Roux, spokesman for the territorial administrator
installed by South Africa, Louis Pienaar, said police would try to
trace the remaining 300 ex-Koevoet members and serve them with
demobilization papers. He said there would be no further
demobilization ceremonies, and added that the unit's weapons were
stored securely at Okave police base.
   U.N.-supervised elections are scheduled for Nov. 7-11 to elect
an assembly to draft a constitution for an independent Namibia. The
South-West Africa People's Organization, which waged the guerrilla
war, is favored to get the most votes but needs a two-thirds
majority to have full control of the assembly.
   South Africa has ruled Namibia since World War I, in violation
of U.N. resolutions since 1966. Last year, it agreed last year to
grant independence as part of a regional treaty that also included
withdrawal of Cuban troops from Angola, Namibia's northern neighbor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
