<HEAD>Protestors Demand Suspected Terrorist's Release</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout with occupation ending; no pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group demanding the release of a
Palestinian wanted on terrorism charges in the United States
occupied the Justice Ministry for eight hours Tuesday.
   About 20 members of the Movement for the Defense of Social and
Political Rights, who entered the ministry at 11:50 a.m., left
after Justice Minister Fotis Kouvelis promised them ``positive
developments'' in the case of Mohammed Rashid.
   The interim conservative-leftist government has said decisions
on extradition and other foreign policy matters would be left to
the administration formed after elections scheduled for Nov. 5.
   Rashid, 35, is accused in the bombing of a Pan Am jumbo jet over
Hawaii in 1982, which killed a Japanese teen-ager and wounded 15
people.
   Extradition has been approved by the Supreme Court, but the
final decision rests with the justice minister.
   Conservative Premier Tzannis Tzannetakis' government is
scheduled to resign Friday and be replaced by a Cabinet that will
run the country during the period leading up to and during the
elections.
   Kouvelis condemned the sit-in, saying the protesters had chosen
to show their support for Rashid in the ``worst way.'' He said
violence would not be used to eject them.
   Rashid has been in custody in Greece since his arrest in May
1988. He first served a five-month prison term for trying to enter
the country with a false Syrian passport and in March was sentenced
to eight more months after homemade knives were discovered in his
cell.
