<DOCNO> AP891003-0176 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-89 1911EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-FlagArt     10-03 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flag Art,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chicago Sues Flag Artists to Test Desecration Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI T. PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten artists who want to display works featuring
the U.S. flag are being sued by the city, which wants to test a new
statute outlawing flag desecration, lawyers said Tuesday.
   ``These artists each have done works that depict the flag,''
said Gwen Osborne, spokeswoman for the American Civil Liberties
Union in Chicago.
   ``Needless to say, curators and galleries were hesitant to
display them,'' Osborne, whose organization is representing the
artists.
   The lawsuit, filed Monday in Cook County Circuit Court, was
moved to the court of U.S. District Judge George M. Marovich after
the ACLU said the case raised questions of constitutionality.
   ``Even though the artists are named as defendants, essentially
we are asking the judge to make a decision as to whether the flag
ordinance is constitutional and can be enforced,'' said Connie
Busceni, spokeswoman for the office of the city's corporation
counsel.
   ``If it is, we'll decide what we want to do then'' regarding
prosecuting the artists for their displays, she said.
   The artists' sculptures, paintings and collages are part of a
two-month exhibit probing censorship of the arts. The artists could
not be reached immediately for comment.
   The multi-media exhibit, called ``Inalienable Rights, Alienable
Wrongs,'' also features poetry readings and film. Bookstores,
galleries and theaters are showing segments of the exhibit from
Sept. 15 through Nov. 15, said Harvey Grossman, the ACLU's legal
director.
   Galleries, fearing prosecution, have refused to display the
segment focusing on the U.S. flag, he said.
   ``These artists and curators must be able to exhibit their works
without the threat of arrest, seizure of their art and meritless
prosecutions,'' Grossman said.
   The ACLU sent a letter Sept. 25 to the city's attorneys and the
police chief on behalf of the 10 artists, who believed they might
be arrested if their flag-related works were shown.
   Instead of responding directly, Grossman said, the city filed
the lawsuit to seek clarification of the ordinance passed March 16.
   The measure was prompted by the controversy that erupted when
student artist ``Dread'' Scott Tyler placed a flag on the floor for
his piece, ``What is the Proper Way to Display a U.S. Flag?'' The
work was part of a student exhibit at the School of the Art
Institute of Chicago.
   Scott's work outraged many veterans and others. Thousands
marched and demonstrated at the museum, demanding removal of the
work.
   The City Council then passed the ordinance barring the display
of U.S. flags on the floor or of flags that have been marked or
have items attached to them. It also prohibits reproducing the flag
on merchandise or containers.
   The ACLU said the law is vague and the wording makes it unclear
what type of artwork would be in violation of the ordinance.
   Tyler, one of the artists named in the suit, does not have a
listed telephone and could not be reached through an artists' group
with which he is affiliated.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891003-0177 </DOCNO>
