<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-89 2151EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SpermBanks     10-03 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sperm Banks,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>New State Rules Ban Gay Men, IV Drug Users From Donating Sperm</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sperm banks in the state can no longer
accept gay men and intravenous drug users as donors because of new
state health regulations prompted by fears about AIDS, officials
said Tuesday.
   For the first time, sperm banks must get a state license and
must subject all donors to at least two AIDS tests before their
sperm is used, said Mary Anne Gardineer, an associate director of
the New York state Health Department.
   ``Women who choose to undergo artificial insemination should not
be subjected to unnecessary risks for serious and even fatal
illnesses,'' she said.
   The regulations took effect Monday and automatically exclude a
person from donating sperm if he has had homosexual activity,
intravenous drug use or sex since 1977 with a person at high risk
for the AIDS virus.
   The same people already are barred from donating blood in the
state for the same reason, Gardineer said.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is caused by a virus that
damages the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to
infections and cancer. It is spread most often through sexual
contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood
or blood products, and from pregnant women to their offspring.
   The national Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta have no
documented cases of AIDS being transmitted through sperm donors,
said a spokesman, Chuck Fallis.
   Gardineer said Australia had one case _ eight women who received
sperm from the same donor, who tested positive for the AIDS virus.
Four of the women later tested positive for the virus, but three of
their babies born through artificial insemination were healthy,
Gardineer said. The fourth pregnancy never came to term.
   New York state has about one-quarter of the nation's AIDS cases
with 25,000 confirmed cases.
   Geoffrey Knox, a spokesman for the Gay Men's Health Crisis, said
he had no problem with the sperm bank prohibition against gay men.
   ``We have the same goal in mind, which is having a safe sperm
bank,'' Knox said.
   The new state rules forbid the release of a sperm donor's name
and address, except in cases where the man specifically gives his
consent.
   Gardineer said she could not be sure how many sperm banks the
state has because they have never been licensed before.
   The regulations don't apply in cases where a person is donating
sperm for a specific person, such as his wife.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
