<FIRST>r a AM-USANetwork     10-03 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-USA Network,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>USA Network Buys 26-Film Package, Including ``Good Morning, Vietnam''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY SHARBUTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cable television's USA Network said Tuesday it
has bought cable TV rights to 26 current motion pictures, including
the hits ``Good Morning, Vietnam'' and ``Three Men and a Baby,'' in
a multimillion-dollar deal.
   USA, which bought the package from Touchstone Pictures, said it
would start airing the films next May. But no decision had been
made which would be the first to be shown, officials of the company
said.
   USA's purchase is ``a reflection of a changing marketplace'' for
syndicated films, said Robert Jacquemin, president of Buena Vista
Television, the TV sales arm of the Walt Disney Co., which owns
Touchstone Pictures.
   ``We think it's one business now,'' he said, referring to
broadcasting and cable. The latter, according to the A.C. Nielsen
Co., is in 51 million of the estimated 92.1 million homes with
television.
   ``It really is a syndication breakthrough for us,'' said USA
president Kay Koplovitz said, whose company last year said it was
spending $250 million for original made-for-cable TV movies airing
this year and next.
   USA's purchase price for the 26 motion pictures pictures was not
disclosed, although sources close to the deal estimated it at about
$50 million. The sale was announced at a news conference here.
   The films, some of which already have aired on pay cable after
their theatrical runs, include ``The Dead Poets Society,'' the
recently-released ``An Innocent Man'' with Tom Selleck, and the
upcoming ``Blaze'' and ``Stella,'' which star Paul Newman and Bette
Midler, respectively.
   According to David Kenin, USA's senior vice-president for
programming, the films face two steps before airing on USA, which
says it has more than 49 million subscriberss and is one of the
nation's largest basic cable services.
   The smaller Showtime network, a pay cable with nearly 10.5
million subscribers, according to the A.C. Nielsen Co., can air the
films first under an existing agreement.
   Then, he said, CBS, NBC or ABC could buy rights to air the films
on their networks.
</TEXT>
