<FIRST>r w AM-US-Greece     10-03 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Greece,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Says U.S. Could Lose Greek Bases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There's a possibility U.S. forces will have to
withdraw from their four major bases in Greece next year, a State
Department official said Tuesday.
   Negotiations on continued use of the bases are expected to
resume after elections and formation of a new Greek government in
November.
   Once the talks restart, ``I don't think anyone can rule out that
the negotiations might be unsuccessful,'' Assistant Secretary of
State Raymond G. H. Seitz told a House subcommittee on Europe and
the Middle East.
   ``I think we're close to agreement,'' Seitz said, describing the
situation at the last session of the negotiations in May. But there
are many uncertainties, he indicated in answering a battery of
questions.
   He said the United States expects to resume negotiations but
``we don't know'' what kind of government will be elected or what
its mandate will be.
   ``The answer is yes,'' Seitz answered with evident hesitation to
the question of whether there was any contingency planning for
dismantling of the bases by Greece's May, 1990, deadline for a new
agreement.
   Greece's interim government said in July the installations must
be dismantled by then if a new pact is not concluded.
   A five-year agreement signed by the former Socialist government
expired last year and the 1990 deadline was fixed for removal of
the bases in absence of new arrangements.
   The current governing coalition of conservatives and leftists
has said it will avoid national issues, including the bases matter,
until after the election. It was formed after the June 18 vote
failed to give any simgle party a majority in the 300-member
one-chamber parliament. The interim government has said it will
deal mainly with scandals surrounding officials of the defeated
administration of Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou.
   Two of the U.S. bases are on the Aegean island of Crete, where
the Navy's 6th Fleet refuels and the Air Force maintains a
communications station. The Navy has a listening post near Athens
and the Air Force has a support group at Hellenikon, outside Athens
International Airport.
</TEXT>
