<FIRST>u a AM-Hugo 1stLd-Writethru a0720 10-03 0786</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0720,0806</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corps to Lift Bridge; Shellfishing Banned, Advisory Against Swimming</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 4th, `Hollings, D-S.C. ..., to explain
FEMA's responsibility; picks up 5th graf pvs: ``GAO needs ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shellfish harvesting was banned Tuesday
and warnings were issued against swimming in ocean water and rivers
choked with untreated sewage because of damage from Hurricane Hugo.
   U.S. Sen. Ernest Hollings said he would ask for an investigation
of the Federal Emergency Management Agency's response to victims of
the hurricane, but Marilyn Quayle, wife of the vice president, said
the agency had been unfairly criticized.
   Crews working to re-establish a land link between the barrier
islands and the mainland hoped to raise the Ben Sawyer Bridge back
into place Wednesday during high tide. The bridge, tilted at a
45-degree angle, has rested in the Intracoastal Waterway for 13
days since the hurricane struck.
   Hollings, D-S.C., who last week called employees of FEMA a
``bunch of bureaucratic jackasses,'' said he will ask the General
Accounting Office, Congress' watchdog agency, to investigate FEMA's
``incompetent'' handling of disaster relief.
   FEMA is the agency responsible for coordinating federal aid in
national disasters. The agency, with a budget of $600 million and
2,200 employees, reports directly to the president.
   ``GAO needs to find out why this agency couldn't perform in an
emergency,'' he said from Washington. ``That's FEMA's job; it's in
the title. They're supposed to manage emergencies, not cause them.''
   Hollings criticized FEMA for opening too few offices to handle
disaster relief applications. About 10 offices are open in the 22
South Carolina counties that President Bush declared disaster areas.
   FEMA spokesman Bill McAda said he disagreed with Hollings'
assessment of the agency's response, but said he would welcome an
investigation.
   ``Our charter under law is for the long-term recovery and
response to the situation,'' McAda said by telephone from
Washington. ``I believe we're doing that and under the
circumstances doing it as fast as it can be expected to be done.''
   Mrs. Quayle, in Charleston to help at disaster and American Red
Cross centers, also defended FEMA.
   ``Everyone's natural reaction is to want everything done
yesterday,'' she said. But ``from what I've been able to observe,
FEMA, very frankly, got a bum rap.''
   Sewage treatment plants in the area are only partially
operational and are removing only 30 percent of the pollutants from
sewage. When fully operational, about 95 percent of the pollutants
are removed before the sewage is dumped into the ocean.
   ``The waters are turning black, and there are fish kills all
over,'' said Wayne Fanning of the state Department of Health and
Environmental Control.
   The swimming advisory could last months and possibly affect next
spring's tourist season.
   Some 10 million visitors were attracted last year to the Grand
Strand, 60 miles of beach from Georgetown to the North Carolina
line, and accounted for an estimated 35 percent of the state's
total tourism revenue of $4.7 billion, officials said.
   The long-term effect on the shellfishing industry is ``going to
be devastating,'' Fanning said.
   Shellfishing also is a multimillion-dollar industry in South
Carolina.
   Hurricane Hugo slammed into South Carolina Sept. 21 with 135 mph
wind, killing at least 18 and leaving 50,000 homeless, 270,000
jobless, and homes, businesses, schools and municipal buildings
damaged or destroyed as far inland as Sumter and north to North
Carolina. In all, 29 people were killed on the U.S. mainland.
   Damage in South Carolina alone has been estimated at $3 billion
or more, with crop damage placed at some $100 million.
   South of Charleston, workers planned to float barges under the
dangling section of the Ben Sawyer Bridge and use Wednesday
morning's rising tide to help raise the bridge that connects Isle
of Palms and Sullivans Island to the mainland, said Army Corps of
Engineers spokesman Rod Ruffennach. Then cranes will swing the
bridge back into position.
   The bridge will be left in position for cars until experts
determine if they can repair the swing mechanism that opens the
bridge for boats on the Intracoastal Waterway.
   In Murrells Inlet, 10 miles south of Myrtle Beach, author Mickey
Spillane examined the wreckage of his home and office, where he has
written detective novels since 1963. One section of a wall was
gone, and first editions of his books, including ``I, The Jury,''
and ``My Gun is Quick,'' had disappeared. Also gone was a
manuscript of a book in progress.
   ``Hey, not to worry,'' he said. ``You get a flat tire, you fix
it, right?
   ``The missing manuscript? No big deal. I'll make it up in two
weeks, ... maybe three. That's how long it takes to write a book.''
</TEXT>
