<FIRST>r i AM-Salvador     10-03 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wounded Salvadoran Guerrillas Seek Asylum At Mexican Embassy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forty-eight wounded guerrillas,
most of them amputees, moved Tuesday to the Mexican Embassy from
the Metropolitan Cathedral they had occupied for six weeks.
   The occupation began Aug. 20 with eight wounded entering the
church and the number had reached 48 by last weekend, annoying both
the rightist government of President Alfredo Cristiani and Roman
Catholic Church leaders.
   ``The cathedral is not a hotel,'' Monsignor Arturo Rivera Damas,
archbishop of San Salvador, said late last month in an appeal to
vacate the church.
   The guerrillas had said they would stay in the cathedral until
they and wounded comrades on battlefronts were given safe conduct
out of the country for medical treatment.
   But Rivera Damas' chagrin apparently changed their minds. Red
Cross vans took the 46 men and two women from the cathedral to the
Mexican Embassy.
   One man who said he lost his right arm in combat, told The
Associated Press through the embassy gate the wounded will not
comment on future plans until arrangements were worked out with the
Mexican ambassador.
   Access to the embassy was barred. Repeated telephone calls went
unanswered.
   Earlier, insurgents denounced Cristiani's speech Monday to the
U.N. General Assembly in which he called for a cease-fire in the
10-year-old civil war.
   Cristiani, who took office June 1, said his government would
propose a complete cessation of hostilities during peace talks with
rebels scheduled for Oct. 16-17 in Costa Rica.
   The Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, or FMLN, umbrella
for five guerrilla groups, has insisted an agreement must be
reached on democratic reforms before the war can end.
   Joaquin Villalobos, a rebel negotiator, said, ``We want
democracy and peace. It must be in that order, because if peace
comes before democracy, it will be the peace of the cemetery.''
   The rebels demand an end to what they call official repression,
an overhaul of the judiciary and reduction of the armed forces.
   ``Cristiani filled his speech with words like human rights,
peace and democracy. At the same time what we're seeing is a wave
of arrests of members of popular organizations ... tortures,
disappearances and murders,'' said the rebels on their clandestine
Radio Venceremos.
   Vice President Francisco Merino told journalists Monday the call
for a cease-fire ``is not a call for the surrender of the FMLN.''
He said a cessation of hostilities ``would create appropriate
conditions for the search for lasting peace.''
   The rebels observed an 11-day unilateral cease-fire between
Sept. 13-23 for the preliminary talks. They accused the government
of taking advantage of the truce to move forces into
guerrilla-controlled zones and arrest leaders of labor and peasant
organizations considered guerrilla fronts by authorities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
