<HEAD>Two House Hopefuls Advance to Runoff; Former Mayor Leads in Atlanta</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with Forbes and White winning runoff
in Cleveland, 81 percent of precincts reporting in Mississippi. Pick up
10th graf pvs, `In Phoenix ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Atlanta Mayor Maynard Jackson took the early lead Tuesday
night in an election to reclaim his old job, while a Democratic
state senator and a Republican political aide advanced to a
Mississippi congressional runoff.
   In Cleveland, where Mayor George Voinovich is stepping aside,
City Council President George Forbes and state Sen. Mike White won
the top two spots in a non-partisan mayoral primary and advanced to
a runoff. And Phoenix Mayor Terry Goddard sought re-election.
   In Atlanta, Jackson was trying to play leapfrog with incumbent
Mayor Andrew Young, who succeeded him in 1982. With 7 percent of
the precincts reporting, Jackson had 1,567 votes to 485 votes for
City Councilman Hosea Williams.
   Although turnout was light, Jackson had said he hoped for a
large turnout so he would ``get a mandate for action.''
   In Mississippi, state Sen. Gene Taylor and Republican Tom
Anderson each won spots in an Oct. 17 runoff, capturing the top two
spots in a special election to succeed the late Rep. Larkin Smith,
the only Republican in the state's House delegation.
   Taylor and Anderson easily outdistanced the best-known candidate
in the race, Democratic state Attorney General Mike Moore.
   With 81 percent of the 372 precincts reporting, Taylor had
42,725 votes or 42 percent to 37,557 votes or 37 percent for
Anderson, a longtime aide to U.S. Sen. Trent Lott. Moore had 22,082
votes or 22 percent.
   With all 695 precincts reporting in Cleveland, City Council
President George Forbes led with 46,493 votes or 37 percent,
followed by White with 31,440 or 25 percent.
   Court Clerk Benny Bonanno had 28,268 votes or 23 percent,
Cuyahoga County Commissioner Tim Hagan had 11,799 votes or 9
percent and school board President Ralph J. Perk Jr. had 5,891
votes or 5 percent.
