<FIRST>u w AM-Congress-Drugs     10-03 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Drugs,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Helms Urges Adding Authorizing Troops in Panama to Drug Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: The Senate will not finish debate tonight, and the following
should stand for AMs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate became snarled late Tuesday in a
fight over whether to authorize the use of U.S. troops against
Panamanian dictator Manuel Noriega, indicted in the United States
on drug trafficking charges, as it debated legislation to bolster
the war on drugs.
   ``We had a golden opportunity to help the people of Panama rid
themselves of a malignancy,'' Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., said as he
offered his plan.
   His offering came as senators churned through a wide-ranging
bill that would add hundreds of new agents, federal marshals and
prosecutors to the war on drugs and place care of crack addicts
under the Medicaid program.
   ``These amendments will lay the groundwork for a new, expanded
drug control strategy,'' Judiciary Committee Chairman Joseph R.
Biden Jr., D-Del., said as the Senate approved the additions.
   Senators planned to put the finishing touches on the bill
Wednesday.
   Helms' proposal would authorize the president to ``use the armed
forces of the United States to secure the removal of General Manuel
Antonio Noriega from his illegal control of the Republic of
Panama.''
   Biden expressed concern about the measure, saying ``I wonder if
it is so broad that we are authorizing the president to declare
war.''
   He said it was possible that ``the Gulf of Tonkin resolution
might blush by comparison.'' The Tonkin resolution of 1965 led to
escalation of the Vietnam War.
   The Noriega proposal followed the failure of a coup attempt
against him by members of the Panama Defense Forces.
   Earlier, the Senate approved drug bill provisions that would
authorize $57 million for 1,000 new FBI agents, $47.5 million for
250 Drug Enforcement agents in rural areas and $24 million for 313
additional posts in federal prosecutors' offices. It also would
authorize more for judges, marshals and probation officers.
   The bill also would place treatment of crack cocaine users and
perhaps other substance abusers under Medicaid, beginning a year
from now, at a cost estimated by Sen. Daniel P. Moynihan, D-N.Y.,
at $300 million.
   Moynihan, the author of the provision, said the price tag would
be comparatively low because care available for crack addicts is
limited in any case. ``There is no treatment,'' he told reporters.
   The bill was designed to help implement President Bush's war on
drugs. As it went into the hopper, the measure would have required
drug testing of persons arrested, jailed and placed on probation or
paroled.
   A state's failure to satisfy the attorney general about the
extent of its testing program could have led to a cutoff of federal
law enforcement funds.
   The Senate, however, junked those provisions in favor of a plan
by Sen. Christopher Bon, R-Mo., providing for a $5 million pilot
program of testing federal prisoners to determine which procedures
work best. Bond said lawmakers were leery of handing the attorney
general the powers in the original plan.
   Senators worked late into the night, heaping additions of their
own onto the bill, ranging from a study of the possibility of
ending the use of disposable needles to earmarking forfeited drug
funds to buy weapons and body armor for agents.
   ``We'll probably pass a lot of these things and then they will
never see the light of day,'' said Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, the
GOP floor leader.
   ``The House won't let it happen'' and the Senate itself might
have some second thoughts before final action, Hatch said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
