<SECOND>AM-Mutilation,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Items Found During House Search Can Be Admitted in Mutilation Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note the following may be offensive to some readers.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Items found during in a search of the home
of a man on trial for the rape and sexual mutilation of a
7-year-old boy can be admitted as evidence, a Superior Court judge
ruled Tuesday.
   Earl Shriner, 39, charged with attempted first-degree murder,
first-degree assault and two counts of first-degree rape,
understood his rights when he let police into his home on May 21,
Judge James Healy ruled.
   Shriner, 39, described as mentally retarded man with a history
of sexual violence against young people is charged with the May 20
attack in which the boy was choked, raped and his penis was cut off.
   Officers seized a yellow strap, a piece of braided cord and a
blood-stained jacket from Shriner's home. Investigators said the
strap and cord may have been used to choke or bind the boy.
   Shriner said he bloodied the coat with his own blood when he
scraped his hand after falling off his bicycle.
   In arguments Monday, Shriner's lawyer, Dino Sepe, contended the
items should be withheld from evidence because they were seized
without a search warrant and by coercion.
   Deputy prosecutor Jim Roche argued that Shriner voluntarily
allowed police to search his home and said Shriner was familiar
with such searches from past experiences.
   Shriner, held in lieu of $1 million bond, is scheduled for trial
Jan. 22.
</TEXT>
