<FIRST>r a PM-DigestBriefs     10-03 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Digest Briefs,0590</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Clean air legislation is gaining momentum in
the House, following a breakthrough agreement that would apply
California's tough auto tailpipe standards to the whole country
starting with 1994 models.
   The 22-0 vote Monday in the House Energy and Commerce
environment subcommittee came after two powerful lawmakers _ Reps.
Henry A. Waxman, D-Calif., and John D. Dingell, D-Mich. _ shook
hands and ended a bitter dispute over the auto standards.
   Waxman, the champion of environmental groups, and Dingell, the
auto industry's best friend in Congress, said Monday they would
oppose any attempts to change the agreement. Their pact virtually
ensures new, tough auto pollution controls because the Senate's
clean air legislation is even stricter than the compromise.
   The auto industry was quick to express its displeasure with the
proposed exhaust standards. Harold A. Poling, chief operating
officer for Ford Motor Co., said the standards ``are not feasible
and ... would improve air quality by less than 1 percent compared
with the president's proposal.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev, decrying crippling strikes
that officials say may force some people to brave a winter without
enough heating oil, is urging parliament to vote for a 15-month ban
on strikes.
   The Soviet president made the appeal Monday at the end of a
legislative debate on emergency economic measures proposed by First
Deputy Premier Lev Voronin, the official Tass news agency reported.
   Gorbachev told the legislators to discuss the proposed ban and
be prepared to vote on it today. He called the ban a ``necessary
measure ... to protect democratization from anarchy and
irresponsible management.''
   A key element of Gorbachev's reforms is perestroika, or
restructuring the Soviet's Union's stumbling and shortage-ridden
economy, and the Soviet leader said that economic transformation is
``under threat'' because of strikes.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ruling that the funding of Texas schools
is unconstitutional will mean a chance at equality for poorer
districts in the nation's second-largest school system, a lawyer in
the case says.
   The state's education commissioner, who had defended the
financing system, called for a tax increase so poorer districts can
``equalize upward.'' But Gov. Bill Clements said more money won't
necessarily solve the problem.
   Monday's unanimous 9-0 decision by the Texas Supreme Court found
``glaring disparities'' between rich and poor school districts,
violating a requirement in the state Constitution for an
``efficient system'' of public schools.
   The court said financing for Texas' 3.3 million students must be
overhauled by May.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five amateur astronomers are preparing for an
undreamed-of opportunity to go eyeball to eyeball with the universe
using what will be the world's most powerful space telescope.
   In a gesture of appreciation for scientific contributions by
hobbyists using backyard and rooftop telescopes, the Space
Telescope Science Institute has offered 20 hours of observing time
on the Hubble Space Telescope to projects designed by amateurs.
   The telescope, to be launched on a space shuttle in March, is a
joint project of the National Aeronautics and Space Administration
and the European Space Agency. The project, based at Johns Hopkins
University, is expected to cost about $750 million and has been in
planning stages for a decade.
   For someone who is not a professional astronomer, the odds of
getting to use the telescope are comparable to George Jetson's
chances of getting a raise from his tightfisted boss at Spacely
Sprockets.
</TEXT>
