<FIRST>a e PM-APArts:Alaskana Adv06   10-03 0892</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: Alaskana, Adv 06,0917</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 06</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri PMs, Oct 6 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Everything About Alaska Can Be Found in New Mexico</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SITKA, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The unassuming facade of The Observatory
gave no hint of the significance of what was inside. But like a
good book, Dee Longenbaugh's bookstore could not be judged by its
cover.
   Inside was a collection that had become a treasure to book and
map collectors worldwide. Longenbaugh's specialty is ``Alaskana'' _
books, maps and prints that tell of the Last Frontier's colorful
past.
   The treasure still exists, but not in this scenic fishing port
and mill town along southeast Alaska's rain forest coast. Sitka and
its 8,000 residents recently lost the best collection of literary
Alaskana to Santa Fe, N.M.
   For Longenbaugh, 55, the move south represents a return to her
roots. She grew up in northern New Mexico.
   ``It's very, very interesting, because I have lived in Sitka for
26 years,'' she said. ``So am I still a northern New Mexican? Am I
an Alaskan? Don't know. Gotta go down and find out.''
   Longenbaugh doesn't plan to open her new store until later this
year. But she expects it will offer more space than the cramped
quarters of her Sitka shop, where the lack of order was enough to
make a librarian faint. Thousands of books were crammed on shelves,
stacked on the floor and buried under desks _ everywhere except on
a narrow ribbon of linoleum that snaked through the shop's two
small rooms.
   The hand-printed signs that separated the books by subject did
little to alleviate the disheveled appearance. Longenbaugh's
passion for out-of-print books long ago overcame any passing
interest in library science.
   ``I'm at the other end of the spectrum from the book dealer who
has thousands of volumes and knows where every one is,'' she said
recently before the move.
   Longenbaugh began to turn her love for books and fascination
with polar-region history into a business 13 years ago. Her
children were growing up and she was looking for something fun and
profitable to do with her time.
   She started trading books from her home on a tiny island off
Sitka's waterfront, but soon realized she needed a store. In 1977,
she rented a small house on a back street and converted it into The
Observatory with 343 out-of-print books on Alaska.
   Today she has about 3,000 volumes on Alaska, 6,000 on other
subjects, 2,200 historic prints and maps, and dozens of reference
books. She began trading in maps and prints in 1979 after a buying
trip to England.
   ``I kept noticing in little towns there would be a little print
and map shop,'' she recalled. ``I thought, `Gosh, I wonder if
anybody in Alaska would be interested in old maps of Alaska?'''
   They were. Alaskans comprised about 50 percent of Longenbaugh's
clientele. About 40 percent were from other states and about 10
percent traded from overseas.
   With virtually no advertising, the self-taught
historian-bookseller built an international business. She remains
somewhat perplexed about how she became so well-known among book
and map collectors.
   ``I don't know,'' she said. ``Word of mouth, I think.''
   Although Longenbaugh hopes to ``go upmarket somewhat'' with her
Santa Fe store, she easily resists being stereotyped as a
highfalutin trader of rare books and maps.
   ``On purpose I run a democratic bookstore. My idea is that you
can come into the shop and you may not see anything you like, and
you can leave, but I don't want you to say, `There wasn't anything
in that place I could afford.'
   ``Good reading is good reading,'' she said. ``If it's an old
library discard, that's OK _ the content is still perfectly good
and it's fun to read.''
   Longenbaugh also rejects the notion that booksellers shouldn't
specialize in their favorite subjects.
   ``The rule of thumb goes, you are never, never to deal in a
specialty where you yourself collect, because you will cheat your
customers by grabbing off the good stuff.
   ``My feeling is, if I dealt with something that bored me I
wouldn't enjoy doing it. Sure, I take one now and then. But I
always figure, there's another copy out there. The customer can
have the next one.''
   A friendly woman with a hearty laugh and insatiable curiosity,
she revels in playing detective for customers seeking a particular
out-of-print book.
   ``It's just so much fun,'' she said. ``Lots of dealers don't
like to do book searches because they are so time consuming. I
charge a dollar and a half, and I'm sure I spend a lot more than
that.''
   Her Sitka customers now have to request that service by mail.
They also can no longer hear her classical music show on the local
public radio station, or enjoy her narration of the station's daily
soap opera.
   ``People like Dee are irreplaceable,'' said Jake Schumacher,
program director for KCAW-FM. ``Her particular combination of
personality and talent is something that is rare even in a big
city, let alone in a town our size.''
   Longenbaugh is touched by such sentiment. ``Bless their hearts,
everybody's being really regretful.
   ``And I'm so pleased, because think how horrible it would be to
live in a place so many years and have nobody care when you took
off.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
