<FIRST>r f PM-TreasuryBills     10-03 0174</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Treasury Bills,0180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Interest Rates on Short-Term Treasury Securities Increase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities rose in Monday's auction to the highest level in several
weeks.
   The Treasury Department sold $7.4 billion in three-month bills
at an average discount rate of 7.83 percent, up from 7.72 percent
last week. Another $7.4 billion was sold in six-month bills at an
average discount rate of 7.92 percent, up from 7.79 percent last
week.
   The rates were the highest since three-month bills sold for 7.88
percent on Sept. 5 and six-month bills averaged 8.08 percent last
June 19.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 8.10 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling
for $9,802.10 and 8.36 percent for a six-month bill selling for
$9,599.60.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index
for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages, rose to 8.38
percent last week, up from 8.18 percent the previous week.
</TEXT>
