<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-89 0107EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ConsumerConfidence     10-03 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Consumer Confidence,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Say Consumer Confidence Stabilized in September After August Retreat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. consumer confidence in the economy steadied
last month after dropping sharply in August, the Conference Board
said in a survey that suggested a recession is unlikely for the
forseeable future.
   The business research organization's Consumer Confidence Index
totaled 115.4 in September, the same as a month earlier, the group
said Monday. The July figure was 120.4.
   The index, covering 5,000 households nationwide, is a
measurement of consumer trust in the economic future, based on
buying plans, job availability and general business conditions. It
is based on a 1985 base year of 100.
   ``The sustained high level of public confidence, despite some
indications that business activity may be slowing, is
encouraging,'' Fabian Linden, executive director of the board's
Consumer Research Center, said in a press release.
   ``Recent consumer survey findings do not show the slightest
signs of recession,'' he said. ``The strong employment situation,
the benign pace of inflation, and receding interest rates add up to
a comfortable economic environment for the consumer.''
   The survey showed that nearly 27 percent of respondents thought
business conditions were good, roughly the same as a month earlier.
But opinion on job availability declined, with 30 percent of
respondents describing employment as plentiful, vs. 31.6 percent in
August and about 33 percent in July.
   Homebuying plans declined slightly in September, with 2.9
percent of respondents saying they intended to purchase a home, vs.
3.5 percent a month earlier.
   But plans to purchase cars rose to 7.8 percent of respondents,
vs. 7.4 percent in August, 7.1 percent in July and 6.7 percent in
June.
   Consumer behavior is scrutinized by forecasters because it can
provide important evidence on the direction of the economy.
Consumerism accounts for a majority of U.S. economic activity.
   The Conference Board is a worldwide business network of
companies from more than 50 countries, based in New York.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
