<FIRST>r f PM-CoelhoJob     10-03 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coelho Job,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Congressman Coelho Takes Job With New York Banking Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Rep. Tony Coelho, the California
Democrat who resigned his congressional seat in June amid
allegations of financial impropriety, says he is joining a New York
investment banking firm.
   Coelho's appointment as a partner in the firm Wertheim, Schroder
and Co. was announced Monday in New York by James A. Harmon,
chairman and chief executive officer of the firm, which also has
offices in Tokyo and London.
   The former majority whip, Coelho was the No. 3 leadership
official in the House. He announced his resignation May 26 after it
was revealed he had failed to report a $50,000 loan from a savings
and loan whose chief executive had set him up in a junk bond deal
financed by the loan.
   Coelho maintains that the deal was proper and that his only
mistake had been an accounting oversight.
   But the resulting controversy threatened to damage his run for
majority leader, the No. 2 House post, and he stepped down
effective June 15 rather than subject his party to further ethics
problems.
   ``I don't know the business,'' Coelho said of his new job, but
added: ``I'm excited because it gives me an opportunity to grow.''
   Coelho said he would be working in the areas of mergers and
acquisitions and asset managment in the company's foreign
operations, offering strategic advice and pursuing new clients for
the firm. Current clients include Warner Communications, Revlon
Group and Southern Pacific Transportation Corp.
   ``They were interested in my ability to make strategic
decisions, which can be applied in business as well as in
government and politics,'' Coelho said.
   He will not do any lobbying for the company, Coelho said,
although he plans to continue personal support for legislation to
help disabled Americans. Coelho is an epileptic.
   He plans also to serve on the boards of several corporations and
to teach university classes occasionally, Coelho said.
</TEXT>
