   Entrepreneur Richard Branson says he has sold a 25
percent stake in his Virgin Music Group to Fujisankei
Communications Group of Japan for $150 million.
   The stake would be the largest holding by a Japanese company in
an existing British concern, Virgin Music said.
   The announcement Monday followed last week's news that Columbia
Pictures Entertainment Corp. of the United States agreed to be
acquired by Sony Corp. of Japan for $3.4 billion. It also marks a
trend of corporate takeovers in the U.S. entertainment industry,
especially by foreign firms.
   Virgin Music and the media conglomerate Fujisankei, through its
subsidiary Pony Canyon Inc., plan to launch a new record label in
Japan to promote sales of top British pop artists in the Far East.
   Virgin Music's lineup includes singers Mike Oldfield, Phil
Collins, Peter Gabriel, Keith Richards, Simple Minds, Human League,
UB40 and Boy George, many of them already popular in Japan.
   ``We could not have hoped for a better partner than Fuji,''
Branson said. ``They don't think just short term.''
   Virgin Music ``consciously chose a partnership which would not
only ensure our future independence under existing management, but
would provide a springboard for our ambitions to become the world's
No. 1 music group,'' he said.
   Branson took Virgin Music private last year, saying he wasn't
happy with the stock market's valuation of the shares, which were
sold to the public in 1986.
   Virgin Music had revenue of $400 million in 1988, making it the
sixth largest record company in the world, the company said.
   Branson also owns Virgin Atlantic Airways, a cut-rate
trans-Atlantic airline.
   Virgin is the latest of independent record labels to be snapped
up recently by big corporations, following a trend in the music,
film and television business.
   Dutch-owned Polygram currently is in talks to purchase Los
Angeles' A&amp;M Records, Herb Alpert's label, for a reported $500
million.
   In other deals in recent years, MCA Records bought Motown
Records for $61 million and Thorn-EMI of Great Britain paid about
$80 million for a 50 percent stake in Britain's Chrysalis Records.
   The consolidation trend intensified this summer when Philips'
Polygram Records unit bought independent Island Records for what
analysts estimated was $300 million.
   A still-independent major label belongs to David Geffen. But it
is closely allied with Time-Warner Inc.'s record unit, which was
one of the chief attractions in Time Inc.'s $14 billion merger with
Warner in July.
   Among big labels, CBS Records was snapped up by Sony Corp. and
RCA Records was bought by Bertelsman AG of West Germany.
   Bucking the trend was MCA Records chief Irving Azoff, who
announced in August he was leaving MCA to start his own label. MCA
is negotiating with Azoff to help fund the deal in a setup like the
Geffen's with Warner.
   Azoff estimated it would take $75 million to $100 million in
funding to launch an independent record label, and said all five
competing U.S. record distributors and several Wall Street
investment groups have expressed interest in bankrolling him should
the deal with MCA fail.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
