<DOCNO> AP891003-0221 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-89 0121EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Zenith Bjt   10-03 0753</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Zenith, Bjt,0780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zenith Returns to Roots But It's TV Future Is Fuzzy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zenith Electronics Corp. is returning to its
consumer-electronics roots with the proposed sale of its computer
unit, but the future of the last major U.S.-based television maker
remains fuzzy.
   Both the North American television market and the stock market
appear to be friendly toward Zenith at the moment.
   But experts say there are no guarantees that the high-definition
television technologies to which Zenith is committed will ever find
a large market, or that Zenith will be able to survive in a sea of
hungry foreign competitors.
   ``It's a good company but it's not a good business,'' said James
Magid, an electronics-industry analyst with the New York investment
firm Needham &amp; Co. Inc.
   Glenview-based Zenith announced Monday it had agreed to sell its
computer unit to France's Groupe Bull and would use the proceeds to
lighten its debt load and sharpen its focus on new television
technology.
   The decision surprised some observers, since the company had
long been rumored to be seeking a buyer for its
consumer-electronics unit, by far the weaker of Zenith's two major
divisions.
   But Zenith received only fire-sale prices for its television
business, so it decided to sell its computer division instead,
which makes personal and laptop models, Chairman Jerry K. Pearlman
told a news conference Monday in New York.
   ``We are a highly leveraged company in two very tough
businesses,'' he said. ``We couldn't do either of them appropriate
justice.''
   Zenith's stock surged $3.25 to close at $17.25 a share Monday on
the New York Stock Exchange.
   Pearlman and industry analysts said the deal, valued at more
than $600 million, would give Zenith a solid financial base from
which to continue battling foreign competitors.
   Pearlman estimated Zenith's total debt at $600 million. He said
Zenith will pay down all its short-term debt and a portion of its
long-term debt with the money from the sale, leaving it with less
than $50 million in proceeds to be used for other things.
   In a statement, Zenith said it would use some of the cash from
the sale to fund work on ``new consumer electronics and component
technologies, particularly high-definition television and advanced
high-resolution color displays.''
   Analysts said high-definition television, which produces much
sharper pictures than today's television screens, is something of a
gamble given the unknown size of the market.
   ``HDTV is only one piece _ a futuristic piece _ of the consumer
electronics pie,'' said analyst Laura Lederman of Duff &amp; Phelps
Inc. in Chicago. ``And it's a piece of pie that hasn't even been
baked yet.''
   Faced with the possibility of a foreign onslaught of HDTV sets,
the Commerce Department proposed last year that the government take
a major role in HDTV research in this country.
   But the Bush administration now considers HDTV just one of
several telecommunications technologies worthy of federal support,
said Eileen Dougherty, a spokeswoman for the National
Telecommunications and Information Administration.
   Ms. Dougherty denied any reduction in the administration's
commitment to assist HDTV's development.
   ``There may appear to be less of a commitment only because HDTV
is now being considered along with the broader issue of
telecommunications,'' she said.
   Another Zenith technology, the flat-tension-mask video monitor,
is the industry standard in the portable computer field, analysts
said, and would represent a significant improvement in television
picture quality if it could be enlarged, with or without
accompanying HDTV components.
   Zenith envisions the flat tension mask as one component of an
HDTV system.
   The deal to sell the computer division, which is subject to
shareholder and regulatory approval, was seen as a coup for
Paris-based Bull, which will acquire Zenith's successful and highly
regarded SupersPort line of laptop computers as part of the
purchase.
   The 10-year-old computer division, which employs 4,000 of
Zenith's 37,000 workers, has been a bright performer for Zenith
during a decade that proved disastrous to the U.S. television
industry.
   But television prices stabilized this year, halting an
eight-year slide, and are expected to rise next year, due in part
to a shortage of glass for picture tubes.
   Meanwhile, Zenith's computer sales have begun to sag.
   Last month, the company announced it was deferring employee
raises as part of a cost-cutting program to combat losses from
slack computer sales.
   Zenith turned a profit of $11.7 million last year after three
years of widening losses, but had a net loss of $17 million for the
first half of 1989.
</TEXT>
