<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-89 0838EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Japan-Sony     10-03 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-Sony,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sony Chairman Stresses Columbia Management Will Remain American</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN MOFFAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The management of Columbia Pictures Entertainment
Inc. will remain American even after the company is acquired by
Sony Corp. for $3.4 billion, Sony Chairman Akio Morita said Tuesday.
   Morita said Sony will leave filmmaking decisions to American
managers just as it has left day-to-day management of CBS Records,
which it acquired in 1987, to local executives. Industry analysts
say Sony has taken a hands-off approach to running CBS Records, the
world's largest music company.
   ``Columbia Pictures and CBS Records will remain in the hands of
American management,'' Morita told a news conference.
   ``We manage our subsidiaries as autonomous businesses and though
we provide financial backing we give complete autonomy and make a
business environment where local people can do creative work.''
   On Tuesday, Coca-Cola Co.'s board of directors gave formal
approval to the sale of the company's 53.8 million shares of
Columbia Pictures to Sony USA Inc., a subsidiary of Sony, at $27 a
share.
   With that completed, Morita said, Sony's tender offer for the
shares would begin Wednesday.
   Morita said Sony has ``no immediate plans'' to send Japanese
executives to work at Columbia, and said his company would work to
allay fears of a ``Japanese invasion.''
   Some Americans have expressed concern that Sony may use its
ownership for ``propaganda'' purposes or may censor films critical
of Japan. Congresswoman Helen Delich Bentley has called for an
investigation into whether Sony's takeover of Columbia will reduce
competition, thereby violating anti-trust laws, Kyodo News Service
reported.
   Critics in both Japan and the United States have raised fears
that the takeover may increase friction at a time when a $50
billion bilateral trade imbalance and rapidly increasing Japanese
investment in the United States are raising economic tensions.
   ``I think it's too bad such concerns have been raised,'' Morita
said.
   He stressed that the takeover was a friendly one welcomed by
Columbia and said he expected the relationship would follow the
pattern of Sony's buyout of CBS Records.
   ``In the United States I spoke with CBS Records executives and
they said `Thank you very much for buying us' and I was very happy
when I heard that,'' Morita said. ``We worked hard to make a good
working environment and they're completely satisfied.''
   Morita said he hoped that rather than increasing friction,
Sony's management of U.S. entertainment firms would set a good
example.
   ``If we ... show the acquisition of Columbia is a success for
its American employees, we can remove apprehensions and concerns
and Americans may no longer feel Japanese are strangers or can't be
understood,'' Morita said.
   He said recent takeovers by non-Japanese firms have not raised
as many fears among Americans. Australian-born media tycoon Rupert
Murdoch bought 20th-Century Fox, and the Australian firm Qintex
Entertainment recently purchased MGM-UA Communications with less
press attention than the Sony buyout.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
