<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-89 0856EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-EuopeanTV     10-03 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Euopean TV,0444</SECOND>
<HEAD>European Foreign Ministers Adopt TV Proposal Opposed By U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUXEMBOURG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   European foreign ministers Tuesday adopted a
measure intended to prompt local television stations to use mostly
home-grown programs.
   The officials, representing the 12 nations of the European
Community, approved the proposal during the start of day-long talks
on a range of foreign policy and trade issues.
   Only Belgium and Denmark opposed the TV plan, according to a
community spokesman, who demanded anonymity.
   The proposal, called Television Without Frontiers, has sparked
sharp complaints from the U.S. government and film industry.
   It sets out the trading bloc's blueprint for opening up TV
broadcasting as part of the move to a single, European-wide market
of 320 million consumers in late 1992. By that date, the dozen
nations of the Common Market intend to remove the many trade
barriers restricting the free movement of money, goods, services
and people.
   The TV measure would enable broadcasters in Europe to transmit
channels throughout the trading bloc as long as they did not
violate certain moral and other standards.
   But it also contained a provision designed to ensure that _
``where practicable'' _ a majority of entertainment programs shown
on European television be made in Europe.
   In approving the measure, the foreign ministers agreed on
wording that, according to the spokesman, says, ``This is an
obligation which is politically binding on member states to
achieve.''
   The United States has urged the community to scrap the plan. The
American TV industry said its European earnings would be seriously
hurt by such a restriction.
   During a European swing last month, U.S. Trade Representative
Carla Hills reiterated the American opposition.
   ``We are not in favor of local content in any context and more
particularly in the province of thoughts,'' she said.
   Local content provisions refer to measures requiring that a
certain percentage of a product be produced domestically.
   There has been concern in the United States about several
community proposals that would appear to throw up protectionist
barriers around the European-wide market in 1992.
   Mrs. Hills had earlier written key members of the European
Parliament, the community's legislative body, to complain about the
TV measure.
   Community quotas, she wrote, ``would be blatantly
discriminatory, patently unjustifiable, and would almost certainly
have a disastrous effect on the U.S. industry's substantial
European earnings.''
   Defenders of quotas argued that European culture was at stake.
They fear a flood of American soap operas, sitcoms and other
programs would tie up the airwaves.
   News, sports and game shows would be excluded.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891003-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-89 0935EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-CommoditiesProbe     10-03 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Commodities Probe,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean Trader Pleads Guilty to Mail Fraud at Board of Trade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former soybean trader at the Chicago Board of
Trade became the 13th person to plead guilty in connection with a
federal investigation into illegal commodity trading activity.
   John Eggum, 47, pleaded guilty Monday to two counts of mail
fraud before U.S. District Court Judge William T. Hart. Eggum
admitted to making a pre-arranged trade with an undercover FBI
agent, said Assistant U.S. Attorney Mark Rotert.
   ``Eggum misled the customer'' by noting a false time for placing
his order and made about $125 on May 19, 1988 on a ``curb'' trade,
after official trading had ended, Rotert said.
   Also, on Jan. 5, 1989, Eggum admitted to making $50 for a fellow
trader to make up for a mistake Eggum had made, Rotert said.
   ``He deliberately sold at a price below what the lot was
trading,'' he said. ``He used the customer order to repay another
trader.''
   The charges carry a maximum penalty of 10 years in prison and a
$500,000 fine, but prosecutors have said they will seek lighter
sentences for those who agreed to cooperate.
   The trader to whom Eggum paid the $50 was Harry Patten III, who
already has entered a guilty plea for two counts of violation of
the Commodities Exchange Act.
   The FBI spent 2{ years investigating fraudulent trading at the
BOT and Chicago Mercantile Exchange. In all, 46 traders and a clerk
were indicted. Thirteen people have pleaded guilty, and three have
not yet entered pleas. The rest have pleaded innocent.
</TEXT>
