<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-89 1103EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-KodakVenture     10-03 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kodak Venture,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kodak Announces Joint Venture With Finnish Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastman Kodak Co. and a Finnish company
will merge their biotechnology operations into a jointly operated
bio-products company, Kodak officials said today.
   The company will be a 50-50 joint venture, with headquarters in
Rochester, Kodak spokesman Paul Allen said. It will employ 300
workers in the United States and Europe, all existing employees of
the two companies, he said. Sales are expected to exceed $50
million a year.
   The new company will include Kodak's Bio-Products Division and
the bio-products business of the Helsinki-based Cultor Ltd.,
formerly known as Finnish Sugar Co. Ltd. Cultor is a publicly held
company with sales of $922 million in 1988.
   Kodak did not release financial details of the joint venture.
Allen said the move was part of Kodak's plan to focus on its core
businesses and either divest or find new ways to manage other
businesses.
   The agreement includes Kodak operations in Rochester and in
Cedar Rapids, Iowa, where a large-scale fermentation plant is under
construction.
   One of the biggest products of Kodak's bio-products division is
Snomax, an artificial snow maker. Cultor's bio-products division
manufactures industrial enzymes and biochemicals.
   ``This joint venture will allow both partners to leverage their
existing commitment to biotechnology, maintain their access to
important technology and gain an established customer base,'' said
Kodak Vice President Dennis DeLeo.
   Jose J. Coronas, general manager and vice president of Kodak's
bio-products division, was named president and chief executive
officer of the joint venture.
</TEXT>
