<FIRST>r f PM-CoalStrike 1stLd-Writethru f0051 10-03 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coal Strike, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0051,0403</SECOND>
<HEAD>UMW Calls Selective Strikes, Blocks Non-Union Coal Trucks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with tires flattened, windshields
broken. Picks up 2nd graf, A striking ... A version moving on general news
wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROB WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROBINSON CREEK, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Windshields were smashed and tires
flattened today on a picket line set up in support of the United
Mine Workers strike against Pittston Coal Group.
   More than 350 miners in Kentucky and West Virginia walked out
Monday at mines filling Pittston orders.
   At the Rob Fork Mining Co., State Police said ``jackrocks,'' or
bent roofing nails welded together, were used to flatten the tires
of at least three coal trucks, a management employee's pickup and a
State Police cruiser. Two passing coal trucks had windshields
smashed.
   Nearly 200 men in camouflage congregated around the entrance to
Rob Fork, where the strike affects 50 miners. As the crowd parted
to allow foremen to drive through, a faint ringing could be heard
as jackrocks dropped on the pavement.
   State Police said no immediate arrests were made.
   A striking miner was hit by a non-union coal truck attempting to
cross a picket line Monday, but he was not seriously hurt. The
incident set off a four-hour confrontation between miners and a
convoy of non-union trucks poised to cross the line to unload their
coal. The standoff ended with the trucks driving away.
   State Police dispatched 38 troopers, but there were no arrests
and no reported problems at other picket lines in Kentucky or West
Virginia.
   UMW President Richard Trumka ordered selective strikes at two
mines in Kentucky and five in West Virginia to block shipments of
coal the union contended were bound for the Pittston Coal Group for
processing. Pittston is the nation's largest coal exporter.
   About 1,700 union members in Virginia, West Virginia and
Kentucky have been on strike against Pittston since April 5 after
working more than a year without a contract. The dispute centers on
health and pension benefits and job security.
   About 250 UMW employees walked off the jobs at Sunglo Mining Co.
and Rob Fork Mining, both based in southern Pike County. Just
across the state line in Logan County, W.Va., the union targeted
M&amp;H Coal Co., War Eagle Construction Co., Gar Coal Co., Auger
Resources and Can Run Coal Co.
</TEXT>
