<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-89 1224EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-McCaw     10-03 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-McCaw,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>McCaw Buying Half-Interest In NYC Cellular; Selling Southern Properties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KIRKLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McCaw Cellular Communications Inc. said
today it was acquiring a half-interest in a New York City cellular
franchise and selling interests in three Southern states to Contel
Cellular Inc.
   The first agreement could lead to McCaw gaining sole control
over one of the two cellular-telephone franchises in New York, the
nation's biggest market.
   The second, covering 13 mobile-telephone franchises in Alabama,
Kentucky and Tennessee, would make the Contel Corp. subsidiary the
nation's seventh-largest cellular phone company, according to a
statement issued by McCaw, the largest.
   The statement said McCaw signed an agreement to acquire the
Metromedia Co. interest in one of two New York cellular franchises
for $1.9 billion in cash, about $275 per ``pop,'' subject to a
45-day right of first refusal by LIN Broadcasting Corp.
   A pop is an industry yardstick obtained by multiplying a market
area population by the percentage ownership of a cellular company
serving the market. Two cellular franchises, one for the local
telephone company and one for an independent operation like McCaw,
are available in each market.
   The Metromedia deal would give McCaw a 50 percent voting
interest and 45.67 percent equity interest in the New York
franchise.
   LIN holds a 50 percent voting interest and 45 percent equity
interest in the franchise, which would be controlled entirely by
McCaw if the LIN acquisition goes through.
   McCaw's separate $110-a-share cash tender offer for the
approximately 53 million shares in LIN, a deal amounting to $250 to
$265 a pop, has been extended to Oct. 13. McCaw, LIN's largest
shareholder with a 10 percent interest, has been tendered more than
8 million shares, said Tom Campo at Adams &amp; Rinehart, representing
McCaw in New York.
   The Contel agreement would provide McCaw about $1.3 billion in
cash, about $205 a pop, subject to closing price adjustments.
   The Metromedia deal covers about 6.8 million pops and the Contel
deal about 6.1 million pops.
   These are ``two more steps toward achieving our longstanding
strategic objective of creating a national cellular network that
will give American consumers an independent alternative to
traditional providers of telephone service,'' McCaw Chairman Craig
O. McCaw said.
   He described Contel as ``a fellow independent with whom we have
had a long and mutually beneficial relationship.''
   McCaw, based in this Seattle suburb, operates in 127 areas with
a total of 50 million pops in 26 states, including major regional
systems along the West Coast and in the Rocky Mountains, Northeast,
Florida and Texas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
