<FIRST>d f BC-RadioPurchase     10-03 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Radio Purchase,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Great American Announces Purchase of Two FM Radio Stations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Great American Broadcasting Co. says it has
agreed to buy FM radio stations in Denver and Tampa, Fla., and will
seek a waiver to operate the Tampa station in a market where the
company operates a television station.
   Great American did not disclose what it will pay Sandusky Radio
for the two stations, KBPI in Denver and WKRL in Tampa. The
purchase brings to 12 the number of FM stations Great American owns.
   ``We are looking forward to entering the Denver radio market.
Our former company, Taft Broadcasting, owned radio stations in
Tampa and we are pleased that Great American Broadcasting will
return to that outstanding radio market,'' Carl J. Wagner, Great
American broadcast group president, said Monday in announcing the
purchase.
   Great American sold its previous Tampa stations when it acquired
WTSP-TV in 1985. If the Federal Communications Commission approves
the purchase of WKRL, it will be the second time Great American has
taken advantage of a more liberal FCC policy toward common
ownership of TV and radio stations within a single market.
   The FCC relaxed waiver standards earlier this year, saying it
would look favorably on applications in Top 25 markets with a
diversity of independent broadcast voices.
   In applying for a waiver earlier this year for Cincinnati and
Kansas City, Great American cited numerous operating efficiencies
gained from having both TV and radio stations in a market. The FCC
granted waivers in both cases, although Cincinnati and Kansas City
rank just below the top 25 markets.
