<FIRST>r f AM-NomuraChairman     10-03 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nomura Chairman,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nomura Names American Co-Chairman of U.S. Operation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's Nomura Securities Co. Tuesday named an
American veteran of Wall Street as co-chairman of its U.S.
securities operation, a step toward giving it an American identity
and management style.
   Max C. Chapman Jr., the 46-year-old former president and chief
executive of Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co. Inc., said he hoped to put a
Wall Street stamp on the U.S. operations of the world's largest
securities firm.
   ``I believe Nomura is deadly serious about trying to find a way
to marry their system and the good parts of the American system
together,'' he said in a telephone interview.
   Chapman _ who served as a captain in the Marine Corps Reserve
and played football four years at the University of North Carolina
_ will share the top job at Nomura with the current chairman,
Katsuya Takanashi.
   Nomura has invested heavily in its New York operation but has
yet to show consistent success. Its U.S. operations lost about $18
million in the year ended Sept. 30, 1988, and Nomura has reduced
its broker-dealer staff to 550 from a peak of 650 before the 1987
stock market crash, the company said.
   Chapman, who spent his entire career at Kidder, said he resigned
from the firm earlier this year after being passed over for the job
of chief executive of Kidder's parent company, Kidder, Peabody
Group Inc., which is majority owned by General Electric Co.
   Nomura is the last of Japan's big four securities firms to have
an American in the rank of co-chairman or vice chairman. Chapman
will serve as co-chairman of both Nomura Securities International
Inc. and Nomura Holding America Inc.
   Nomura's main business in the United States is funneling money
from Japanese investors into the U.S. stock and bond markets. It
also works with Japanese companies doing business in the United
States. Its goal is to pick up more American customers,
particularly corporations that need sophisticated financial
services.
   Chapman said the United States has the world's most efficient
financial markets and he believes he can help spread American
innovations to other markets, including Tokyo's.
   ``Someone had to satisfy me that there was a sincere desire to
modify and work together, to build an American-type firm within a
Japanese organization,'' Chapman said. ``That will determine the
success of many multinationals, to find bridge between cultures and
styles.''
</TEXT>
