<HEAD>Crop Futures Finish Narrowly Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures prices advanced while other grain
and soybean futures closed narrowly mixed Tuesday on the Chicago
Board of Trade.
   The modest advance in the wheat market was linked in part to
expectations that the Agriculture Department eventually will accept
an Egyptian bid for 500,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized
prices.
   The USDA rejected an Egyptian bid Tuesday morning, but analysts
said Egypt had come back with a higher bid.
   Corn and soybean futures opened lower and stayed on the
defensive for most of the session. The selling reflected harvest
pressure and profit-taking after a strong rally in the previous
session.
   A National Weather Service six- to 10-day outlook issued late
Monday called for little or no rain for the Midwestern corn and
soybean country during the first four day of next week.
   Corn and soybean harvesting advanced at a strong pace last week
under ideal weather conditions, according to an Agriculture
Department report that showed 16 percent of the corn crop and 18
percent of the soybean crop harvested as of Sunday compared to 10
percent and 4 percent, respectively, a week earlier.
   At the close, wheat futures were 1\ cents to 3 cents higher with
the contract for delivery in December at $4.09} a bushel; corn
futures were { cent lower to { cent higher with December at $2.41 a
bushel; oats were unchanged to 1 cent higher with December at
$1.47} a bushel; soybeans were 1{ cents lower to 2 cents higher
with November at $5.77 a bushel.
