<DOCNO> AP891003-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-89 1540EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Zenith Bjt   10-03 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Zenith, Bjt,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zenith Faces Fuzzy Future in TV Business</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zenith Electronics Corp. is making the right move
by giving up its global leadership in the laptop computer market
but its success in the cutthroat television business is far from
assured, industry experts say.
   The outlook for higher TV prices bodes well in the near term for
Zenith, which is the last major TV manufacturer based in the United
States and the second-biggest seller of color TVs.
   But Zenith's survival in consumer electronics over the long haul
depends on its ability to develop innovative products while keeping
its costs low and its public profile high.
   ``It's going to be a grunt and grind to do this thing,'' Robert
Johnson, an analyst with the Houston-based brokerage firm Rotan
Mosle Inc., said Tuesday. ``But now they've got the cash to do it.''
   Zenith announced on Monday it had agreed to sell its computer
division, which includes Zenith Data Systems and the
build-it-yourself Heath Co., to France's Groupe Bull for as much as
$635 million.
   Zenith will use the proceeds to eliminate most of its burdensome
debt load. The Glenview-based company will have an after-tax gain
of $22 million, Chairman Jerry K. Pearlman said Monday.
   Zenith Data Systems sold $1.4 billion worth of computers last
year and is the world's larget seller of battery-powered laptop
computers, with 27.6 percent of the world market, according to
Dataquest, a high-technology marketing research firm.
   But in the past year, other major computer makers have
introduced laptop models that compete with Zenith's for both
consumer and defense-contract business.
   Faced with tough competition in both computers and televisions
and unable to finance both, analysts say, Zenith was forced to
choose between borrowing more money or selling part of the company.
   Unable to find a buyer willing to pay more than about $200
million for its consumer-electronics unit, Zenith opted out of the
more salable computer business instead.
   ``I thought it was something they should do but I wasn't sure
they would they would do it,'' said Mark Hassenberg of Donaldson,
Lufkin &amp; Jenrette, one of many analysts who applauded the decision.
   According to Television Digest, a publication that tracks the TV
industry, Zenith ranked second to French-owned RCA in sales of 1989
model color TVs to U.S. dealers. But its share of the market has
slipped to 12 percent from 18.5 percent over the past seven years
while such competitors as Sharp, Mitsubishi and Toshiba have
steadily gained market share.
   Pearlman said Zenith's consumer electronics business was
profitable in 1988 excluding interest costs and is expected to be
$15 million more profitable than that in 1989, again excluding
interest costs.
   He also emphasized Zenith's commitment to high-definition
television, using sharper-picture technology that some see as the
future of TV.
   But analysts said HDTV is still several years away. And
prospects for higher TV prices after nearly a decade of decline are
tied to a continued shortage of glass for picture tubes and
continued strong demand from China.
   The Zenith that emerges after the computer-division sale will
have lots of cash and not much debt, which could make it an
attractive takeover target, some analysts believe.
   But other say foreign television makers, the most likely
suitors, would be reluctant to bid for America's last TV maker.
That was what made it difficult to sell the television business in
the first place.
   ``It's easier for a foreign company to buy the computer business
because there are a lot of other U.S. computer businesses,'' said
analyst Laura Lederman of Duff &amp; Phelps Inc. in Chicago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
