<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-89 2032EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Toro-Lawn-Boy     10-03 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Toro-Lawn-Boy,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Toro To Spend $85 million For Lawn Boy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Toro Co. has cut an $85 million deal to buy
the Lawn-Boy subsidiary of Outboard Marine Corp., a move that will
trim Toro's earnings by up to 25 percent for fiscal 1990 but double
the company's sales of walk-behind power mowers, Toro announced
Tuesday.
   The transaction is subject to government antitrust approval
because the deal would give Bloomington-based Toro about 15 percent
of the national market share in walk-behind power mowers, said
Dennis Himan, a Toro spokesman.
   ``We don't see it as a significant item,'' Himan said of the
antitrust scrutiny.
   Lawn-Boy Inc., based in Plymouth, Wis., had sales in fiscal 1988
of $153 million. The Wisconsin plant makes lawn and garden tillers,
snow throwers and space heaters. Lawn-Boy mowers are assembled at a
plant in Sardis, Miss., and engines for the mowers are made in
Oxford, Miss.
   Himan said the company has no immediate plans to alter
manufacturing locations or make layoffs.
   But Frank Rolfes, an analyst for Minneapolis-based Dain Bosworth
Inc., said he expects there to be some consolidation of operations.
   Toro, which also makes snow throwers, irrigation equipment and
other outdoor maintenance equipment, had sales in fiscal 1989 of
$643.5 million.
</TEXT>
