<FIRST>r f BC-Intel-Ireland     10-03 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Intel-Ireland,0195</SECOND>
<HEAD>Intel Announces Personal Computer Component Factory Near Dublin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Intel Corp. announced Tuesday it will
build a factory near Dublin, Ireland, to build circuit boards for
personal computers.
   The boards and other parts will be sold to European companies
for assembly into personal computers under their own labels, Intel
said. Intel also plans over 10 years to add plants for making chip
wafers and computer components, spokeswoman Pam Pollace said.
   The facility is set for completion in a year and will employ
about 400 people.
   In addition to its $400 million capital investment, Intel is
committing $300 million to training, research and development in
Ireland during the next 10 years.
   ``Europe is a very important market for Intel. It represents
almost a quarter of our annual revenues,'' said Gordon Moore,
chairman of the Santa Clara-based semiconductor company.
   John O'Brien of the Ireland Industrial Development Authority
said the Intel action is the latest in a series of such moves by
high-tech companies from the United States.
   Ireland's electronics industry boasts $5 billion in annual sales
and a workforce of 25,000.
</TEXT>
