<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-89 1720EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Gillette     10-03 0813</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gillette,0845</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gillette Introduces New Razor</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY16</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gillette Co. unveiled a new razor Tuesday and
said it would support it with a $175 million multinational sales
and marketing campaign, which the company said would be the biggest
ever in the shaving industry.
   But analysts said the company could nick itself in the
pocketbook if consumers don't take to the higher-priced product,
which Gillette is billing as the biggest shaving advance in 20
years.
   The silver and black razor, called Sensor, and featuring two
spring- mounted, ultra-thin blades, will be sold starting in
January at an introductory price of $3.75.
   ``We want to make sure people are not inhibited from using it
because of a high price for trial,'' said Peter Hoffman, vice
president of marketing for Gillette.
   The system's refill cartridges will cost 25 percent more than
similar blades now on the market, Hoffman said, and double the cost
of disposable razors.
   Hoffman said using the Sensor system would cost about $20 a
year, compared with about $16 for Gillette's Atra Plus and about
$10 for disposable razors.
   The new product will be promoted in 19 North Atlantic countries,
with about $80 million of the $175 million to be spent in the
United States.
   In trading Tuesday on the New York Stock Exchange, Gillette's
stock rose $1 to $47.87{ a share. Its stock price has surged from
about $33 a share last December, partly in anticipation of the new
product.
   ``The big concern would be `Can consumers tell the difference
between the new system and the old?''' said Bonita Austin, analyst
with the investment concern Wertheim Schroder. ``Also, it will be
more expensive to the consumer, so will the margins be as good as
other products?''
   Gillette officials said last week that the new razor was
developed over the course of about 10 years at a cost of some $200
million.
   Sensor is similar to Gillette's Atra brand, which has a
pivoting, twin-blade razor head. However, Sensor's design also
enables each spring-cushioned blade to move independently, which
Gillette says allows it to hug the skin without digging in. The
Atra Plus, with two cartridges, sells for about $4.
   Many analysts declined to comment on the new product before they
had the opportunity to view it first-hand. But most agreed the
production costs were high.
   ``They spent lot of money on it,'' said Brenda Landry, analyst
with the investment firm Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. ``But historically
when Gillette has brought out a new blade it has been successful.''
   ``Market share will be critical,'' Wertheim's Austin said.
``They will need to take enough market share to justify the
expenses.''
   Gillette said it holds 18 patents on the product and four others
are pending.
   Landry said the company will license the razors eventually to
make a compatible blade ``but it won't be this coming year.''
   Other razor companies were quick to point out the benefits of
their own products and find fault with the new razor.
   ``You're still putting cold steel on your face which I
understood was done away in a number of countries when they did
away with the guillotine. It is not the modern away of shaving,''
said Victor Kiam, president of Remington Products Inc., which has
aout 40 percent of the electric shaver market.
   Kiam added that the new product could benefit his company.
   ``What Gillette is trying to do is trade people up from
disposables to systems,'' he said. ``We're in the upper end of the
market and therefore it should help the growth of that entire
segment.''
   Warner-Lambert Co., which makes Schick razors, cited the new
razor's expected higher retail price. Schick's Ultrex Plus and Slim
Twin razors sell for under $3.
   ``With Sensor, Gillette is asking consumers to pay a
significantly higher premium price ... '' said Ray LeFebvre,
president of Warner-Lambert's consumer health products unit.
   LeFebvre also said that Schick's total market share has risen
while Gillette's has declined.
   ``If Gillette is indeed `The best a man can get,''' referring to
Gillette's advertising slogan, ``their recent sales don't support
it.''
   Gillette said the new product was simultaneously launched in the
United States, Canada and Europe, the first such international
marketing blitz for the company.
   Gillette has interests in toiletries and writing products, but
its biggest stake is in razors, where it controls more than 60
percent of the world market.
   Analysts have said the new product would help expand market
share and improve earnings for Boston-based Gillette, which fended
off takeover attempts in recent years but had to weather major
restructurings in the process.
   The company undertook a major restructuring after turning down a
$4.12 billion Revlon Group Inc. buyout offer in November 1986. Last
year, Gillette repurchased 15.6 million of its shares to head off
an attempted takeover by Coniston Partners of New York.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
