<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-89 1758EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     10-03 0717</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0743</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coffee Futures Sink With No Quotas In Sight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Coffee futures prices sank to new life-of-contract lows Tuesday
on New York's Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa Exchange after Brazil's chief
coffee executive said he saw no chance for a return to
international price supports until next year.
   On other commodity markets, livestock futures advanced; precious
metals declined, energy futures rose; and grains and soybeans were
mixed.
   Futures prices for green, unroasted coffee settled 3.51 cents to
4.03 cents lower with the contract for delivery in December at
76.50 cents.
   All contracts established new lifetime lows during the session
but none fell below 74.80 cents, the 14-year low established Aug.
14 by the now-expired September contract.
   The heaviest selling occurred early in the session after Jorio
Dauster, president of the Brazilian Coffee Institute, said he saw
no possibility of a new International Coffee Agreement before next
March, when the new Brazilian president takes office.
   Dauster made the remarks to reporters covering an International
Coffee Organization meeting in London. The representatives of 41
coffee exporting countries and 18 importing countries will wrap up
their two-week session on Friday.
   Brazil, the world's largest coffee producer, wields a heavy bat
at the talks. Brazil's reluctance to accept a lower coffee export
quota was one of the factors that led to a breakdown of the coffee
price support system three months ago.
   ``We should not rush into new negotiations unless we see that
the elements that led us to deadlock have been removed,'' Dauster
told reporters at a news conference.
   Few observers expect the London meeting to produce a new
price-support mechanism to succeed the export quotas that were
suspended July 4, precipitating a 30 percent drop in coffee prices.
   But Dauster's remarks reinforced perceptions that the coffee
market is headed lower still.
   Esther Eskenasy, a market analyst with Cargill Investor Services
Inc., said coffee-producing countries continue to underprice each
other in a battle for market share, eliminating an incentive for
coffee roasters to buy in large quantity.
   ``They are just buying hand-to-mouth,'' she said. ``There are a
lot of cheap coffees all over the place.''
   Ms. Eskenasy said Mexico recently dropped the price for its
old-crop coffee, which is of lower quality than newly harvested
beans, to 60 cents a pound and several other producers were selling
old-crop coffee at 65 cents a pound.
   Hog futures rose sharply on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange in
response to higher-than-expected cash prices and strengthening
chart signals. Cattle futures rebounded from Monday's steep losses.
   Live cattle settled .08 cent to .35 cent higher with October at
71.35 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent lower to .35 cent
higher with October at 82.75 cents a pound; live hogs were .05 cent
lower to .93 cent higher with October at 45.10 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .05 cent to .50 cent lower with February
at 48.50 cents a pound.
   Gold and silver futures slipped lower on New York's Commodity
Exchange as the dollar strengthened on currency markets.
   Gold settled 70 cents to 80 cents lower with October at $366.90
a troy ounce; silver was 0.2 cent to 0.3 cent lower with December
at $5.295 a troy ounce.
   Most energy futures advanced modestly on the New York Mercantile
Exchange ahead of the American Petroleum Institute's weekly report,
which showed a slight decline in refining activity, a
1.7-million-barrel increase in U.S. crude oil stocks, a
4.5-million-barrel rise in U.S. gasoline stocks and a
112,000-barrel increase in U.S. stocks of petroleum distillates.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 5 cents to 18 cents
higher with November at $20.13 a barrel; heating oil was .10 cent
to .46 cent higher with November at 59.68 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .16 cent lower to .67 cent higher with November at
56.64 cents a gallon.
   Wheat futures advanced while other grain and soybean futures
closed narrowly mixed Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat settled 1\ cents to 3\ cents higher with December at
$4.09} a bushel; corn futures were unchanged to 1 cent lower with
December at $2.40{ a bushel; oats were unchanged to 1 cent higher
with December at $1.47} a bushel; soybeans were 1} cents lower to
1} cents higher with November at $5.76\ a bushel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
