<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0667</SECOND>
<HEAD>DJIA Hits New High As Wall Street Surgers Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS Amex index close in 22nd graf; UPDATES 16th graf to
include machinists' rejection of contract; UPDATES with closing prices
throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wall Street surged to a new high Tuesday as
investors, optimistic about the prospects for interest rates,
scooped up blue chip and consumer issues.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials achieved a new closing
high, rising 40.84 to end the session at 2,754.56. That topped the
widely-followed barometer's previous high close of 2,752.09,
reached on Sept. 1.
   Broader market indicators also scored new highs.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declining ones by a margin of about
2 to 1 in nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed
stocks, with 996 stocks up, 509 down and 486 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to a heavy 182.55
million shares, up from 127.41 million in the previous session.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 221.51 million shares.
   Analysts said Wall Street was awash with optimism about interest
rates as prices rose and yields slumped in the credit markets. The
Treasury's bellwether 30-year bond was up more than $5 in late
afternoon trading, while its yield slumped to 8.16 percent from
late Monday's 8.21 percent.
   Analysts said hopes seemed to be increasing that the Federal
Reserve might relax its credit policy further, given a relatively
slow pace of economic growth and no recent sign of increasing
inflationary pressures.
   The Fed's policy-making body, the Federal Open Market Committee,
was meeting Tuesday, but the central bank followed its usual
procedure and did not announce any decisions.
   Strength in the dollar, which withstood central bank
intervention, also bolstered prices on Wall Street Tuesday.
   Ralph J. Acampora, a market analyst with Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co.,
said traders were upbeat to the point that they ignored some of the
financial markets' recent worries, such as weakness in junk bonds.
   ``This market's turning a cold shoulder to what could be
concerning news for investors,'' he said.
   Analysts reported some program trading, but the broad advance
``despite the negatives is telling us that there's a lot of
interest out there,'' Acampora said.
   The market extended the gains it chalked up late in Monday's
session, when the Dow Jones industrial average picked up 21 points.
   The most actively traded issue on the NYSE Tuesday was USX,
which jumped 1] to 36\ amid speculation that financier Carl Icahn
was adding to his 11.4 percent stake in the company.
   Boeing was up 3[ to 59} as the company's unionized machinists
voted on whether to accept a new three-year contract or strike at
midnight. After the market closed, it was announced that the
machinists had turned down their tentative agreement with Boeing.
   Besides the blue chips, the biggest winners were consumer
stocks, which boast predictable growth. American Express gained 2\
to 38\ and Philip Morris soared 5] to 172.
   But those gains came at the expense of technology issues.
   IBM skidded 2| to 106. Analysts said the computer maker was
suffering the fallout from last week's announcement that its
third-quarter earnings would be below expectations.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market gained $32.764 billion, or 0.95
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
reached a new closing high, rising 1.94 to 196.84.
   New ground was also broken at the American Stock Exchange, where
the market value index closed at 393.02, up 3.36.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index moved up 4.42 to 404.44, and
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index gained 3.84 to close at 354.71.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market rose
2.09 to 477.28.
</TEXT>
