<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     10-03 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Rise Amid Panama Unrest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices rose Tuesday, supported by
concern about the unrest in Panama.
   The November contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude oil, gained 12 cents to close at $20.13 per
42-gallon barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   Analysts said prices were buoyed by the turmoil in Panama, where
soldiers opposed to Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega seized his
headquarters in an attempt to oust him but loyalists
counterattacked. Oil investors worried that the conflict could
disrupt the movement of oil tankers through the Panama Canal,
although they recognized that event still appears unlikely.
   ``What we did not see was tremendous panic, (but) it lent a
steady tone to the market,'' said Jerry Samuels, a vice president
at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., referring to the impact of the
Panama situation.
   Home heating oil futures traded on the mercantile exchange also
rose. The November contract for heating oil edged up 0.10 cent a
gallon to close at 59.68 cents and subsequent months posted larger
gains.
   The November contract for unleaded gasoline slipped 0.16 cent a
gallon to 56.64 cents. Subsequent months advanced, however, with
the December contract gaining 0.38 cent to 55.08 cents.
   Samuels said refined product prices drew further strength from
reports that Amerada Hess Corp., which owns a big refinery in St.
Croix, Virgin Islands, was experiencing delays in getting the
facility back to normal operations in the wake of damage by
Hurricane Hugo.
</TEXT>
