<FILEID>AP-NR-10-03-89 2122EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-OilTaxes     10-03 0619</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Taxes,0637</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bentsen Seeks Oil, Gas Tax For Wetlands Fund</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairmen of the Senate Finance and Energy
committees have included a new tax on off-shore oil and gas
production in pending legislation and want to use the millions of
dollars in expected revenues to protect and restore coastal
wetlands.
   Spokesmen for the oil and gas industry say, however, that
drilling on the outer-continental shelf has done little to harm the
Gulf Coast's troubled wetlands. They said their industry is opposed
to being solely responsible for financing the proposed Coastal
Wetlands Trust Fund under the provision backed by the chairmen,
Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, and Bennett Johnston, D-La.
   ``Since most of the causes of wetlands losses were unintended
consequences of activities that provided public benefits, an
equitable solution would be to fund wetlands conservation programs
out of general revenues. It is unfair to tax a single industry to
address a broad land-use problem,'' Joseph Lastelic, a spokesman
for the American Petroleum Institute, said Tuesday.
   Environmentalists, however, say off-shore drilling has damaged
coastal wetlands in Louisiana and Texas, and although
outer-continental shelf drilling may not directly cause wetlands
erosion, setting up and operating support facilities on the
mainland have contributed to losses of coastal marshes.
   Under the plan drafted by Bentsen and Johnston, D-La.,
production from federal offshore waters would be taxed at 2 cents
per 1,000 cubic feet of natural gas and 3 cents per barrel of oil.
   Industry estimates say the plan would raise about $100 million
annually, while the senators say revenues would be closer to $383
million over five years.
   The plan is included in Bentsen's version of what is known as
budget reconciliation legislation pending before the Finance
Committee, of which Bentsen is chairman. There have been no
hearings on the plan.
   Johnston said late Monday that getting the tax included in the
reconciliation bill was ``the difficult part'' of moving the plan
through the Senate.
   The bill is the chief legislative vehicle for enacting spending
cuts to meet budget targets.
   According to a fact sheet from Johnston's office, wetlands loss
on the Gulf Coast is critical, especially in Louisiana. Johnston's
office also said oil and gas activity is one cause of erosion in
coastal wetlands, which provide habitat for migratory birds, fish
and other ildlife, as well as commercial and recreational benefits.
   ``Navigation, access and pipeline canals and other activities
related to the exploration, development and production of oil and
gas along the Gulf Coast and on the outer continental shelf have
had adverse effects on many of the coastal wetlands of the Gulf
Coast region,'' Johnston's office said.
   ``Oil and gas production in the coastal areas have contributed
(to wetlands losses). I wouldn't say it's the No. 1 factor, but
they have contributed their part,'' said Bill Reffalt, refuge
program director for the Wilderness Society.
   Mike Baly, executive vice president of the American Gas
Association, said natural gas is ``probably less than 10 percent of
the problem.''
   Baly said the natural gas industry would pay the greatest share
of the tax _ accounting for 91 percent of what the association
projects will be $98 million in annual revenues.
   ``At a time when 50 percent of our oil comes from foreign
countries and concern about reducing our deficit from oil imports,
it's difficult for us to understand why they're lessening the
competitive factor for natural gas by applying a federal tax,''
Baly said.
   Scott Feierabend, director of the fisheries and wildlife
division at the National Wildlife Federation, said he would support
the Bentsen-Johnston approach.
   Bentsen said Monday his plan would ``be a great thing for the
coastal waters, Louisiana, Texas and the United States.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
