<FIRST>r f AM-CrazyEddie     10-03 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crazy Eddie,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crazy Eddie Says It Will Liquidate Remaining Assets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNION, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crazy Eddie Inc., the discount electronics
chain known for its high-pitched commercials, turned down the
volume for good Tuesday, announcing it would liquidate its last 18
stores.
   The company, which had been seeking to reorganize under Chapter
11 of the bankruptcy laws, said it would liquidate because vendors
were no longer willing to extend credit, among other factors.
   Without the credit, it could not keep operating, the company
said. Because liabilities greatly exceeded assets, stockholders
would receive nothing, it said. Trading had been suspended when the
share price fell below 25 cents.
   Managers were told of the planned closings during a morning
meeting at the company's headquarters in Edison, said Humphrey
Stokes, manager of the Crazy Eddie store here.
   ``It was kind of like a load being lifted off your shoulders,''
he said.
   The announcement ends a turbulent 20-year history for the
company founded by high-school dropout Eddie Antar with a lone
store in Brooklyn, N.Y. At its peak, Crazy Eddie had 43 stores in
New York, New Jersey, Connecticut and Pennsylvania.
   They employed 1,500 people and once brought in sales of $300
million. The company's stock reached $21 a share. The tag line
``Our prices are insane,'' screamed so often on television and
radio spots by former disc jockey-actor Jerry Carroll, made the
chain known to millions.
   But a rift among Antar family members who served as executives,
declining demand for electronics, tougher competition and seeming
disorganization brought on severe financial woes.
   Antar, who brought the company public in 1984, later sold much
of his stock, and resigned as president but stayed on as chairman.
He dropped from sight and never granted interviews.
   Dissident shareholders, led by turnaround specialist Victor
Palmieri and Houston electronics retailer Elias Zinn, took control
of the company in November 1987 and found a huge inventory
shortfall.
   Nearly three months after Crazy Eddie sought bankruptcy
protection in June, the Securities and Exchange Commission accused
Antar and top management with insider trading and systematically
doctoring financial figures to inflate earnings.
   The scheme allegedly involved exaggerating inventory and falsely
reducing bills to suppliers.
   Meanwhile, at the store here, the floor contained compact disc
players and other stereo equipment in their boxes and pyramids of
Mr. Coffee machines. Stokes said he wanted to show customers that
the store had goods to sell, but conceded that the stock room was
far from brimming over.
   ``This is my job, my livelihood,'' said Stokes. ``But you've got
to make the best of it,'' he said, confident he could find work in
the computer industry. Stokes vowed to go out of business in the
``Crazy Eddie tradition'' _ ``blow-out blitzes.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891003-0266 </DOCNO>
