<FIRST>r f BC-DeereStrike     10-03 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Deere Strike,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Seeks Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HORICON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The striking machinists union offered
Tuesday to resume talks with John Deere &amp; Co. on a new contract.
   ``The union is ready to meet, at their convenience,'' said
Dwayne Scott, a spokesman for International Association of
Machinists and Aerospace Workers Local 873.
   There was no immediate response from Deere, a manufactuer of
farm equipment.
   The union, which represents 940 workers at Deere's Horicon plant
and another 225 on layoffs, walked out Sunday after their old
contract expired.
   The union's negotiating committee had recommended acceptance of
the company's contract offer, but the tentative pact was voted down
by the rank and file on Saturday, Scott said.
   Scott said a key issue was job security, although some members
said they also wanted pay parity with other John Deere plants.
   The average pay for union workers is $15 an hour, Scott said.
   Deere, based in Moline, Ill., manufactures farm tractors and has
other plants in Illinois, Iowa, Minnesota, Colorado and Georgia.
   The Horicon plant is the only one whose workers are not
represented by the United Auto Workers.
</TEXT>
