<SECOND>BC-Paris Real Estate,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>$600 Million Sale Believed Biggest French Commercial Real Estate
Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kaufman &amp; Broad Home Corp. said Tuesday it
sold an office building complex in Paris for about $600 million,
which it said was the biggest commercial real estate deal in French
history.
   The complex, to be called Washington Plaza, is located on 2.2
acres near the Champs Elysee, a site where the Shell Oil Co.
currently has its French headquarters.
   The buyers were an international group of investors headed by
Kowa Real estate, a unit of Industrial Bank of Japan, Kaufman &amp;
Broad said in a statement.
   Kaufman &amp; Broad, a big U.S. home builder, sells its commercial
real estate projects in France before developing them.
   Kaufman &amp; Broad said it will renovate two facades in the
existing Paris structure to retain the building's historical
significance, and build five buildings totaling 560,000 square feet
and five levels of underground parking.
   Construction is to begin in December 1990, when Shell moves out
of the existing building, and should be completed by spring 1993,
Kaufman &amp; Broad said.
