<FIRST>r f AM-Merck-Britcair     10-03 0139</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Merck-Britcair,0145</SECOND>
<HEAD>Merck To Purchase British Company That Makes Seaweed Wound Dressings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RAHWAY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Merck &amp; Co. Inc. announced Tuesday an
agreement to acquire the shares of Britcair Ltd., a 4-year-old
British company that has developed a wound dressing from seaweed.
   Merck did not disclose terms of the agreement, but said it would
augment its manufacture of wound dressing products that use kelp.
   A Merck news release said BritCair's seaweed wound dressings are
superior to cotton gauze dressings for use on wounds such as dermal
ulcers and also wounds caused by skin grafts.
   BritCair, with headquarters in Aldershot, England, uses a new
technology for the production of a gelatinous fiber. Dressings
produced from this fiber interact with wound fluids to form a gel
over the wound and help it heal better, according to the Merck
release.
</TEXT>
