<FIRST>u f AM-Digital-Resignation     10-03 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Digital-Resignation,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Digital Senior Executive Resigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAYNARD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Digital Equipment Corp. on Tuesday
announced the resignation of senior vice president John J. Shields,
described as the No. 2 man at one of the world's largest computer
companies.
   Shields, 51, made a personal decision to leave the company to
pursue other interests, a statement from Digital said.
   ``Jack was instrumental in creating the 70,000-person
international sales and services organization that helped make
Digital the world's second largest computer company,'' said Digital
President Kenneth Olsen.
   Olsen said Shields ``played a key role in formulating the
company's sales, services, and marketing strategy.''
   The company's release contained no statement from Shields, who
was unavailable for comment at Digital, and his home address was
not available.
   Digital's stock fell $2.25 a share to $88.75 Tuesday on the New
York Stock Exchange.
   Sonny Monosson, who publishes a newsletter covering Digital's
activities, said that for many years, Shields was being groomed as
a successor to Olsen.
   But recently, he said, Shields became less visible at the
company.
   ``It was pretty obvious something was up,'' Monosson said. He
publishes The Monosson Report in Boston.
   Monosson said Shields apparently believed he could not attain
the No. 1 spot and so decided to leave.
   ``There were some indications that Shields' responsibilities had
been off-loaded to other individuals in the Digital hierarchy,''
said Paul Zorfass, director of research at the Yankee Group in
Boston.
   Nikki Richardson, a Digital spokeswoman, said Shields' decision
was made for personal reasons and any other comments were
speculation.
   Shields joined the company in 1961 as a field service engineer
and in 1964 was named manager of field service. In 1974, he was
promoted to vice president of field service and training.
   He continued to expand his duties and in 1986 was named senior
vice president in sales, services, marketing and international
business.
</TEXT>
