<FIRST>r f BC-InfinitiAds     10-03 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Infiniti Ads,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nissan's Infiniti Ads Finally Show the Car</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nissan Motor Corp. on Tuesday unveiled
new ads for its Infiniti luxury car line that finally gives a
glimpse _ if a fuzzy one _ of a nameplate previously wrapped in
advertising mystery.
   The new ads are to begin appearing later this month as part of a
$60 million print and television campaign by the Japansese
automaker that so far has lacked direct reference to either of the
two Infiniti models.
   The new television commercials continue the style of pastoral
scenery but now include a blurry car whizzing past at the close.
   The changes in the ad campaign begin Oct. 16 nationally and Oct.
23 in the 30 markets where there are Infiniti dealers, Infiniti
Division General Manager William Bruce said.
   He said more commercials will air Nov. 5 but declined to say
whether the Infiniti Q45 or M30 cars would appear in them. The cars
go on sale Nov. 8.
   The Infiniti cars are the second Japanese luxury car line to be
introduced this year in the United States. Toyota Motor Corp. began
selling its Lexus line last month. Lexus officials have said they
anticipate selling around 70,000 vehicles in 1990.
   Nissan, which changed its name from Datsun earlier this decade,
is attempting to make the name Infiniti familiar to potential
buyers before the car itself, using brand rather than product
advertising.
   ``I find them a breath of fresh air and rather intriguing,''
said automotive analyst Scott Merlis of Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. ``I
hear everybody talking about it. I suppose you have to give them
credit in breaking new ground in automotive advertising.''
   But analyst Charles Brady of Oppenheimer &amp; Co. said, ``My
personal belief is that to sell a car, you should show a car.''
   The new ads were shown at what Nissan called the national media
introduction of the Infiniti cars, which will sell for $23,500 and
$38,000. The cars also were shown on the auto-show circuit earlier
this year. Bruce declined to say how many cars the division
expected to sell.
   The line's print ads to date have shown such nature-oriented
scenes as an outcropping of rocks, crashing waves or a field of hay
along with often-philosophical text that does not prominently
mention the name of the car.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
