<FIRST>r f BC-FarmersGroup     10-03 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Farmers Group,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big Insurer to Reorganize</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers Insurance Group Inc. said Tuesday it
would consolidate its property-casualty operations as part of a
major management reorganization.
   Farmers Chairman Leo E. Denlea Jr. also said the company would
conduct a multimillion-dollar study to examine how to make its
computerized business systems more efficient.
   H.J. Browning, a vice president of field operations, was
promoted to senior vice president and chief information officer to
oversee the study, reporting to Denlea.
   Leading the host of new jobs and reassignments, Denlea said he
had appointed William H. Braddock to a new No. 2 post as executive
vice president of the Los Angeles-based insurer. The move will
allow Denlea to concentrate more on life insurance and the
reorganization of business systems, officials said.
   Denlea said he also would nominate Braddock, formerly the vice
president of marketing, to the board of directors.
   Farmers spokesman Jeffrey Beyer said the restructuring was part
of a process that Denlea launched two years ago and was unrelated
to the uncertainties surrounding a hostile takeover bid for
Farmers' parent, the British BAT Industries PLC conglomerate.
   Farmers, the 15th-biggest U.S. insurer, was acquired last year
by London-based BAT, which is now trying to fight off a $22 billion
takeover bid by Hoylake Investments, a consortium put together by
investor Sir James Goldsmith.
   If Goldsmith succeeds in the takeover, he has agreed to sell
Farmers to a French insurer, Axa-Midi Assurances, for $4.5 billion.
   Farmers expanded into its 27th state last year, Tennessee, and
Beyer said the company is considering moving into Alabama and
Georgia as well as plotting how to strengthen its operations in
such Midwest states as Minnesota and Wisconsin.
   Reporting to Braddock under the reorganization will be the field
operations vice presidents for Farmers' California, Midwest and
Western zones, and the vice presidents of claims, marketing and
commercial insurance underwriting.
   Also reporting to him will be a new vice president for the
property-casualty staff, who will supervise officers in charge of
the actuarial, underwriting and administrative services functions,
the company said.
</TEXT>
