<FIRST>r f BC-Tyson-Soviets     10-03 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Tyson-Soviets,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poultry Firm Says Contract Signed To Supply Soviet Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGDALE, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poultry giant Tyson Foods Inc. of
Springdale said Tuesday it had signed a contract to provide chicken
parts to the Soviet Union.
   Tyson spokesman Jim Blair said the contract was signed with
another U.S. food company, which he declined to name, that has
agreed to supply the Soviet Union with chicken. Blair also declined
to disclose volume or price figures, saying non-disclosure of that
information was part of the contract.
   ``The Russians have committed themselves to a major purchasing
program of consumer items, including food, and this is simply part
of the program,'' said Blair, Tyson's general counsel.
   He declined to say when the contract was signed, but said it was
announced to Tyson management Monday.
   According to Blair, the contract calls for a substantial amount
of frozen chicken hindquarters _ thighs and legs _ to be shipped in
containers to U.S. ports, where the containers would be transferred
to cargo ships for transport to the Soviet Union.
   Shipments are to begin ``almost immediately,'' he said.
   The effect on the U.S. chicken market will be very limited, he
said.
   ``It won't do anything to the American market except add
stability, as any big contract does over a period of time,'' Tyson
said. ``In fact, there won't be any disruption in the supply to our
normal customers.''
   Blair said the contract is with a company with which Tyson
normally competes in the United States. He would not say whether
the company was either Conagra Inc. of Omaha, Neb., or Perdue Farms
Inc. of Salisbury, Md.
   The multicompany arrangement, he said, arose because ``I don't
think any single company would have the capacity to fulfill the
contract'' without disruption of its normal operations.
   He said that, as far as he knew, the arrangements with the
Soviet Union involve no export subsidy by the U.S. government. The
sale by Tyson, Blair said, was at U.S. market prices, as was the
sale to the Soviet Union by the company with which Tyson has
contracted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
